<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rudd's Ride Back in Sync </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Critics say the business side of  
stock car racing is sapping all the fun out of the sport. Anyone 
who agrees probably can't help but pull for Ricky Rudd in the Pepsi 
400 on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Considered a dinosaur in NASCAR circles because he owns a  
one-car team in an era of multicar conglomerates, Rudd suffered a 
difficult blow to his business this week. His sponsor for most of 
the decade, Procter &AMP; Gamble, decided to pull its Tide label off 
the 24-year Winston Cup veteran's car at year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	He responded with one of his best qualifying laps of the year,  
making the front row outside of Joe Nemechek. And for that effort, 
every racing fan who has ever started his own company -- or simply 
bought a box of Tide, for that matter -- has a reason to cheer for 
Rudd this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is really the first time I've ever experienced anything  
like this,'' Rudd said. ``I guess racing is growing and it's 
changing and, hopefully, it's all for the better. But I think, 
unfortunately, a lot of the guys who paid their dues and helped 
create the sport are tending to get run over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rudd's detractors will be quick to point out that he has created  
many of his own problems. When he split with Rick Hendrick and 
created his own team in 1994, Rudd kept the sponsorship deal with 
Tide going. And even five years ago, he must have been able to see 
that one-car owners were quickly becoming outnumbered in the 
garage, on the test track and, most importantly, on the earnings 
ledger. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there's no denying Rudd has reason for hard feelings.  
</P>
<P>
	Proctor &AMP; Gamble is likely to move its sponsorship to Precision  
Preparation Inc., a company best known for its CART team, one that 
won't put a car on a NASCAR track until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Whoever drives that car will take the logo that belonged to  
Rudd, who has one of the most impressive records in the sport. He 
has won at least one race for 16 seasons straight, from 1983-98. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Rudd is mired in 38th place in the points standings  
without a top-10 finish. He says sales and promotion had been the 
last thing on his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm probably guilty of working way too many hours and worrying  
way too much about this race team, instead of going up with a fancy 
briefcase and a nice powerpoint presentation,'' Rudd said. 
</P>
<P>
	PPI owner Cal Wells said he didn't mean to stir up bad feelings  
with Rudd, who has been very critical of Wells, or with other 
NASCAR drivers who might feel like he is barging in on their turf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry Ricky feels the way he does,'' Wells said. ``We're  
not here to kick him or anyone else off. We're here to build a 
strong foundation in this sport and in this industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside Rudd in Saturday's race will be Nemechek, another underdog  
who nonetheless has the manpower of Felix Sabates' Sabco racing 
team at his disposal. 
</P>
<P>
	A few rows back are Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon and Dale  
Jarrett, who, in different ways, symbolize where the sport has gone 
over the last decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to do a lot outside of what you do on the racetrack  
to keep everyone happy and sometimes even that isn't enough,'' 
Jarrett said. ``Everybody wants to be on the side of a winning car 
and as we know, that's not really possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Rudd is clearly out of the Winston Cup points chase,  
Jarrett, Gordon and Earnhardt are in the thick of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, who will start 12th, holds the lead by 157 points over  
Bobby Labonte heading into the second half of the season. Gordon 
has four victories, more than anyone in the field, but stands 314 
points behind Jarrett in the quest for a third straight title. 
Gordon will start 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt is in seventh place. He ran second at Daytona in  
February and earned his lone victory this year at Talladega, 
proving his restrictor-plate program has as much potential as 
anybody's. 
</P>
<P>
	But a disappointing qualifying effort stuck him at 10th on the  
starting grid, and left his car in need of work before the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little rougher ride, a little tougher to drive it than  
it was here in February,'' Earnhardt said. ``We should have tuned 
on the bumpers or the rubbers or the springs or something a little 
more. It sure wasn't a good ride.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
