<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's main stock exchange climbed to a 20-month  
high Friday as foreign investors continued to spearhead a two-day 
rally. The dollar edged higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 71.72 points,  
or 0.40 percent, closing the week at 17,932.47 points. It was the 
index's highest closing since Sept. 29, 1997, when it finished at 
17,987.21. On Thursday, the average closed up 331.01 points, or 
1.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.08 yen by late afternoon, up 0.32 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
120.78 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by continued brisk buying from overseas institutional  
investors, the Nikkei average briefly passed the 18,000 point mark 
for the first time since September 1997, rising as high as 
18,066.28 in the morning before falling back on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	An overnight rise on the New York Stock Exchange and hope for an  
economic recovery in Japan combined to boost Tokyo share prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence in our country's economy is being reflected in  
stocks, and I am happy about it,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu 
Nonaka told a regular news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was fairly heavy, with about 705 million shares changing  
hands on the exchange's first section, up from Thursday's 626 
million. Advancers outnumbered retreaters 665 to 531, with 133 
issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists expect the confidence index for major manufacturers  
in the quarterly ``tankan'' survey by Japan's central bank of 
business sentiment, due out Monday, to show an improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average should test the 18,000 mark again next week,  
providing the tankan reflects the expected improvement, said 
Masaaki Higashida, deputy general manager at Nomura Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section rose 12.75 points, or 0.88 percent, to 
1,460.16. The TOPIX posted a 31.21-point gain, or 2.20 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar stayed in a narrow range as  
investors held back ahead of Monday's release of the tankan survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the market has already factored in an improvement  
in the tankan's main numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dollar is at this level after factoring in the tankan,''  
said Hideaki Inoue, foreign exchange manager at Mitsubishi Trust 
and Banking. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged from 120.73 yen to 121.14 yen in Friday's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.86 yen, down  
from 125.04 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond fell to  
1.6850 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7400 percent, driving 
its price up to 100.99 yen from 100.51 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
