<DOCNO> APW19990702.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 08:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade in advance of the long 
holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters have offered different views about the severity of  
hot, dry weather over the next few days in Midwestern growing 
regions, although many predict a return to normal temperatures by 
midweek. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops in Illinois and Iowa face the biggest threat of heat  
stress, which could reduce yields. The young plants are entering 
the pollination stage in which kernels form. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices also were supported by a flurry of new export  
business that came as foreign buyers rushed to take advantage of 
sharply lower prices on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for September delivery rose 1/4 cent to  
$2.59 a bushel; December corn rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.19 1/2 a bushel; 
December oats were unchanged at $1.15 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans 
rose 1 1/4 cents to $4.54 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures edged higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .45 cent to 62.82 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .42 cent to 76.40 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .40 cent to 45 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
.55 cent to 36.90 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
