<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 07:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Rally Across Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets pushed ahead Friday, with  
blue chips in Tokyo and Hong Kong hitting levels unseen since the 
early months of the region's economic crisis and Singapore shares 
climbing to another record finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets were filled with optimism that any interest rate worries  
are out of the way for now, after the U.S. Federal Reserve nudged 
its rates higher on Wednesday but suggested no more monetary 
tightening is likely to be necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index rose 652.44 points, or 4.8 percent,  
to close at 14,184.58, its highest point gain of the year and the 
best finish since Oct. 9, 1997, when the Asian financial crisis was 
starting to be felt in the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. is now less inclined to raise rates, which is helping  
Hong Kong stocks,'' said Patrick Yiu, an analyst at Kingsway SW 
Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's session was Hong Kong's first chance to respond to the  
U.S. interest rate news, after a public holiday on Thursday, so the 
gains were somewhat exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian markets gained further encouragement from Wall Street,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 95.62 points to 
11,066.42 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, Asia's biggest market, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei  
Stock Average rose 71.72 points, or 0.40 percent, closing at 
17,932.47 points. It was the index's highest closing since Sept. 
29, 1997, when it finished at 17,987.21. On Thursday, the Nikkei 
had closed up 331.01 points, or 1.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by continued brisk buying from overseas institutional  
investors, the Nikkei average briefly passed the 18,000-point, 
rising as high as 18,066.28 before falling back on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence in our country's economy is being reflected in  
stocks, and I am happy about it,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu 
Nonaka told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 121.08 yen by  
late afternoon, up 0.32 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 120.78 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore shares inched up to their second record in as many  
days, pushed higher by small investors buying up small-company 
shares. The benchmark Straits Times Index closed at 2,222.45 
points, up 7.70 points, or 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only very selective buying on the blue chips. The  
small stocks are the ones dominating today,'' said broker William 
Pang at G.K. Goh Stockbrokers said. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai blue chips rose 2.2 percent, after giving up about  
half of their early huge gains. The SET index rose 11.56 points to 
533.33. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares bucked the trend and fell, as renewed  
clashes between police and demonstrators kept nervous investors out 
of the market. The JSX Composite Index dropped 2.504 points, or 
0.37 percent, to 670.538. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed sharply higher on strong buying in  
technology stocks. The Weighted Stock Price Index rose 104.72 
points, or 1.2 percent, to 8,572.09. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices showed a modest rally. The  
NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 14.82 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
2,141.92. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher as interest rate worries  
vanished. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 35.42 
points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,578.72. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed higher, with stronger  
prices for commodities giving a lift to resource-based companies. 
The All Ordinaries Index rose 26.8 points, or 0.9 percent, to 
3,028.9. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Sentiment was boosted by the U.S. interest rate news and  
expectations of a speedup in reforms by leading conglomerates. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 13.44 points, or 1.4 
percent, to 933.42. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Prices were buoyed by regional and Wall Street  
gains as well as enthusiasm about local economic prospects. The 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, closed at 
845.62, up 10.31 points, or 1.23 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
