<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Second Quake Felt in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SATSOP, Wash. (AP) -- The second sharp earthquake in two days  
jolted an area from Oregon to British Columbia Friday night, 
toppling chimneys and rupturing gas and water mains. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake, which hit at 6:43 p.m., was estimated at magnitude  
5.5 by the U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo. The Pacific 
Northwest Sesimograph Network at the University of Washington 
seismology lab in Seattle estimated it at 5.1. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Steele, UW seismology lab coordinator, said the Colorado  
lab was looking at one facet of the quake and the UW lab was 
looking at the duration of shaking. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake was centered near Satsop, about 68 miles southwest of  
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stuff was flying off the shelves,'' said Trudy Donnor, who was  
getting ready to start cleaning the four-story state Insurance 
Building in Olympia when the quake hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the first one I've ever felt in my life, and I didn't  
think it was funny at all. I didn't know a concrete building could 
sway like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The roof of a furniture store collapsed in Aberdeen, about 20  
miles west of the epicenter. A hospital reported four people with 
quake-related injuries that were not serious. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas leaks, toppled chimneys and power outages were reported  
throughout the area of Grays Harbor County, said Rob Harper of 
Washington State Emergency Management. 
</P>
<P>
	A quake Thursday night jolted the south Puget Sound area and had  
a 3.0 magnitude. It was centered near Maury Island north of Tacoma. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, a magnitude 5.7 quake rumbled under the Pacific  
Ocean off Vancouver Island, about 115 miles southwest of Port 
Hardy, British Columbia. The quake early Friday was not felt 
because of its distance from land. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 02:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plumber Loses Fight for Mansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) -- In a story with shades of a Dickens novel,  
a young plumber who allegedly found his way into the heart of a 
77-year-old widow has lost his bid to evict her son from the family 
mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	The literary parallel is not a stretch. Take it from Superior  
Court Judge Frank Williams, who evicted Kevin Tinney from Belcourt 
Castle on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the `Posthumous Papers of the Pickwick Club' by Charles  
Dickens ... there is a place called Dingley Dell,'' said the judge. 
``The inhabitants ... represent all of humankind: good and evil, 
sophisticated and ignorant, beneficent, and avaricious. 
</P>
<P>
	``Belcourt is today's Dingley Dell.''  
</P>
<P>
	Williams invalidated a deed that gave Tinney partial ownership  
of the building and ordered him to be out of the 60-room mansion by 
July 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Tinney, the adopted son of the mansion's deceased owner Ruth  
Tinney, had accused fellow co-owners Donald Tinney and his wife, 
Harle, of running the mansion into the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	He sued to have the $3.2 million mansion sold and the proceeds  
divided among the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Tinney, Ruth Tinney's son, and his wife countered that  
Kevin Tinney used undue influence to get his name onto the deed and 
sought to have it invalidated. 
</P>
<P>
	The 60-room, French-chateau style mansion was purchased by the  
Tinney family in 1956 for $25,000. The family rented it out for 
weddings and other functions. Today, visitors can tour the mansion 
for $8. 
</P>
<P>
	In the winter of 1974, Kevin Tinney -- then named Kevin Koellisch  
-- charged the Tinneys $600 to fix the heat, when other plumbers 
wanted $10,000 up front. The Tinneys were so grateful they began 
inviting him to dinner almost every night. 
</P>
<P>
	Before long, Kevin Tinney's home became the castle.  
</P>
<P>
	His detractors testified that Kevin Tinney, who was in his 30s,  
began paying special attention to the 77-year-old family matriarch 
after her husband, Harold, died in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The two appeared very affectionate in public and Ruth Tinney  
once said ``Kevin wants to marry me,'' Harle Tinney testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Tinney, who said he is gay, denied that he proposed to  
Ruth, and said his kisses were like those of any son. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Tinney adopted Kevin Koellisch in 1990 and he changed his  
last name. Although his natural mother was living at the time, 
Tinney said their relationship had been strained for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Tinney said recently that Ruth Tinney wanted him to  
inherit part of Belcourt and adopted him to reduce his inheritance 
taxes. Six months after the adoption, Ruth Tinney deeded part of 
Belcourt to Kevin Tinney. 
</P>
<P>
	After that happened, witnesses testified, he began to pay less  
attention to Ruth Tinney. One testified that, late in life, she 
said she regretted adopting him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Tinney died in 1995 at 89. Within two years, the family  
feud erupted. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Tinney accused Harle Tinney of pilfering money from  
catering events and parties held at the mansion. She accused him of 
embezzlement. 
</P>
<P>
	At trial, Kevin Tinney, who has lived in the mansion with his  
companion for the last 15 years, claimed he wanted a chance to buy 
a sole interest in the place and fix it up. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald and Harle Tinney offered him $500,000 to drop the case,  
but he refused, asking for more than $1 million, the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony in the case ended in April, but the judge had hoped  
the two sides could reach an agreement before issuing his ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight is not over. When they pass each other in the mansion,  
cold quick glares go back and forth. More significantly, Kevin 
Tinney said Thursday that his lawyer will appeal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
