<HEADLINE> Amtrak Engineer Ignored Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- An Amtrak engineer ignored a  
dispatcher's warning and ran a red light before his southbound 
train slammed into one going north, injuring eight people, a 
federal investigator said today. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was seriously hurt in the crash in downtown Jacksonville  
early Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The southbound train was moving at 55 mph and narrowly missed  
hitting the other train either head-on or engine-to-engine. 
</P>
<P>
	The southbound engineer barreled through the red light, which  
could be seen from two miles away, and then was warned by a 
dispatcher to stop, said Russ Gober of the National Transportation 
Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The two engines of the northbound train, which was moving at 14  
mph, were just moving off onto a side track when the southbound hit 
them, knocking the trains' engines on their sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Gober said the engineer radioed: ``I made a bad mistake. I used  
bad judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trains, both called the Silver Palm, were carrying a  
combined 300 passengers between Miami and New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	Four locomotives and seven cars derailed, said Jane Covington, a  
spokeswoman for CSX Transportation, which owns the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers said the accident jolted them out of their seats.  
Eight people were treated for minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was asleep and then I heard my wife. I jumped up and held up  
the top bunk where my kids were sleeping,'' said Modesto Romero of 
Newark, N.J. ``They were a little scared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The railroad's main line was expected to be open today.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
