<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biffle Wins Pole For Diehard 200 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- Greg Biffle, a winner twice in the last  
seven NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series events, will start his Ford 
from the pole Saturday in the DieHard 200 at The Milwaukee Mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Biffle's record speed of 121.102 mph Friday locked up the  
sophomore driver's third pole of the year. His lap was 
four-thousandths of a second quicker than that of Randy Tolsma, who 
went 121.086 in a Dodge. 
</P>
<P>
	Both drivers broke Jack Sprague's year-old qualifying record of  
120.530. Sprague, who qualified his Chevrolet third, also was under 
the previous standard. He went 121.049. Stacy Compton's Dodge was 
next at 120.826, followed by the Chevy of Jay Sauter at 120.518. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixth through 10th in were Joe Ruttman, Scott Hansen, Rick  
Crawford, Dennis Setzer and Ron Hornaday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Hansen, however, was involved in an accident with Jeff  
Andretti in the post-qualifying practice session. His team rolled 
out a backup Chevy, which will require Hansen to drop to the tail 
end of the 34-truck field for the start of the 200-mile race. 
Andretti's crew will attempt to repair its only Chevrolet. 
</P>
<P>
	Biffle, who's bidding to complete a single-season sweep of  
victories on short tracks, road courses and superspeedways, has 
finished in the top-10 in seven of his past eight starts. 
</P>
<P>
	He won at Memphis Motorsports Park in May and at Portland  
International Raceway in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team is clicking right. Everybody is doing a good job,''  
said Biffle, fifth in the points race. ``The driver is getting more 
familiar with the truck ... we're just getting things figured 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biffle will have to beat three former winners -- Sprague,  
Hornaday and Mike Bliss -- who qualified 14th. Also in the field is 
Mike Wallace, a former NASCAR Busch Series winner at The Milwaukee 
Mile, who has two truck series victories this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
