<HEADLINE> F-16 Pilot Dies in Fla. Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKEECHOBEE, Fla. (AP) -- The pilot of an Air Force F-16 Falcon  
was killed when he crashed during a low-level training mission in a 
remote section of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-seat jet went down shortly before noon Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The F-16, part of the 93rd Fighter Squadron, was one of four  
planes on a training mission from Homestead Air Reserve Base, 30 
miles southwest of Miami. The crash happened in northern Okeechobee 
County, about 150 miles north of Miami, and rescuers had difficulty 
reaching the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead pilot was identified as Air Force Reserve Maj. Samuel  
D'Angelo III, an American Airlines pilot and a 19-year military 
veteran who had recently flown a mission over northern Iraq's 
``no-fly'' zone. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Angelo, a resident of Key Largo, was a flight commander  
assigned to the 93rd Fighter Squadron. 
</P>
<P>
	The training mission had the pilots simulating a bombing run.  
D'Angelo had been performing maneuvers that required the plane to 
dip so low it was almost touching the ground, said Richard 
Cordones, spokesman for the Homestead reserve unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordones said he didn't know whether D'Angelo tried to eject  
before the plane crashed. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
