<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Closes at New High 11,139.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks reached new highs today as a strong  
employment report fed investors' enthusiasm and capped a week of 
extraordinary strength on Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial 
average rose 72.82 to close at 11,139.24, easily topping its 
previous record close of 11,107.19, set May 13. The Dow rose 586.68 
points for the week, a gain of more than 5 percent and the biggest 
one-week gain in its 103-year history. Broader stock indicators 
also moved higher, with the Nasdaq composite index and Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500 achieving new closing highs. The Nasdaq was up 34.83 to 
2,741.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        11,139.24  + 72.82
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,690  Declines 1,228  Unchgd  605
NYSE Volume:         567,656,410
Most Active NYSE issue:         Pfizer Inc38 5/8   + 1 1/4
S&AMP;P 500:         1389.25  + 8.29
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          802.42  +  7.47
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,741.01  + 34.83
Gold(final) -    $264.10    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Job Growth Surging  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is still roaring ahead, creating  
more than a quarter-million new jobs in June everywhere from 
amusement parks to banks. Though the overall unemployment rate 
crept up to 4.3 percent, all industries except manufacturing and 
mining posted solid gains. Orders to U.S. factories were up 1.1 
percent, the Commerce Department said. Indeed, some economists 
suggested the strong job growth could prolong concern at the 
Federal Reserve that the economy might be growing too fast for its 
own good. American businesses added 268,000 new jobs, a big 
turnaround from May when they cut payrolls by 5,000, the Labor 
Department said today. Meanwhile, Average hourly earnings -- a key 
gauge of inflation -- were up by 3.7 percent over the previous June, 
to $13.23. 

</P>
<P>
	Execs Guilty of Insurance Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Two executives with Columbia/HCA Healthcare  
Corp. were found guilty today of defrauding Medicare and other 
government insurance programs of nearly $3 million. The jury 
acquitted another executive and could not reach a verdict on a 
fourth defendant. Jay Jarrell and Robert Whiteside, both executives 
of the nation's largest hospital chain, were found guilty of 
conspiring to defraud and defrauding the tax-supported 
health-insurance programs. Michael Neeb was acquitted. The jury 
could not reach a verdict on Carl Lynn Dick, who was accused of 
conspiring to defraud Medicare, Medicaid and CHAMPUS, which is 
medical insurance for the military. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Auto Industry May Set Record  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor's U.S. sales increased 4 percent in  
June, compared with a strong performance a year ago, as the auto 
industry continued its steady growth toward a record sales year. 
Bob Rewey, Ford's sales and marketing chief, says the question is 
not so much whether 1999 will be a record sales year for the U.S. 
auto industry, but by how much it will break the records. General 
Motors planned to report its June sales later today. Ford's overall 
car sales increased 10 percent, excluding its Jaguar Cars and Volvo 
AB units. Ford said the increase was due to retail demand, as 
less-profitable sales to government and business fleets were down 
from a year ago. But like DaimlerChrysler AG, which reported 
Thursday that its Chrysler unit's sales were down 5 percent last 
month, Ford saw demand for its light trucks level off. 

</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank: N.Y., London Layoffs  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The 5,500 layoffs resulting from  
Deutsche Bank's takeover of Bankers Trust will come mainly in New 
York and London -- places where the two banks had overlapping 
trading operations, Deutsche Bank said today. The layoffs will be 
split ``about 50-50'' between the two cities, bank spokesman Dierk 
Hartwig said. None of the layoffs will be in Germany because 
Bankers Trust ``had no presence in Germany'' before the merger, 
hence there is no overlapping, he added. In a radio interview, 
chairman Rolf Breuer said both Deutsche Bank and Bankers Trust 
employees will be affected. 

</P>
<P>
	Retailer Laura Ashley Sells Stores  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- British-based Laura Ashley Holdings has completed  
the sale of its unprofitable chain of 94 North American stores. But 
the retailer of English country fashions and furnishings still has 
to overcome years of losses and management turmoil. Laura Ashley 
sold its U.S. and Canadian stores to a group of investors supported 
by Malayan United Industries, the Malaysian firm that last year 
injected $70 million into Laura Ashley in exchange for a 40 percent 
stake. Terms of the sale, completed today, were not disclosed. 

</P>
<P>
	Apache Opens Door for Collaboration  
</P>
<P>
	FOREST HILL, Md. (AP) -- Apache, the most widely used software  
for powering Internet servers, will become part of a not-for-profit 
corporation, a move designed to add stability and enable 
collaboration with established companies. The free, open-source 
software, is produced by volunteer programmers who share ideas and 
computer code to create the server software now used by 61 percent 
of Internet-connected servers, according a survey by Netcraft, a 
consulting firm in Bath, England. 

</P>
<P>
	Calif. Investigating Silicon Workers  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The government will investigate a  
newspaper's report that Silicon Valley high-tech companies pay 
Asian immigrants low wages to assemble electronic parts at home, 
possibly violating a number of labor, tax and safety laws. State 
Labor Commissioner Marcy Saunders told the San Jose Mercury News 
that officials plan to meet next week to begin forming a task force 
of state and federal labor officials. In stories published Sunday 
and Monday, the Mercury News reported that the use of immigrants to 
make electronic parts at home has been widespread in Silicon Valley 
since the early 1980s. At least a dozen local contract 
manufacturers have been involved in piecework arrangements within 
the past year, the newspaper said. 

</P>
<P>
	Coke: Another Recall in Poland  
</P>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Coca-Cola recalled a new batch of mineral  
water in Poland, this time due to bacteria contamination. The 
recall was the second this week in Poland and came even as the 
world's largest soft-drink company was restocking Belgian 
supermarket shelves with Coke as it attempts to recover from a 
four-week health scare. Although no illnesses have been reported in 
Poland, a Health Ministry expert said sampling at the plant 
discovered E. coli. The bacteria can cause illness and death, but 
the experts said the amount found at the Coca-Cola plant in 
southwest Poland was so small that it posed no health risk. 
Coca-Cola shares were at 64 13/16 down 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Approves IMF Requirements  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government approved key economic  
reforms, apparently inspired by the improved prospects of a badly 
needed foreign loan. The Central Bank announced it was lifting a 
major currency-trading restriction, while the upper house of 
parliament approved several economic bills -- all conditions for 
getting a $4.5 billion loan from the International Monetary Fund. 
An IMF team that visited Moscow this week praised Russia's economic 
performance and indicated that lending could soon be resumed. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia's Stock Market Rebounding  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Less than a year after the Russian economy  
crashed, the stock market is making a strong comeback, although 
business is modest, with investors torn between cheap prices and 
fears of getting burned twice. Fueled by expectations of a new $4.5 
billion loan from the International Monetary Fund and higher world 
oil prices, the Russian Trading System index rose 1.6 percent today 
to close at 133.67 points. The index is up 110 percent since last 
year's crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment: rises from 4.2 percent to 4.3 percent  
</P>
