<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends at Record High 11,139.24 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose to new records in a quiet session  
Friday as a strong employment report fed investors' enthusiasm and 
capped a week of extraordinary strength on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 72.82 to close at  
11,139.24, easily topping its previous record close of 11,107.19, 
set May 13. For the week, the Dow rose 5.56 percent or 586.68 
points, the biggest weekly point gain in its 103-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators extended a string of records. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 10.26 to close at 1,391.22, and the 
Nasdaq composite index rose 34.84 to 2,741.02. Both indexes set new 
closing highs Wednesday, Thursday and Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks marched higher Friday as the Labor Department said  
American businesses created a total of 268,000 new jobs in June, 
with all industries except manufacturing and mining posting solid 
gains. The increase in jobs was slightly stronger than economists 
expected, and average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation 
pressures, increased by 3.7 percent in June compared to a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In a less buoyant market, the report might have punctured  
investors' zest for stocks. Higher wages can drag earnings down 
because labor costs account for most of consumer prices. They also 
raise the specter of another increase in interest rates following 
this week's modest hike by the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bond market, which often sets the tone for stocks, was  
unmoved by the jump in wages. The yield on the benchmark 30-year 
Treasury bond remained steady at 6.0 percent, setting the stage for 
a sixth consecutive gain in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	``The markets blew right past it,'' said Ricky Harrington,  
technical analyst with Wachovia Securities in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington said market indexes were holding on to an influx of  
money from mutual fund managers, who settled their portfolios 
earlier this week as the second quarter drew to a close Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this kind of market, money managers don't want to be caught  
with cash on hand,'' he said. ``They want to show their clients 
that they're fully invested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors, meanwhile, continue to welcome strong economic news,  
discounting the fact that it could translate into inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this stage, we've got strong momentum and a real mania for  
stocks,'' Harrington said. ``It would take awfully bad news to 
change investor psychology and turn them away from this market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Farr, president of Farr, Miller &AMP; Washington, a  
Washington, D.C.-based financial consulting firm, said he believes 
the market gained enough support from the Fed's moderate interest 
rate increase to rise still higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has endured several bouts of fear,'' he said.  
``Each one has tested the resolve of the bull market. But every one 
has been for emotional reasons, not for rational ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, cyclical stocks, which perform best during times of  
economic expansion, rose broadly. International Paper rose 1 1/4 to 51 
and Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing rose 1 11/16 to 88 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks continued to gained strength from the interest  
rate environment. American Express, up 4 5/8 to 137 3/4, was the 
strongest Dow component. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading technology stocks contributed to gains on the Nasdaq,  
with Cisco Systems gaining 2 11/16 to 67 1/16 and Sun Microsystems 
rising 1 7/8 to 70 1/16. Internet companies were almost uniformly 
higher, with search engine company Infoseek risine 5 1/2 to 55 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-8 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into the three-day Independence Day weekend, many Wall  
Street players missed the fireworks. U.S. markets will be closed 
Monday in observance of the holiday, and many traders took Friday 
off as well. NYSE composite volume totaled a weak 753.20 million 
shares, compared with 1.02 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.79 to 655.12, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 7.47 to 802.42. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.09 to 456.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.4 percent. In  
Europe, Germany's DAX index rose 0.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 
rose 0.05 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.3 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
