<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Dennis Brown    	
</P>
<P>
	KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Dennis Brown, a former child star who  
became known as the Crown Prince of Reggae, died Thursday. He was 
42. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial reports suggested Brown died of complications caused by  
respiratory problems, but his cause of death had not yet been 
confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown rose to prominence amid a 1970s wave of reggae singers  
that included Bob Marley, who introduced the music to listeners 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown released a string of hit songs beginning with ``No Man is  
an Island,'' which he recorded in 1969 at the age of 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The singer's most fruitful period came later, when he produced  
hits including ``Westbound Train,'' ``How Could I Leave,'' and 
``Ghetto Girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He earned a Grammy nomination in 1995 for his album ``Light My  
Fire.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Edward Dmytryk    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Film director Edward Dmytryk, a member of the  
Hollywood Ten who served prison time during the Red Scare-era witch 
hunts of the 1940s and was blacklisted until he named names of his 
communist comrades, died Thursday. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmytryk had been ill for a year and succumbed to heart and  
kidney failure, said his wife, Jean Porter. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmytryk was a rising young director at RKO Pictures in 1945 when  
he joined the Communist Party. He said he stayed ``only a few 
months,'' but two years later the House Committee on Un-American 
Activities called him and nine other Hollywood figures to a 
Washington hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	All refused to answer questions about party membership. They  
were convicted of contempt and sentenced to a year in federal 
prison. When Dmytryk finished his sentence, he admitted that he had 
been a party member. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1951, Dmytryk returned to the House committee and identified  
26 people as communists. Only then did he find work in Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	After making a string of low-budget films for Stanley Kramer,  
the producer assigned him to the 1954 World War II drama, ``The 
Caine Mutiny,'' starring Humphrey Bogart. The film's success made 
Dmytryk an in-demand director. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmytryk also directed ``Raintree County,'' ``The Young Lions,''  
``The Carpetbaggers'' and other films starring some of Hollywood's 
most famous names. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Shig Kariya    	
</P>
<P>
	SILVER SPRING, Md. (AP) -- Shig Kariya, a Japanese American  
businessman who was interned during World War II and later founded 
Mikasa Inc. tableware company, died June 25 of pneumonia. He was 
84. 
</P>
<P>
	Kariya was born in Japan to parents who had immigrated to  
California in 1913, yet traveled to Japan frequently on business. 
Along with his parents, he was placed in a relocation camp during 
the war years because of his ancestry. 
</P>
<P>
	After his release, Kariya and seven others teamed up in 1948 to  
create American Commercial Inc. to import tableware from Japan. The 
company soon changed its name to Mikasa, which continues to market 
china, crystal and flatware. 
</P>
<P>
	Kariya earned Japan's Emperor's Award in 1988 for his work in  
promoting relations between his native and adopted countries. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Isaac Campbell Kidd Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Ret. Adm. Isaac Campbell Kidd Jr., who in  
the mid-1970s was simultaneously commander in chief of the U.S. 
Atlantic Fleet and NATO's supreme allied commander in the Atlantic, 
died Sunday at age 79. He had battled cancer for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Kidd began his Navy career in 1942 after graduating from the  
U.S. Naval Academy. When he retired in 1978, he had 23 years of sea 
duty, including commands of destroyers, destroyer divisions and 
squadrons, a flotilla and three U.S. fleets in the Atlantic, 
Pacific and Mediterranean. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Robert Pohill    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert Polhill, an American professor at  
Beirut University College who was held hostage in the Middle East 
for 39 months, died Thursday at Georgetown University of 
complications from throat cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	A resident of Arlington, Va., Polhill was 65.  
</P>
<P>
	Polhill was working as an assistant professor of business  
studies when he and three fellow faculty members were seized in 
January of 1987 by gunmen posing as police officers on the 
college's campus. 
</P>
<P>
	During most of his time in isolation, Polhill was chained in  
windowless rooms, receiving only occasional visits from doctors to 
treat his diabetes. He was released in 1990, as part of an effort 
to improve relations between Iran and the United States. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Constance Shacklock    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Constance Shacklock, a mezzo-soprano who was one  
of the leading singers at the Royal Opera House from 1946 to 1956, 
died Tuesday. She was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Shacklock made her debut at the Royal Opera in 1946 in  
``The Fairy Queen'' by Henry Purcell. But she made her reputation 
as one of the outstanding performers of Wagner. 
</P>
<P>
	One of her triumphs was singing Brangaene in ``Tristan und  
Isolde'' opposite Kirsten Flagstad. She sang that role in her first 
appearance outside Britain, at the State Opera House in East Berlin 
in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	She made more than 500 appearances at Covent Garden, and for a  
decade was the featured singer at the ``Last Night of the Proms'' 
at the Royal Albert Hall. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sylvia Sidney    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sylvia Sidney, the waiflike star of the 1930s  
who got an Oscar nomination in 1973 for a comeback role in ``Summer 
Wishes, Winter Dreams,'' died Thursday. She was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sidney made her professional theater debut at 16 and was  
still acting 70 years later, with a brief appearance in the 1988 
hit ``Beetlejuice'' and a small role in ``Mars Attacks'' in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the directors she worked with were Josef von Sternberg, in  
``An American Tragedy,'' 1931; Alfred Hitchcock in ``Sabotage'' 
(also called ``A Woman Alone''), 1936; William Wyler, in ``Dead 
End,'' 1937; and Fritz Lang in ``Fury,'' 1936, ``You Only Live 
Once,'' 1937, and ``You and Me,'' 1938. 
</P>
<P>
	Her return to the screen was in the 1973 drama ``Summer Wishes,  
Winter Dreams,'' in which she played Joanne Woodward's doomed 
mother. She was nominated for an Academy Award for best supporting 
actress. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Lord Whitelaw    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lord Whitelaw, one of the most prominent  
Conservative politicians of the postwar years and a principal ally 
of former British premier Margaret Thatcher, died Thursday. He was 
81. 
</P>
<P>
	William Whitelaw served as Northern Ireland secretary and leader  
of the House of Commons under former Prime Minister Edward Heath in 
the 1970s, and as home secretary and leader of the House of Lords 
during Mrs. Thatcher's governments in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	He led the Lords until 1988, and after Mrs. Thatcher's  
resignation in 1990 continued as deputy leader of the Conservative 
Party for nine more months. He stepped down in August 1991 after 16 
years in the post and 35 years' service to the party. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
