<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid To Pay $1.1M in Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The nation's third-largest drugstore  
chain will pay $1.1 million in fines to settle a lawsuit that 
claimed its stores sold expired infant formula, condoms and other 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid Corp. also agreed to post notices at its 640 California  
stores telling customers who purchased expired goods that they 
could be reimbursed or given replacements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to do our utmost to ensure the integrity of  
our products,'' the Camp Hill, Pa.-based company said Friday. 
``Selling expired merchandise is not something that Rite Aid, or 
any retailer, would knowingly allow to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors from three California counties and one city filed  
the suit last month, after investigators found more than 200 
outdated products in about 50 of the chain's stores in California. 
Some condoms were four years past their expiration date. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had no reports of infants falling ill from outdated  
products, but they cautioned that formulas lose their nutritional 
value over time, and that condoms and spermicides lose their 
effectiveness after their expiration dates pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid said its policy had always been to pull items off  
shelves 30 days before they expire; after the investigators' 
disclosure, that was changed to 60 days. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
