<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shandling, Ex-Manager Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Garry Shandling has settled a $100 million  
lawsuit against his former manager, ending a dispute that brought 
attention to the potential conflicts of interest created when 
managers double as TV producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The terms of the settlement between the comedian and Brad Grey  
were not disclosed Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very pleased we could achieve it without the necessity  
of a trial,'' said Shandling's attorney, David Boies. 
</P>
<P>
	Shandling's lawsuit alleged that Grey's role as his manager and  
executive producer of the now-ended ``The Larry Sanders Show'' 
represented a conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit alleged that Grey was able to ``triple-dip,'' taking  
excess commissions and fees out of the HBO series. It also claimed 
Grey used Shandling's name to make $200 million-plus in other 
show-business deals and owed him a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Grey resigned as Shandling's manager in 1997. Shandling sued the  
following year. 
</P>
<P>
	While Grey's success as a producer is unusual, managers are  
increasingly serving as producers on sitcoms starring their 
clients. Networks and production companies have complained these 
executives don't always earn their producer title or money. 
</P>
<P>
	Grey's lawyer, Charles Shephard, said the case was not  
indicative of an industry-wide problem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
