<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Stock Market Rebounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's stock market is making a strong comeback  
less than a year after the economy crashed, but fears of getting 
burned twice have tempered investors' urge to snap up low-priced 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Fueled by expectations of a new $4.5 billion loan from the  
International Monetary Fund and higher world oil prices, the 
Russian Trading System index rose 1.6 percent Friday to close at 
133.67 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is up 110 percent since last year's crash, a  
remarkable turnaround after the troubles set off by Asia's 
financial crash in the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly bankrupt, Russia was forced to default on its sovereign  
debt last August and devalue the ruble, sending the market into a 
tailspin. Spooked by rumors of everything from government 
nationalization to the return of communism, investors fled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russia limped through the crisis and its market has bounced  
back in spite of political turmoil that saw three prime ministers 
and new Cabinets with each one. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, trading volumes on Russia's market these days are  
modest. On Friday, the volume reached $27 million, far below 
pre-crisis levels but still up from recent volumes of about $5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebound is largely attributed to new IMF optimism and talk  
of more credits. Also, the government has made some headway in 
persuading creditors to reschedule its Soviet-era debts, which 
account for about two-thirds of its $150 billion foreign debt 
burden. 
</P>
<P>
	But the fact that prices are so low are certainly not a  
deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
	``People started buying Russian shares again mostly because the  
price is so low,'' Boris Fyodorov, former tax minister, wrote this 
week in Segodnya daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 12:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Primary Calendar Concerns GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the Republican National  
Committee said today he will appoint an advisory panel to recommend 
ways to reverse a trend among states to hold presidential primaries 
earlier and earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Releasing a tentative primary schedule for next year, RNC  
Chairman Jim Nicholson said he was ``concerned about the trend 
toward front-loading the calendar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa caucuses, one of the first major events in 2000, could  
come as early as Jan. 31, he said. And by the end of February, 
about 40 percent more delegates will have been chosen than by the 
same time in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is so compressed and it goes off like a string of  
firecrackers once it starts,'' he said. ``A person who might have 
gotten a bounce because of a surprisingly good showing in an early 
primary ... (won't have) time to really maximize that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previous incentives, like giving states more delegates if they  
push back their primary, have failed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our major concern is that not enough people get involved in  
this process of choosing who the nominees will be for the most 
important job on Earth,'' Nicholson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I think if you would ask the candidates, they would  
agree,'' he said. ``They would like to have more time to be out in 
more states and learning their issues and learning more about those 
regions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said he will appoint senior Republican officials to  
his advisory panel, which probably will be chaired by a former RNC 
leader since many former chairmen ``have run for and been elected 
president of the United States. ... They've been through the mill 
in this process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel will issue findings by the end of the year so that the  
suggestions can be considered during the RNC winter meeting next 
January in California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will instruct them to examine all possible options,  
including the plan recently put forth by the National Association 
of Secretaries of State, which is a regional rotating primary,'' he 
said. ``I'm going to ask them to look at other possibilities, 
including a stronger incentive-based program, perhaps, a national 
delegate selection day, and others that have been put on the table 
around the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said the RNC rules committee also is studying the  
issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 15:16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Charismatic Improves After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charismatic continues to improve from surgery  
for leg fractures sustained in the Belmont Stakes that could have 
proved fatal. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of severity, and on a scale of one to 10, it was a  
'nine','' said Dr. Celeste Kunz, whose quick reaction help saved 
the life the Kentucky Derby-Preakness winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fracture (a condylar fracture of the left front cannon  
bone with an additional fracture to the seasmoid) was dangerously 
displaced,'' she said Friday at news conference at Belmont Park. 
``If it had broken through the skin, the prognosis would have been 
lowered significantly. I fitted the leg with a compression boot 
suitable to the horse's weight and size in order to immobilize 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis and trained by D.  
Wayne Lukas, was retired and will go to stud 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when in the running of the Belmont Stakes June 9 he  
thought the injury occurred, Dr. Stephen Selway, who operated on 
the colt the following day, said his best guess was that it 
happened between the quarter and eighth poles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he carried his head changed and, although his momentum  
carried him on, he seemed to lose his fluidity of motion,'' Selway 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic finished third behind Lemon Drop Kid and Vision and  
Verse in his bid to become the 12th Triple Crown champion and first 
since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Selway credited quick action to ``stabilize Charismatic's  
physiological condition following the injury'' as being of critical 
importance in the horse's survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Chris Antley also helped by dismounting shortly after the  
finish and lifting the injured leg to relieve the weight on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic has responded well to surgery and to continuing  
treatment. He is expected to remain in his stall for another two to 
three months. Complete healing of the fracture is expected to take 
four to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Although horses with somewhat similar injuries have resumed in  
competition, Charismatic's retirement was considered the most 
prudent course to pursue, Selway said, ``to preserve an invaluable 
gene pool.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 03:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Confirmed for Treasury Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- By an overwhelming margin, the Senate has  
confirmed Lawrence Summers to succeed Robert Rubin as treasury 
secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, will assume the top job today following a  
swearing-in ceremony, Treasury Department spokeswoman Michelle 
Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined Treasury in 1993 as undersecretary for international  
affairs and has served in the agency's No. 2 job since 1995, when 
Rubin became secretary. Rubin announced his resignation on May 12, 
and Clinton immediately named Summers to be his successor. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators approved Summers in a 97-2 vote Thursday. Only Sens.  
Wayne Allard, R-Colo., and Bob Smith, R-N.H., voted against him, 
while Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., did not vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, a millionaire Wall Street investment banker before  
joining the administration, has not said what he will do next. He 
led the Treasury Department during a time of historic levels of 
economic growth, debt reduction, job growth and low inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said that Summers had a close working relationship with  
Clinton and that the handling of economic matters would be in good 
hands with Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is extraordinarily bright, extraordinarily insightful about  
the economy,'' Rubin told NBC News. ``It is very interesting to 
watch him talk with the president because when he starts to say 
something, the president just hones in on him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate PBS interview, Rubin stressed that Summers had  
also developed a close working relationship with Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan. Rubin said he and Summers had met weekly 
for the past several years with Greenspan over breakfast or lunch 
and exchanged views on a wide range of economic issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``That relationship has been enormously useful when we have had  
to deal with crises and with serious issues,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin called ``totally untrue'' the suggestion in the PBS  
interview that he had considered resigning from the administration 
because of his unhappiness with Clinton after the Monica Lewinsky 
scandal erupted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president made terrible mistakes. He acknowledged he made  
terrible mistakes,'' Rubin said. But he said he still had ``a great 
deal of respect'' for the way Clinton kept focused on issues such 
as the Asian financial crisis and other duties during the 
impeachment ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers has said he sees no need to change any of Rubin's  
policies on issues facing Treasury, including Social Security and 
Medicare reform, the health of the U.S. steel industry, Japan's 
worrisome economy and the dismal U.S. savings rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers is a native of New Haven, Conn., and was a Harvard  
economics professor and the World Bank's chief economist before 
joining Treasury. He was also a domestic policy economist on 
President Reagan's Council of Economic Advisors from 1982 to 1983. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
