<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Charismatic Improves After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charismatic continues to improve from surgery  
for leg fractures sustained in the Belmont Stakes that could have 
proved fatal. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of severity, and on a scale of one to 10, it was a  
'nine','' said Dr. Celeste Kunz, whose quick reaction help saved 
the life the Kentucky Derby-Preakness winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fracture (a condylar fracture of the left front cannon  
bone with an additional fracture to the seasmoid) was dangerously 
displaced,'' she said Friday at news conference at Belmont Park. 
``If it had broken through the skin, the prognosis would have been 
lowered significantly. I fitted the leg with a compression boot 
suitable to the horse's weight and size in order to immobilize 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis and trained by D.  
Wayne Lukas, was retired and will go to stud 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when in the running of the Belmont Stakes June 9 he  
thought the injury occurred, Dr. Stephen Selway, who operated on 
the colt the following day, said his best guess was that it 
happened between the quarter and eighth poles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he carried his head changed and, although his momentum  
carried him on, he seemed to lose his fluidity of motion,'' Selway 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic finished third behind Lemon Drop Kid and Vision and  
Verse in his bid to become the 12th Triple Crown champion and first 
since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Selway credited quick action to ``stabilize Charismatic's  
physiological condition following the injury'' as being of critical 
importance in the horse's survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Chris Antley also helped by dismounting shortly after the  
finish and lifting the injured leg to relieve the weight on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic has responded well to surgery and to continuing  
treatment. He is expected to remain in his stall for another two to 
three months. Complete healing of the fracture is expected to take 
four to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Although horses with somewhat similar injuries have resumed in  
competition, Charismatic's retirement was considered the most 
prudent course to pursue, Selway said, ``to preserve an invaluable 
gene pool.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
