<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil TV Stars Sell Phone Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Open almost any newspaper these  
days and you'll see soap opera star Luana Piovani, advising that 
her number is 15. On television, her sultry rival Ana Paula Arosio 
invites viewers to ``make a 21.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two actresses are pitching rival phone companies, a concept  
that was unthinkable until last July, when Brazil sold its mammoth 
government-owned telecoms monopoly Telebras for $19 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Saturday, private competition will begin in earnest.  
The government predicts consumers will receive unprecedented 
benefits and options in price, service and quality. 
</P>
<P>
	It also could cause unprecedented confusion, at least at first.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's great that the phone companies are using nice-looking  
girls in ads,'' said taxi driver Flavio Nunes, eyeing a phone 
company billboard. ``But they haven't told me how much my calls 
will be. I'm still not sure which company to use.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new system, users can choose the carrier they want for  
long-distance and international calls. It's a novelty for 
Brazilians, and means a whole new menu of phone numbers for any 
non-local call. 
</P>
<P>
	The old way, people made a long-distance call by punching a  
``0'' followed by a two-digit area code and the number. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, between the ``0'' and the area code comes another two-digit  
number corresponding to a local private carrier. Seven phone 
companies exist, and two more are scheduled to start up by year's 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest company is Embratel, represented by Ms. Arosio and  
her ``21.'' Now owned by MCI WorldCom Inc. of Jackson, Miss., it is 
the only company that serves all of Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Piovani's ``15'' stands for Spanish-owned Telefonica. The  
company will battle Embratel for the market in Sao Paulo, South 
America's biggest city, accounting for half of Brazil's $4 billion 
a year phone business. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's National Telecommunications Agency, Anatel,  
expects a price war among services, as happened when cellular phone 
operators were privatized. And because users pick a company on 
every call, the battle should be permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	In an opening salvo last week, Embratel announced discounts of  
up to 20 percent discounts for corporate rates. Telefonica 
responded by cutting its rates up to 15 percent and promised 
further discounts for households. 
</P>
<P>
	Price cuts are not the only methods the telecom companies will  
use to woo callers. Among the attractions expected to be offered 
soon are discounts and ``frequent dialer'' bonuses for good 
customers and special rates for Internet users. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
