<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Beer Rivals Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Brahma and Antarctica, bitter rivals  
for Brazil's beer and soft-drink business, are merging to in an 
attempt to become a global power in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would be the world's third-largest brewery,  
after Anheuser-Busch Cos. and Heineken NV, in terms of volume of 
beer production and the world's fifth-largest beverage company by 
volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan announced Friday, the new company would be known  
as Companhia de Bebidas das Americas, or AmBev. 
</P>
<P>
	``This kind of association is inevitable. We are the first (in  
Brazil) but I think we will start seeing Brazilian giant companies 
in some sectors moving to consolidation to compete in the global 
market,'' Marcel Telles, Brahma's president said explaining that 
AmBev plans to use its Brazilian base of operations as a 
springboard for expansion across Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Brahma and Antarctica sold a total of 16.4 billion  
gallons of beer and 6.5 billion gallons of soft drinks. They have 
combined assets of $4.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Brahma has a 50 percent share of Brazil's beer market, while  
Antarctica retains about 25 percent. Jointly, the two company's 
have 39 percent of Brazil's beverage market, including beer, soft 
drinks, mineral water, health drinks and tea. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the market concentration, especially in the area of  
beer, analysts have said that the deal is almost certain to run 
afoul of antitrust authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Sensitive to antitrust concerns, the presidents of Brahma and  
Antarctica met with Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso 
before announcing the move. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the two companies were also careful to  
characterize the deal as an ``association'' under which they would 
remain wholly-owned subsidiaries of a merged entity. 
</P>
<P>
	Under this arrangement, AmBev would maintain separate  
distribution networks and marketing operations for its different 
brand names, but would join production lines to increase 
efficiency, said Victorio de Marchi, Antarctica's president. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials intend to argue that this separation should  
guarantee competition in the domestic market, when they make their 
case before Brazil's Economic Defense Council, which handles 
antitrust matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Brahma's Telles and Antarctica's Marchi would be co-chairmen of  
AmBev. Brahma executive Magim Rodriguez will be president, 
overseeing day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The creation of AmBev also means the end of the Brahma's  
partnership with Miller Brewing Co., a unit of Philip Morris Cos. 
Inc., and Antarctica's partnership with Anheuser-Busch. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch said it will pull out from an equity purchase  
agreement with Antarctica, which would have increased its stock in 
the company from the current 5 percent to 30 percent by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Brahma's Telles said his company was notifying Miller  
of the AmBev deal. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 12:00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Semis: Sampras-Henman, Rafter-Agassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- The winner of the Wimbledon men's  
title is guaranteed a little bit of tennis history. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Sampras, aiming for his sixth title, hopes to tie Roy  
Emerson's record of 12 Grand Slams, while semifinal opponent Tim 
Henman bids to become the first British player to win the men's 
championship since Fred Perry in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	Andre Agassi seeks to emulate Bjorn Borg, the last player to win  
the French Open and Wimbledon titles in the same year. Borg last 
did it in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	And his semifinal foe, Pat Rafter, seeks to beat Agassi to  
become the first Australian to hold the No. 1 ranking since John 
Newcombe in 1974. He then can become the first Australian to hold 
both the U.S. Open and Wimbledon titles at the same time since Rod 
Laver in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sampras-Henman semifinal is a repeat of last year's matchup,  
when the American triumphed 6-3, 4-6, 7-5, 6-3 on the way to his 
fifth Wimbledon title. 
</P>
<P>
	They are friends, and frequently play golf together when they  
meet on the tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know his game very well, he knows my game very well and  
we've practiced together quite a bit over the past couple of 
years,'' said Sampras, 5-0 against Brit with three of those 
victories coming on grass. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played a tight match at Queen's and a tight match here last  
year,'' Sampras said. ``The crowd's going to be behind him, which 
won't be easy but I've been in this situation before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a matter of time before he breaks through and wins  
here. Hopefully it won't happen this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henman, who ousted Jim Courier in a 4 1/2-hour fourth-round match,  
will have a huge and noisy crowd roaring him on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm through to the semis for the second year, so my confidence  
is very high,'' said the 24-year-old Brit. ``I don't feel like I've 
got anything to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he knows that Sampras, whose titles have come in the past  
six years, isn't used to losing at Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at Pete's record, he's played 45 matches here in  
the last six or seven years and he's won 44 of them,'' Henman said. 
``I think his record is self-explanatory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras didn't lose a set until he met Mark Philippoussis in the  
quarterfinals, and went through after the big-serving Australian 
injured a knee early in the second set and withdrew while leading 
6-4, 1-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-seeded Agassi, 5-3 against Rafter, is still on a roll  
following a depressing slump in 1997. He dropped to 141 in the 
world that year, and played in lower- ranked Challenger 
tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	Climbing rapidly back up the rankings, Agassi came up with a  
stunning French Open triumph from two sets down to Andrei Medvedev 
in the final. Agassi now has won 12 matches in a row, all in Grand 
Slam events. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to be in the semis these days and not feel good  
about your game, it really is,'' said Agassi, who crushed former 
French Open champ Gustavo Kuerten in straight sets in the 
quarterfinal. ``But I think everybody is playing better, not only 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter, the two-time US Open champion who overpowered  
eighth-seeded Todd Martin to make the semifinal, had never been 
past the fourth round at Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pretty big milestone for me and I want to keep going,''  
the Australian said after his 6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (7-3) 
victory over Martin put him in the final four. Andre's obviously 
hitting the ball very well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today was the best I've volleyed since I've been here, and I'm  
pretty confident I'll be able to break Andre's serve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter said the chance of being No. 1 wasn't on his mind.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so happy to be here at the moment, the semifinals,''  
he said. ``The finals of Wimbledon definitely overshadows the No. 1 
positions in my book.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
