<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boldon Wins Men's 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Ato Boldon won the men's 100-meter  
showdown Friday night at the Athletissima track and field meet, 
beating world record-holder and training partner Maurice Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon burst down the lightning-quick Pontaise track in 9.86  
seconds, tying the season's second-best time. Boldon also run 9.86 
at Athens last month, but finished second to Greene, who smashed 
the world record in 9.79. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Boldon, of Trindad &AMP; Tobago, finished .07 seconds  
ahead of Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Jason Gardener broke the 10-second barrier for the  
first time in his career, placing third in 9.98. Olympic silver 
medalist Frank Fredericks of Namibia was fourth in 10.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Making up for a disappointing seventh-place finish at the USA  
Championships last week, Larry Wade posted the season's fastest 
time in the 110-meter hurdles of 13.01. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be the best at what I do,'' Wade said. ``I don't  
have a time or a championship to aspire to. I just want to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wade led an American sweep of the top three places. Mark Crear  
finished second in 13.04 and Allen Johnson was third in 13.13. 
</P>
<P>
	Norberto Tellez of Cuba won the men's 800 in 1:44.05, with  
Kenya's Kennedy Kimwetich second in 1:44.13 and Olympic silver 
medalist Hezekiel Sepeng of South Africa third in 1:44.31. 
</P>
<P>
	Falilat Ogunkoya of Nigeria registered the fastest time of the  
season in the women's 400 with 50.01, nearly a half-second ahead of 
Lorraine Graham of Jamaican. American Suziann Reid, runner-up at 
the U.S. championships, finished third. 
</P>
<P>
	American Melissa Morrison made up for a bad stumble at the U.S.  
championships, winning the women's 100 hurdles in 12.74, .01 
second. ahead of Nigeria's Glory Alozie. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
