<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Offers Sampras His Team Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Todd Martin is ready to step aside and  
let Pete Sampras play singles when the United States meets 
Australia in the Davis Cup quarterfinals July 16-18 at Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras, inspired by the Americans' dramatic win over Britain in  
April, wants to return to the team. In order not to upset the team 
by stealing a singles spot, he offered only to play doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Pete should be playing singles,'' said Martin after  
losing to Pat Rafter in the Wimbledon quarterfinals Friday. ``I 
don't know if Pete thinks that, I don't know if Gully (team captain 
Tom Gullikson) thinks that, and I don't know if Jim (Courier) 
thinks that, but I want our best team on court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Courier and Martin played both singles and doubles when the  
United States beat Britain 3-2. Sampras declined to play, saying 
his priority was on winning Grand Slam titles not the Davis Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Philippoussis sustained a knee injury Friday during his  
quarterfinal match against Sampras, and retired early in the second 
set. He is doubtful for the Davis Cup. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
