<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:20 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	'Godfather' Author Dies at 78  
</P>
<P>
	BAYSHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Best-selling author Mario Puzo, creator of  
the fictional Corleone mob family and winner of two Oscars for his 
screen adaptations of his book ``The Godfather,'' died today at age 
78. Puzo died, apparently of heart failure, at his Long Island 
home, said Neil Olson, his literary agent. Puzo had just finished 
work on his latest book, ``Omerta.'' The book is due out in July 
2000. Puzo wrote seven other novels in addition to ``The 
Godfather.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Belfast Talks End With No Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The British and Irish prime  
ministers announced a bold plan today to form Northern Ireland's 
long-postponed Protestant-Catholic government -- without securing 
the support of key local politicians. Under the plan announced 
after week-long negotiations, Tony Blair of Britain and Bertie 
Ahern of Ireland said they were hoping to see Northern Ireland's 
legislative Assembly elect the new administration on July 15. But 
the conditional nature of their plan was underlined by Ahern, who 
called the plan ``an agreement for consideration.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Job Growth Shows Strong Rebound  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The unemployment rate edged up slightly to 4.3  
percent in June even though job growth showed a strong rebound 
during the month as amusement parks, restaurants and construction 
firms gobbled up workers, the Labor Department reported today. 
Manufacturing, however, continued to miss out, with job losses in 
that sector now totaling nearly a half-million workers since the 
Asian crisis hit. The jobless rate for more than a year has been at 
levels not seen in nearly three decades. Unemployment in May had 
dipped to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent. ``The fundamentals of this 
economy remain strong,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman. 

</P>
<P>
	Aversion to Movie Violence Drops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Associated Press poll suggests that  
Americans don't seem to be as upset by violent movies as they used 
to be. The poll found that 40 percent of adults said they would be 
less likely to see a movie if they knew it contained violence -- 20 
points lower than the percentage who answered the same way a decade 
ago. In the poll, conducted by ICR of Media, Pa., only one-third of 
respondents said violence is the biggest problem with current 
movies, about the same percentage who said tickets cost too much. 
An additional 17 percent said movies aren't as good as they used to 
be, and 13 percent said there is too much sex on the big screen. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Opposition Leader Returning  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A top Serb opposition leader will  
return to Yugoslavia despite a military court investigation into 
charges he dodged the draft, a close associate said today. In an 
intensified crackdown against opponents, President Slobodan 
Milosevic's government ordered criminal proceedings against 
Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic for draft evasion during 
NATO's 78-day air campaign. ``The criminal proceedings will not 
prevent Djindjic from returning home,'' the party's deputy leader, 
Zoran Zivkovic said. ``We expect him here next week.'' Djindjic's 
lawyers maintain that he never received the draft call. 

</P>
<P>
	Bald Eagle May Leave Endangered List  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American bald eagle, the living symbol of  
the nation since 1782, is back from the brink of extinction and can 
now be removed from the endangered species list, President Clinton 
said today. Celebrating a three-decade struggle to protect the bald 
eagle against pesticides and encroachments on its habitat, Clinton 
announced a process that is expected to remove the majestic bird 
from the list by July 2000. ``It's hard to think of a better way to 
celebrate the birth of a nation than to celebrate the rebirth of 
our national symbol,'' the president said on the eve of the 
Independence Day weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Earned Between $2M and $10M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush reported today that  
he earned between $2.1 million and $10.1 million last year, mostly 
from selling his interests in oil, gas, real estate and the Texas 
Rangers professional baseball team. The early front-runner for the 
GOP presidential nomination reported no debts and listed a 
diversified trust valued at between $1 million and $5 million as 
his largest asset. He also reported owning more than a half million 
dollars in U.S. Treasury notes. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 58; Nasdaq Up 27  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 58.57 points at 11,124.99. The Dow's all-time high close was 
11,107.19 on May 13. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,610-1,282. The Nasdaq was up 27.69 at 
2,733.87. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras, Agassi, Stevenson Advance  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi are one  
victory from an All-American final on the Fourth of July. Sampras 
reached the semis when Mark Philippoussis quit with a knee injury 
today while holding a one-set lead. Agassi beat Brazil's Gustavo 
Kuerten 6-3, 6-4, 6-4. Alexandra Stevenson, an 18-year-old 
Californian, became the first qualifier in Wimbledon history to 
reach the women's semifinals, beating Jelena Dokic, 6-3, 1-6, 6-3. 
Sampras will face Britain's Tim Henman. Agassi is paired with U.S. 
Open champion Patrick Rafter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
