<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Freebies For VIPs in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Kings, queens and assorted VIPs will get  
no free tickets, transportation or parking during the 2002 Winter 
Olympic Games, a policy committee of the Salt Lake Organizing 
Committee decided Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, headed by Nolan Karras -- Gov. Mike Leavitt's Olympic  
representative -- drafted an ethics and conflict-of-interest code 
and policies intended to open records and meetings to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ad Hoc Policy Committee was given its charge Feb. 11 when  
SLOC was reorganized following allegations that Salt Lake bidders 
lavished gifts, favors, cash payments, medical care and jobs on 
International Olympic Committee members and their relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Karras said SLOC will just say `no' when American or foreign  
dignitaries ask for complimentary tickets or other favors during 
the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to get lots of requests from all kinds of  
government officials -- kings, queens and heads of countries,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even SLOC's own 54 volunteer trustees may have to purchase  
tickets to Olympic competitions, though that issue is undecided, 
Karras said. The no-freebie policy applies to virtually everyone 
other than IOC members, who by contract will get credentials and 
special seating at every Olympic ceremony and event. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's sweeping policies on ethics, internal records and  
board and committee meetings will go to the full board of trustees 
Thursday for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel polished the rules after four hours of negotiation  
with lawyers for newspapers and TV and radio stations in Salt Lake 
City. Many of the practices already have been adopted by SLOC, a 
private corporation using millions of dollars in taxpayer money it 
is supposed to repay after the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Exceptions govern many disclosure rules, and one of the most  
contentious debates Friday came over SLOC's 50-volume budget, which 
has never publicly been disclosed. SLOC has released only a 
sketchy, four-page summary of the $1.45 billion budget. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC president Mitt Romney also argued for strictly limiting  
disclosure of SLOC salaries, saying nothing good could come of it. 
SLOC will release the salaries only of officers and the five 
highest-paid employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Any greater disclosure ``will cost us more money'' as employees  
discover that others in equivalent positions are getting paid more, 
Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, the ad hoc panel tightened a conflict-of-interest  
rule that already tossed three trustees from the SLOC board. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules says key employees, officers and board trustees  
must resign if they or their spouses or children own 5 percent or 
more of a company receiving $500,000 or more from SLOC. The 
previous threshold was $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Those with smaller conflicts could do business with SLOC if  
conflicts are disclosed and approved. SLOC is hiring an ethics 
officer to review potential conflicts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
