<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Seize U.S. Fishing Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Canadian authorities have seized a 41-foot  
Alaska fishing boat, boarding the vessel with one person aboard and 
taking it into Canadian waters, the U.S. Coast Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lesley Ann was seized Thursday by the Canadian Department of  
Fisheries and Oceans and was believed to have been escorted to 
Prince Rupert, British Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The vessel was fishing legally but was in a disputed zone where  
the United States and Canada have an agreement for so-called ``flag 
state enforcement,'' Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Ray Massey said late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vessels that are U.S.-registered we have jurisdiction over,  
and those that are Canadian registered, they do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Bosworth of Petersburg was fishing for black cod about 50  
miles south of Ketchikan. He radioed the Coast Guard for help 
Thursday afternoon, saying he had been boarded by Canadian 
authorities from the enforcement ship Kitimat II and that the 
Canadians were taking his vessel to Prince Rupert. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard cutter Anacapa went to the area, protested the  
seizure and shadowed the Lesley Ann and the Canadian vessel until 
they reached Canadian waters, the Coast Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian fisheries officials in Prince Rupert could not be  
reached by telephone late Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
