<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals Campus Gun Possession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Nearly half a million of the nation's college  
students own guns and those with alcohol problems are twice as 
likely as others to have them, according to a Harvard University 
study released today. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3.5 percent of college students surveyed said they have a  
gun at school, said Dr. Matthew Miller, a researcher at Harvard's 
Injury Research and Control Center. Some 14 million students attend 
two- and four-year colleges in the United States, so that 
percentage would translate to roughly 450,000, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun possession is significantly more likely among students who  
binge drink and drive, or who damage property after drinking, the 
report said. Binge drinking was defined as having five or more 
drinks at a sitting. 
</P>
<P>
	The report is based on a sample of some 15,000 students at 130  
four-year colleges, and did not account for hunting weapons. The 
results appear in the July issue of The Journal of American College 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	The connection is worrisome, said Henry Wechsler, principal  
investigator at Harvard's School of Public Health College Alcohol 
Study. But he cautioned: ``I don't want to give the impression that 
there are thousands of drunk college students shooting people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based on a 1997 questionnaire filled out  
anonymously by students. The questionnaire primarily focused on 
alcohol use, but also asked students if they had a working firearm 
at school. 
</P>
<P>
	The results found that 6.4 percent of men students said yes, as  
did 1.5 percent of women students. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun ownership increased to 7 percent among those who said they  
were likely to drink heavily, drive while intoxicated or damage 
property after drinking. 
</P>
<P>
	The study had a margin of error of 1 percentage point.  
</P>
<P>
	Although it's possible some students may have been lying or  
exaggerating, Miller said he takes their answers seriously because 
the forms were anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found gun possession at college was more common  
among whites than among minority groups, and more prevalent among 
students who belonged to fraternities or sororities. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate of gun ownership differed by region. Six percent of  
students attending colleges in the South said they had guns, 
compared with 4 percent in the West and 1 percent in the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey also found that two-thirds of the student gun owners  
live off-campus. Although most colleges prohibit guns on campus, 
researchers estimate students keep at least 100,000 guns in the 
nation's dormitories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 14:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Charismatic Improves After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charismatic continues to improve from surgery  
for leg fractures sustained in the Belmont Stakes that could have 
proved fatal. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of severity, and on a scale of one to 10, it was a  
'nine','' said Dr. Celeste Kunz, whose quick reaction help saved 
the life the Kentucky Derby-Preakness winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fracture (a condylar fracture of the left front cannon  
bone with an additional fracture to the seasmoid) was dangerously 
displaced,'' she said Friday at news conference at Belmont Park. 
``If it had broken through the skin, the prognosis would have been 
lowered significantly. I fitted the leg with a compression boot 
suitable to the horse's weight and size in order to immobilize 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis and trained by D.  
Wayne Lukas, was retired and will go to stud 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when in the running of the Belmont Stakes June 9 he  
thought the injury occurred, Dr. Stephen Selway, who operated on 
the colt the following day, said his best guess was that it 
happened between the quarter and eighth poles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he carried his head changed and, although his momentum  
carried him on, he seemed to lose his fluidity of motion,'' Selway 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic finished third behind Lemon Drop Kid and Vision and  
Verse in his bid to become the 12th Triple Crown champion and first 
since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Selway credited quick action to ``stabilize Charismatic's  
physiological condition following the injury'' as being of critical 
importance in the horse's survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Chris Antley also helped by dismounting shortly after the  
finish and lifting the injured leg to relieve the weight on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic has responded well to surgery and to continuing  
treatment. He is expected to remain in his stall for another two to 
three months. Complete healing of the fracture is expected to take 
four to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Although horses with somewhat similar injuries have resumed in  
competition, Charismatic's retirement was considered the most 
prudent course to pursue, Selway said, ``to preserve an invaluable 
gene pool.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 14:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
