<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa UAW Endorsement Discounted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the United Auto Workers discounted  
an early endorsement of Vice President Al Gore for president by the 
union's Iowa affiliate, saying they didn't speak for the parent 
union ``and nobody should think that they do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual rebuke of the Iowa council representing 18,000  
active members by union president Stephen P. Yokich reflected top 
UAW officials' displeasure with the unilateral action as well as 
lingering reticence in labor about the Clinton administration's 
record on trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said the vice president  
was ``working to show the working men and women of the 
international UAW that Al Gore is their candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa UAW endorsed Gore on Sunday, the second show of support  
from organized labor in the key presidential caucus state. The UAW 
event, coming on the heels of an endorsement from Council 61 of the 
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, 
offered Gore important political muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite occasional differences, union leaders have maintained  
friendly relations with the Clinton administration. But former Sen. 
Bill Bradley, Gore's only Democratic challenger, has made inroads 
with many unions, speaking recently to a Teamsters meeting in 
Orlando, Fla., and Service Employees International Union members in 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts saw the Iowa endorsements as a sign that labor was  
ready to put aside its differences with the administration, but 
Yokich's statement and the debate among the leaders of other 
national unions showed that differences remain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the International Executive Board that is empowered to  
make endorsements for candidates for national office following a 
union-wide process of evaluation,'' Yokich said. ``That process is 
anything but finished at this point in time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yokich added that the Iowa council members were ``entitled to  
their opinions,'' but ``a group of less than twenty members in Iowa 
does not speak for the International Executive Board of the union 
and no one should think that they do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a push by some AFL-CIO union leaders to move ahead  
with an early endorsement of Gore has run into resistance from 
several large unions, according to a half-dozen union officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO executive council was considering whether it should  
make a recommendation on an endorsement when it meets in August. If 
it does, the recommendation would be acted upon by the biennial 
convention in October. 
</P>
<P>
	But several unions, including the UAW, the Teamsters and several  
building trades unions, are angry about Clinton administration 
policies on trade and are reticent to play such a big political 
chit so early. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too soon to say. There's a lot of discussion going on  
right now,'' said AFL-CIO spokeswoman Denise Mitchell, adding that 
August was considered the earliest possible date for action, not a 
deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell said the federation would poll union members over the  
next month to gauge their estimations of the candidates and key 
legislative issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really need to know what members are thinking,'' she said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
