<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympian Boxers Lack Admiration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two things Fernando Vargas and Raul Marquez have  
in common are fights with Yory Boy Campas and Olympic appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Appreciation for each other's abilities is noticeably lacking.  
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps it will increase when they fight July 17 at Caesars  
Tahoe in Stateline, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vargas is taking me lightly; he says `it's the easiest fight  
of my life,''' said the 27-year-old Marquez, a 1992 Olympian, who 
lost the IBF junior middleweight title when he was stopped on cuts 
by Yory Boy Campas in the eighth round Dec. 6, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't take no fighter lightly,'' said the 21-year-old  
Vargas, a 1996 Olympian, who won the IBF 154-pound title when he 
stopped Campas in the seventh round Dec. 12, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vargas also said of Marquez, ``He's not an intelligent  
southpaw. Southpaws are usually crafty and hard to hit. He's not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marquez countered by saying, ``The longer it goes, the better  
for me. He doesn't know how to relax. He has average speed and 
decent power. He's got a lot of knockouts but some of those fights 
were stopped kind of early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the Campas who Vargas beat ``wasn't the same guy  
who fought me. The hunger wasn't in him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters are training at Big Bear, Calif., it was from  
there that they were interviewed by telephone Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vargas (16-0, 16 knockouts), of Oxnard Calif., will be making  
his second defense of the 154-pound title. He has talked a lot 
about fighting WBC welterweight champion Oscar De La Hoya, but on 
Friday he said, ``My goal is to unify the junior middleweight 
division, that's all. If he moves up to my division, fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marquez (30-1, 20 knockouts), of Houston, won the title in 1997,  
and he defended it twice before losing to Campas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Campas fight was one I should never taken,'' said Marquez,  
who said he received 70-stitches worth of cuts in his eyebrows 
while outpointing Keith Mullings in a defense Sept. 13, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hadn't trained (for Campas),'' Marquez said. ``In the second  
round my eyes swelled up bad because the cuts hadn't healed well. I 
tried to go for a knockout, but by the eighth round my face was 
messed up, and they stopped the fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he took the Campas fight, Marquez said he got his  
biggest purse because the match was part of a pay-per-view 
doubleheader on which WBC welterweight champion Oscar De La Hoya 
outpointed Hector Camacho. 
</P>
<P>
	But there also was the matter of ego.  
</P>
<P>
	``I got a lot of heat from the Mullings fight,'' Marquez said.  
``A lot of people thought I lost.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
