<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Endorses Forbes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conservative leader Paul Weyrich endorsed  
presidential candidate Steve Forbes on Friday, giving the 
Republican hopeful a boost in his bid to court voters from the 
party's right wing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other candidates appear to be more closely aligned with the  
social issues positions I have taken, but in the end what matters 
is who can deliver on these issues if elected,'' Weyrich said in a 
statement given to The Associated Press. ``I have concluded that 
Forbes is in a better position to deliver than even the most 
ardently committed social conservative candidates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weyrich runs the Free Congress Foundation, a conservative  
Washington think tank. His endorsement gives Forbes' conservative 
campaign a measure of credibility, though it does not come with a 
grass-roots political operation that could translate the backing to 
votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Several GOP candidates --including Gary Bauer, Pat Buchanan and  
New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith -- are competing against Forbes for 
support of social conservatives. Those voters viewed Forbes 
skeptically during his failed 1996 campaign, but he spent the next 
two years shoring up his conservative credentials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Economic and social conservatives are clearly rallying behind  
Forbes to take on the establishment candidate, George W. Bush,'' 
said Forbes spokesman Greg Mueller. The Texas governor is far ahead 
of his GOP rivals in money, endorsements and the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyrich, who coined the phrase ``moral majority,'' helped make  
social conservatives a force in the Republican Party. He had a hand 
in creating the Heritage Foundation think tank and the Christian 
Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyrich shocked the conservative community in February by  
writing an open letter in which he announced ``politics has 
failed'' and that ``we probably have lost the cultural war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His endorsement of Forbes comes at a time when the conservative  
candidates are vying to emerge as an alternative to the more 
moderate Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe it is important that voters in the primary have a  
choice other than George Bush and I believe that Steve Forbes is in 
a position to offer that choice,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Forbes loses the nomination and Smith carries out a threat to  
bolt the GOP, Weyrich said he would join ranks with the senator. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm committed to Steve Forbes for the distance, but if the  
Republicans give us the same sort of ticket that we've had over the 
last several elections and if Steve Forbes does not get the 
nomination and if Bob Smith runs as an independent, I will end up 
supporting Bob Smith,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
