<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lamar Alexander Promotes Tax Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEREDITH, N.H. (AP) -- Lamar Alexander said Friday that his  
Republican presidential rivals may have raised more money than he 
has, but he is doing what really matters -- talking to voters on a 
personal level about issues important to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander met with small-business owners to promote the tax  
reforms that are central to his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, he took aim at the Republican front-runner,  
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, lagging in the polls and in fund raising, said  
there's no evidence Bush, ``a one-time governor,'' is ready to be 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was elected last year to his second term as governor of  
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, a former two-term governor of Tennessee and a  
one-time U.S. secretary of education, said the Texas governorship 
``is largely a ceremonial position. It's the weakest governorship 
in the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready to be president,'' he said. ``He's completely  
untested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In California this week, Bush defended himself against criticism  
about his qualifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in positions where I've made decisions in my life,''  
he said. ``I know how to decide things, and I also know how to 
bring people together. I don't know how I know how to do it, I just 
know how to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander spoke two days after Bush disclosed raising a record  
$36.25 million in the first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, the $2 million that Alexander reported raising was  
about $500,000 short of what aides said last month they expected 
and less than half of what they had hoped to raise by now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush and Mr. (Steve) Forbes have won the money  
primary. I'm going to try to win the New Hampshire primary,'' 
Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Bush) has got his chartered jet named Great Expectations,  
I've got a borrowed bus named Exceeding Expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander was in Meredith to listen to the concerns of the  
business owners, principally about heavy taxes and burdensome 
regulations. He wants to triple tax deductions for dependent 
children to $8,000, abolish inheritance taxes and reduce capital 
gains and income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said government regulations on business should expire  
periodically so lawmakers would be forced to determine whether they 
were justified. Now, regulations just pile up on each other, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Alexander's comments resonated with his audience.  
Several took campaign bumper stickers and the group surprised him 
with an early birthday cake. Alexander turns 59 on Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
