<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid To Pay $1.1M in Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp., the nation's  
third-largest drugstore chain, will pay $1.1 million in fines to 
settle a lawsuit that claimed its stores sold expired condoms, 
infant formula and other products. 
</P>
<P>
	The chain also agreed to post notices at its 640 California  
stores telling customers who had purchased expired goods that they 
could be reimbursed or given replacements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to do our utmost to ensure the integrity of  
our products,'' the Camp Hill, Pa.-based company said Friday in a 
statement. ``Selling expired merchandise is not something that Rite 
Aid, or any retailer, would knowingly allow to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	District attorneys from three California counties and one city  
filed the suit last month, after investigators found more than 200 
outdated products in about 50 of the chain's stores in California. 
Some of the condoms were four years past their expiration date. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had no reports of infants falling ill from outdated  
products, but they cautioned that formulas lose their nutritional 
value over time, and that condoms and spermicides lose their 
effectiveness after their expiration dates pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid said its policy had always been to pull items off  
shelves 30 days before they expire; after the investigators' 
disclosure, that was changed to 60 days. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
