<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes at Record High 11,139.24 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose to new records today as a strong  
employment report fed investors' enthusiasm and capped a week of 
extraordinary strength on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading, the Dow was up 72.82 at 11,139.24,  
easily topping its previous record close of 11,107.19, set May 13. 
The Dow rose 586.68 points for the week, a gain of more than 5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also moved higher.  
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose as the Labor Department said American businesses  
created a total of 268,000 new jobs in June, with all industries 
except manufacturing and mining posting solid gains. The increase 
in jobs was slightly stronger than economists expected, and average 
hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, increased by 
3.7 percent in June compared to a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In a less buoyant market, the report could have punctured  
investors' enthusiasm. Higher wages can drag earnings down because 
labor costs account for most of consumer prices. They also raise 
the specter of another increase in interest rates following this 
week's modest hike by the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bond market, which often sets the tone for stocks, was  
unmoved by the jump in wages. 
</P>
<P>
	``The markets blew right past it,'' said Ricky Harrington,  
technical analyst with Wachovia Securities in Charlotte, N.C. The 
yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond remained steady at 6.0 
percent, setting the stage for a sixth consecutive gain in the 
stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington said investors continue to welcome strong economic  
news, discounting the fact that it could translate into inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this stage, we've got strong momentum and a real mania for  
stocks,'' he said. ``It would take awfully bad news to change 
investor psychology and turn them away from this market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cyclical stocks, which perform best during times of economic  
expansion, led the Dow today. International Paper and Minnesota 
Mining and Manufacturing rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks contributed to gains on the Nasdaq, with  
industry leaders Cisco Systems and Sun Microsystems up strongly. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Farr, president of Farr, Miller &AMP; Washington, a  
Washington, D.C.-based financial consulting firm, said he believes 
the market gained enough support from the Fed's moderate 
interest-rate increase to rise still higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has endured several bouts of fear,'' he said.  
``Each one has tested the resolve of the bull market. But every one 
has been for emotional reasons, not for rational ones.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 09:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Moves Above Record High Close / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
		   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks pushed higher today, lifting the Dow  
Jones industrial average and other market barometers into record 
territory as investors responded to a strong government jobs 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow was up 44.32 at 11,110.74, just  
above its May 13 record close of 11,107.19. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also moved higher.  
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 5.72 to 1,386.68, and the  
Nasdaq composite index rose 20.82 to 2,727.08. Both indexes set 
closing highs on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose as a government jobs report showed a healthy labor  
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that employment at American  
businesses accelerated sharply last month with a total of 268,000 
new jobs created with all industries except manufacturing and 
mining posting solid gains. The increase in jobs was slightly 
stronger than economists expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,  
increased by 3.7 percent in June, compared to a year ago. Higher 
wages can drag earnings down because labor costs account for most 
of consumer prices. They also raise the specter of another increase 
in interest rates following this week's modest hike by the Federal 
Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bond market, which often sets the tone for stocks, was  
unmoved by the jump in wages, as the yield on the benchmark 30-year 
Treasury bond remained steady at 6.0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobs report also found unemployment rates remained near  
their historic lows during June. The jobless rate edged up 0.1 
percent to 4.3 percent as U.S. factories continued to shed jobs. It 
still remains near the lowest levels in three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	International Paper, up 1 3/4 at 51 1/2 and Minnesota Mining and  
Manufacturing, 1 3/8 at 88 9/16, led the Dow higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks fed gains on the Nasdaq, with Cisco Systems up  
1 3/4 at 66 1/8 and Sun Microsystems up 2 3/16 at 70 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 290.44 million 
shares, down from Thursday's pace. Volume was light ahead of the 
three-day Independence Day weekend. U.S. Markets will be closed 
Monday in observance of the holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.84 at 653.17, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 7.57 at 802.52. 


  	   	
</P>
