<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 10:26:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Face Brazil in Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- Brazil vs. the United States. Fourth of  
July. Stanford, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Again.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the two nations met at Stanford Stadium in the men's  
World Cup. Brazil won 1-0 and went on to win the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years later, the same countries, the same venue and the  
same red-white-and-blue date are the setting for Sunday's semifinal 
in the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Only this time, the United States will be the favorite.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every game is a different story. Sometimes the same story  
repeats,'' Brazilian coach Wilson de Oliveira said. ``We hope this 
story repeats. We have a dream. If we can emulate what happened in 
this stadium five years ago, our dream will come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams advanced with one-goal victories Thursday night. With  
President Clinton and his family among the 54,642 fans at Jack Kent 
Cooke Stadium, defenders Brandi Chastain and Joy Fawcett scored off 
corner kicks to rally the U.S. team from a 2-1 halftime deficit in 
a 3-2 victory over Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we'll have to play better against Brazil,'' said coach  
Tony DiCicco, whose team overcame its first real test after winning 
its three first-round games by a combined scored of 13-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil blew a 3-0 halftime lead against Nigeria before Sissi  
scored the first sudden-death overtime goal in Women's World Cup 
history. The midfielder's 22-yard free kick, her tournament-high 
seventh goal, won the game 4-3 in the 104th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the game I turned into an old man,'' de Oliveira said.  
``But after the game I became a young man again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results mean all four teams have qualified for the 2000  
Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The doubleheader was evidence of the unexpected surge in  
popularity of the biggest all-women's sports event ever. Extra 
seats were made available to meet demand, and the crowd was late 
arriving because of a 20-mile backup to the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, also arriving late, watched the second half of the  
U.S.-Germany match from a luxury box with wife Hillary, daughter 
Chelsea, two of Chelsea's friends and Health and Human Services 
Secretary Donna Shalala. 
</P>
<P>
	After the match, the presidential party met the U.S. team in the  
locker room. The players chanted ``Clinton'' as he posed for a 
group picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told us what an inspiration the team was, coming from  
behind,'' midfielder Julie Foudy said. ``I told him thanks for 
coming, it makes a ton of difference for this team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Down 2-1, the Americans tied the score in the 49th minute when  
Chastain volleyed in Mia Hamm's corner kick. 
</P>
<P>
	Fawcett, who almost never joins the attack -- she had 18 goals in  
140 international games heading into the World Cup -- scored the 
game-winner in the 66th when she was positioned perfectly for a 
side header past the outstretched arm of goalkeeper Silke 
Rottenberg. The corner kick came from Shannon MacMillan, who had 
entered the game seconds earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	As it has the whole tournament, the U.S. team came out sloppy.  
Chastain, who later would sustain a mile ankle sprain, played a 
loose ball back to goalkeeper Briana Scurry. Scurry wasn't 
expecting it, and the result was an own goal for Germany in the 
fifth minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffeny Milbrett's low shot tied the game in the 16th minute,  
but Germany regained the lead in injury time when Bettina Wiegmann 
made a move around Cindy Parlow and sent a 22-yard rocket into the 
top left corner of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	That prompted an urgent halftime talk from U.S. captain Carla  
Overbeck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carla said that everything we done in this lifetime comes down  
to these 45 minutes,'' Foudy said. ``We had 45 minutes to make a 
difference. That's it and we had to leave everything on the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the second game, Sissi played a part in all four Brazilian  
goals. Her free kick started a sequence that led to Cidinha's score 
in the fourth minute, and her chip from the corner of the penalty 
box was headed home by Cidinha at the far post in the 22nd. 
</P>
<P>
	Sissi then played the ball to Nene for a 40-yard chip that  
sailed over goalkeeper Ann Chiejine's head from the right flank in 
the 35th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria rallied with goals from Prisca Emeafu, Nkiru Okosieme  
and Nkechi Egbe before Sissi's ``Golden Goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, Sissi is the queen of soccer,'' de Oliveira said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
