<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shipbuilder Hit With More Citations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Navy shipbuilder Avondale Industries Inc. was  
hit Friday with federal citations and $180,000 in proposed 
penalties for improperly maintaining worker illness and injury 
records at its shipyard 
</P>
<P>
	The citations were the second set of alleged safety violations  
issued by Occupational Safety and Health Administration as part of 
its eight-month investigation of Avondale stemming from union 
complaints that the yard is peppered with safety violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metal Trades Council has been involved in a years-long fight  
to represent Avondale workers. 
</P>
<P>
	OSHA said the citations were for three willful violations:  
</P>
<P>
	-- The agency said it found more than 700 cases of improper  
recording of injuries and illnesses when it reviewed a random 
sample of almost 3,500 employee medical files. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Avondale did not provide required supplementary records for  
injuries and illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The company did not provide OSHA access to employee medical  
records. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not merely a 'paperwork' violation,'' said U.S. Labor  
Secretary Alexis M. Herman. ``Accurate records of injuries and 
illnesses are necessary to pinpoint hazards causing injuries and 
illnesses and to correct them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement, Avondale said it believes the inspection  
demonstrated that its record-keeping system is ``99 percent'' 
accurate and blamed the dispute with OSHA over a difference of 
interpreting federal guidelines over record-keeping. The company 
earlier said the disputed medical records involved contract workers 
and are private documents maintained by contract workers' 
employers. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, OSHA issued 60 safety citations and proposed $537,000  
in fines against the company for alleged violations including 
faulty scaffolding, unsafe guard rails, open holes and other 
dangerous conditions. Avondale has appealed those citations, saying 
inspectors conducted a biased investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale has agreed to be acquired by Litton Industries Inc. for  
$529 million. Avondale stockholders are now voting on the deal and 
the results are expected to be announced on July 29. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
