<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Olympian Dies in His Sleep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARY, N.C. (AP) -- A 14-year-old Special Olympian from Egypt died  
in his sleep, probably from an epileptic seizure, said officials of 
the Special Olympics World Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohamed Abdul Baset Barin, a volleyball player, was pronounced  
dead Thursday after his coach called paramedics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is tragic, it is saddening, but it was also, sadly,  
unavoidable,'' said Tim Shriver, president of Special Olympics Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy performed Thursday by the state medical examiner's  
office suggested Barin's death was related to epilepsy. But since 
he died in his sleep, examiners were not certain, said Dr. Tim 
Taft, chairman of a medical advisory committee for the games. Taft 
said Barin was taking medication for his disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know he had an underlying seizure disorder,'' Taft said.  
``That is the most likely explanation for what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Freddoso, chief executive of the Games Organizing Committee,  
said Barin watched volleyball competition Wednesday night before 
returning to his room on the University of North Carolina campus in 
Chapel Hill. He could not be awakened. 
</P>
<P>
	The death is the second at the 10th Special Olympics World  
Summer Games, which opened last Saturday and will end Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A volunteer died of a heart attack after completing his shift at  
the opening ceremonies. And four athletes -- two each from the 
Dominican Republic and Morocco -- were missing after leaving their 
delegations. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the two from Morocco was found in good condition Thursday  
night in Washington, D.C. Authorities don't suspect foul play with 
the missing athletes, who are described as highly functional 
mentally retarded men. 
</P>
<P>
	About 7,000 athletes from more than 150 countries are  
participating in the games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
