<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Lithuania To Go To Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Russia beat Germany 74-70 and Lithuania crushed  
Turkey 80-56 at the European Championships today and both winners 
qualified for next year's Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The top five teams will join Yugoslavia in Sydney. Sixth place  
is enough to qualify because Yugoslavia, which is assured to 
finishing among the top four, had already clinched a trip to 
Australia by winning the world title last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy, Spain and France also qualified by reaching the  
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and Lithuania will play for fifth place, while Germany  
play Turkey for seventh place. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians' victory today over Germany was led by Igor  
Koudeline, who scored 19 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Yevgeny Kissourine came through with a 3-point play and Zakhar  
Pashutin, a guard who had only one point in the first half, made a 
couple of key baskets in the closing minutes to assure the Russian 
victory. The game matched two losing quarterfinalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Two American-based players led Germany. Forward Dirk Nowitzki of  
the Dallas Mavericks had 15 points and forward Ademola Okujala of 
North Carolina had 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Lithuania quickly pulled away against a Turkish team hobbled by  
several injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Led by Arvydas Sabonis, the Portland Trail Blazers center, the  
Lithuanians dominated under the boards and were shooting over 60 
percent as they built up a 32-point lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabonis had 13 points in 19 minutes. Forward Virginijus  
Praskevicius, who plays league basketball in Turkey, had a 
game-high 16 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Lithuania was considered a gold-medal contender, but was upset  
by Spain in the quarterfinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
