<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bald Eagle Soon Off Endangered List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Once near extinction, the American bald eagle  
is ``now back from the brink, thriving in virtually every state of 
the union,'' President Clinton declared today at a White House 
celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced a proposal to remove the majestic bird from  
the endangered species list after a three decade effort to protect 
it. A final decision is expected in July 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to think of a better way to celebrate the birth of a  
nation than to celebrate the rebirth of our national symbol,'' the 
president said on the eve of the Independence Day weekend. ``The 
return of the bald eagle is a fitting cap to a century of 
environmental stewardship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On stage with Clinton was ``Challenger,'' a 10-year-old male  
bald eagle cared for by the National Foundation to Protect 
America's Eagles. ``Challenger'' was blown from a wild nest as a 
baby and experienced too much human contact at a young age to be 
able to survive in the wild. The bird screeched during the 
president's remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe it or not,'' Clinton said, ``Ben Franklin wanted our  
national symbol to be a turkey. The press would be having a field 
day with that to the present day, wouldn't they?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even when removed from the endangered species list, the bald  
eagle will be protected by two laws: the Migratory Bird Treaty Act, 
which prohibits the taking, killing, possession, transportation and 
importation of migratory birds, and the Bald and Golden Eagle 
Protection Act, which bans the taking, possession, transportation, 
export and import of a bald or golden eagle, alive or dead. 
</P>
<P>
	The bald eagle, named America's national bird by the Continental  
Congress in 1782, once thrived, with as many as a half million 
eagles soaring the skies of North America. But by 1963, only 417 
breeding pairs remained in the lower 48 states as a result of 
hunting, loss of prey and habitat and the widespread use of the 
pesticide DDT. 
</P>
<P>
	With the banning of DDT in 1972 and the passage of the  
Endangered Species Act a year later, the bald eagle began making a 
dramatic recovery. Today, there are 5,800 breeding pairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used today's ceremony to call on Congress to approve his  
Lands Legacy initiative, which would provide permanent funding of 
at least $1 billion a year to protect wildlife habitat, farms, 
urban parks and natural treasures across America. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, with recovery well under way, the eagle was  
upgraded from endangered to threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I am pleased to announce that the U.S. Fish and  
Wildlife Service is taking the first step to remove the American 
bald eagle from the endangered species list,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is proposing that the eagle  
be declared fully recovered, with final action due in one year to 
remove it from federal protection under the Endangered Species Act. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
