<DOCNO> APW19990702.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 09:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tips for Mixing Money and Marriage / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The bride is a saver; the groom is a spender.  
She prefers bonds and CDs; he likes stocks and options. 
</P>
<P>
	Balanced checkbook. Overdrawn.  
</P>
<P>
	On-time payments. Late fees.  
</P>
<P>
	Should they call the whole thing off? Hardly.  
</P>
<P>
	But investment advisers accustomed to seeing client couples with  
widely varying views on finances say it's crucial for those tying 
the knot to discuss those differences and how to deal with them 
early on -- as unromantic as it might seem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Failure to plan is probably the biggest reason why people get  
themselves into financial trouble,'' says Larry Elkin, a money 
manager and accountant from Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best advice I can give people just starting out today is  
to talk. You've got to consciously arrive at a set of goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Money is a means for arriving at one's goals, like starting a  
family, running a business, buying a home or traveling. 
</P>
<P>
	And to that end, financial experts offer a few basic  
suggestions: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Discuss your financial status. Although most couples don't  
like talking about money, it's important both parties disclose as 
much as they can about themselves financially -- current earnings, 
potential inheritance and debts. 
</P>
<P>
	One spouse isn't responsible for another's past debts, but his  
or her liabilities and spending habits could crimp future financial 
plans. Remember, you're marrying your finances, too. 
</P>
<P>
	And while you're at it, those money ``personalities'' should be  
discussed since a clash of attitudes and opinions can often put 
more of a strain on a marriage than lack of money. You may need to 
plan around your differences or similarities. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Create a budget. That determines how much money flows in and  
out of your household. Besides living expenses, it should include 
something for savings and investments as well as an emergency cash 
reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Ideally, two-income couples should try to build a budget so that  
one salary can handle all current expenses, says Elkin. The second 
can be saved or invested for important things like a down payment 
on a house or continuing education for a spouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can learn to live on less than you're making right from  
the beginning, the chances are you'll establish a pattern of saving 
and investing that bodes very well for financial success down the 
line,'' Elkin says. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Work out money management. Determining how you're going to  
combine financial resources can be touchy, especially with older, 
more established couples who are used to living on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	The Institute of Certified Financial Planners suggests couples  
have individual accounts for personal use as well as a joint 
account for household expenses, and that one spouse be in charge of 
paying the monthly bills so nothing falls through the cracks. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Keep debt at bay. If you had to borrow for your wedding or  
honeymoon, pay off those debts as soon as possible. You'll save a 
bundle on interest charges in the long run. 
</P>
<P>
	In the future, each spouse should try to avoid overspending by  
sticking to the planned budget. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Review insurance, title assets. New life insurance, or a  
larger policy, may be in order since marriage typically creates 
financial dependency. 
</P>
<P>
	You'll need to draft or update a will to reflect a change in  
marital status. Also, you'll need to change the beneficiaries of 
your insurance policies and retirement plans. 
</P>
<P>
	How you title property should be given careful thought. Most  
couples routinely put everything in both names, which works well 
for those with limited assets by allowing quick transfer of 
property to a surviving partner. But as couples accumulate wealth, 
it may not make sense, especially for those in second marriages 
with children from a prior marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Seek outside help. Financial professionals can help couples  
create a stable foundation on which to build a marriage. There are 
advisers who can help with everything from investing for the future 
to passing your estate on to your heirs. 
</P>
<P>
	If you can't afford one, there's a variety of free information  
available over the Internet, and book stores are crammed with 
personal finance publications to check out once you've settled into 
a new life together. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no need to read them on your honeymoon. There are  
better things to do,'' says Elkin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
