<DOCNO> APW19990702.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts: Brazil Not Healthy Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The long roller-coaster ride touched  
off by the 1997 Asian crisis seems to have subsided on Brazilian 
stock markets, but analysts warn the country is still not out of 
the woods. 
</P>
<P>
	For the last four months, the Bovespa index of the Sao Paulo  
Stock Exchange -- Latin America's largest -- has averaged a healthy 
11,300 points but investors still remain cautious, worried about 
the government's fiscal health. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the Asian crisis erupted in July of 1997, no one believed  
it could threaten other economies,'' recalled Odair Abate, the 
chief economist at Lloyds Bank in Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis took a while to reach Brazil and when it did, ``it  
hit us with a vengeance,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bovespa index reached a high of about 14,000 points in  
August 1997 and was still around 12,000 points when it finally 
succumbed to pressures overseas in October, finally hitting 7,800 
on Nov. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic struck, and investors pulled their money from Brazil. The  
Central Bank spent $10 billion to shore up the real and interest 
rates skyrocketed to 43 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A fiscal austerity package announced by the government in late  
1997 breathed life back into Brazilian stocks, pushing the Bovespa 
back up to the 12,000 range. But the euphoria was short-lived. 
After Russia defaulted on some of its debt in August 1998, the 
market was back below 5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	With the help of a $41.5 billion rescue package, stitched  
together by the International Monetary Fund, and a currency 
devaluation that made share prices cheaper in dollar terms, the 
markets have slowly inched back up. The Bovespa closed Friday at 
11,835. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent market movement hasn't convinced Abate that all is  
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``While in nominal terms share prices have made a significant  
recovery, in dollar terms they are still some 20 percent below 
their pre-Asian crisis levels, '' he said. ``The recovery needs 
more consistency and until then, the market can still fall prey to 
an interest rate hike in the United States or to economic 
uncertainties in Argentina or some other South American country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are still worried about ongoing budget and trade  
deficits, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In May the primary budget deficit came to $454 million instead  
of an expected surplus of $284 million. In the first half of the 
year, Brazil's trade deficit totaled $623 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also are casting a wary eye on interest rates, ``which  
have been substantially reduced, but which are still far too high, 
straightjacketing the economy,'' said Thomas Taterka, head trader 
of Sao Paulo's Banco Cidade. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, inflation is under control and shouldn't be more than 10  
percent this year,'' he said. ``But this is being accomplished by a 
sharp drop in economic activity and unemployment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Official figures show the nation's unemployment rate at close to  
8 percent. But in Sao Paulo, Latin America's largest city, labor 
unions say the jobless rate is 20 percent of the work force -- more 
than 1.7 million people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
