<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Off on Weather News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Prices of grain and soybean futures contracts  
finished sharply lower Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade as 
speculation grew that the fall harvest would bring in bumper crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Although temperatures are expected to soar into the upper 90s in  
Midwest growing regions over the next few days, traders did not 
expect the heat wave would result in significant damage to the 
young crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have seesawed over the past few sessions as market  
participants tried to evaluate the effect the hot, dry weather will 
have. But some forecasters are calling for a return of normal 
temperatures later next week and say there is ample soil moisture 
to protect roots. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures also were pressured by speculation that production  
could soar above 10 billion bushels if the crop makes it through 
the crucial pollination period without significant damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans begin their flowering period next month, and there  
currently appears no threat to reducing what is expected to be 
bumper production. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by expectations for active  
harvesting of the winter wheat crop over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery fell 7 cents to $2.51 3/4 a bushel;  
September corn fell 6 cents to $2.02 1/4 a bushel; September oats fell 
3 cents to $1.08 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 12 1/2 cents to 
$4.34 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and lean hog futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle and pork bellies advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose 0.13 cent to 62.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 0.35 cent to 76.32 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell 0.03 cent to 44.57 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
rose 0.50 cent to 37.05 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
