<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles claim Jim Corsi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles signed right-hander Jim  
Corsi to a minor league contract Friday in the latest attempt to 
bolster their struggling bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Corsi, designated for assignment by the Boston Red Sox on June  
15, will report to Triple-A Rochester on Monday. Corsi went 1-2 
with a 5.25 ERA in 23 games with the Red Sox this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's see if he can throw the ball over the plate and get some  
people out,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said. ``That's what you 
want to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles also announced that they were put right-hander Ricky  
Bones on the 15-day disabled list with fatigue in his right arm and 
called up Gabe Molina from Rochester. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles announced last week that they were recalling Molina  
and sending down Rocky Coppinger. But after Molina arrived in 
Baltimore, the Orioles rescinded the move because Coppinger would 
have had to pass through waivers to be demoted. 
</P>
<P>
	Corsi will likely get a shot soon to contribute to the Orioles'  
bullpen. Baltimore relievers have a 10.50 ERA in 21 innings over 
the last seven games. They lead the majors with 18 blown saves and 
have a major league-worst 5.96 ERA entering Friday's game against 
the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of seeing defensive pitching,'' Miller said. ``We  
have too many guys who are trying to miss bats instead of going 
after hitters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's frustrations boiled over Thursday in Toronto, after his  
relievers lost all three games to the Blue Jays. There were reports 
that a major shakeup would happen with the team this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	All that has gone on so far was a team meeting before Friday's  
game. The Orioles have lost eight straight following a stretch in 
which they won 11 of 12 and are in last place in the AL East. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message will be to go after guys,'' Miller said. ``Let's  
be aggressive and if a guy gets a hit, he gets a hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mindset. When you're pitching good you don't care who  
the batter is. You just throw strike one and adjust from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said he expects to use Rocky Coppinger this weekend in  
New York. Coppinger, who has an 8.31 ERA in 17 1-3 innings, did not 
appear against the Blue Jays. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
