<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 12:00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Gives Clinton No Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When President Bush prevailed in Iraq, his  
popularity rating soared to 91 percent. By contrast, President 
Clinton got no such bounce in the polls from the Kosovo campaign, 
even though his goals were achieved without a single U.S. combat 
casualty. 
</P>
<P>
	The American people paid much more attention to the Gulf War and  
seemed to give scant applause to the outcome of the Clinton-led 
campaign against Serbian forces clearing Kosovo of its ethnic 
Albanian population. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks after he led the 78-day NATO bombing campaign in  
Yugoslavia to a successful conclusion, Clinton still is waiting for 
some type of general acknowledgment that he achieved what he set 
out to achieve, and did it without committing American ground 
troops, the skeptics notwithstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	The astronomical leap in public opinion that his predecessor  
enjoyed at the end of the 1991 Gulf War simply is not Clinton's 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's approval numbers hover near the 50 percent mark. This  
situation has so puzzled the White House that it has given up 
trying to spin the success in Clinton's favor and decided to act as 
if the lack of recognition is no big deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought of some answers and you know what? None of them are  
meaningful,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``He saw it 
through and he's satisfied we did the right thing. I will leave it 
to others why that was so hard for many people in this town to 
accept.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to an ABC News poll conducted after the bombings 56  
percent of surveyed Americans approved of the way Clinton handled 
the conflict in Kosovo, and 40 percent disapproved. A bipartisan 
Battleground Poll released last week showed 49 percent approved of 
Clinton's Kosovo leadership and 43 percent disapproved. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's approval rating dipped into the 50 percent range  
during the Kosovo bombing, lower than it stood during his 
impeachment ordeal. His rating remains in the 50s in most polls, 
although in early June it climbed back to 60 percent in one poll. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, President Reagan's approval rating was 46 percent  
in October 1983, when he sent U.S. forces into Grenada to retrieve 
650 American medical students following the assassination of 
leftist Prime Minister Maurice Bishop. It climbed to 53 percent a 
month later and a point higher the next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton says he does not think there is a message inherent in  
his lowered poll standings. He identified himself with Abraham 
Lincoln, who once said during the Civil War that 10,000 angels 
swearing he was right would not make any difference if he had been 
wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have tried to do what I think is right for my country  
here,'' Clinton said. ``The public and the members of the other 
party and others ... can react however they like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, one aide who worked closely with Clinton on Kosovo  
said the sentiment in the White House is that Americans feel good 
about ``our moral stand'' and that bodes well for Clinton's legacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Several factors pushed the Kosovo conflict to the edge of  
Americans' minds. It produced no identifiable leaders, as the Gulf 
War produced Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf and gave new prominence to 
Gen. Colin Powell. Americans were ambivalent about the reasons the 
United States got involved. And the nation's attention was suddenly 
pulled away with the high school shootings in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The war made less difference on Main Street,'' said Stephen  
Hess, presidential scholar at the Brookings Institution. 
``Americans generally lost interest in it, which sort of was a plus 
for the president. It gave him some wiggle room as the air war was 
going on, but the down side was there wasn't much to take credit 
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hess said Clinton also was hurt some by his success in resisting  
pressure for ground troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``All it cost us was money,'' he said. ``With a ground war, an  
awful lot more people would have been committed and a lot more 
attention would have been paid. There were a lot of people in this 
war, in a sense, who never left home. The stealth bomber groups 
left from home and returned for dinner.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
