<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dr. J: Tennis Phenom Is My Daughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Alexandra Stevenson plays tennis with a  
vengeance and plenty of flair. More than overpowering serves and 
mammoth ground strokes, her game exudes a natural-born talent for 
playing to the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Much like her father, Dr. J.  
</P>
<P>
	Julius Erving, the Basketball Hall of Famer who redefined the  
game with high-flying dunks and charisma, said Friday he is the 
father of the 18-year-old tennis phenom. His statement by telephone 
to The Associated Press came shortly after Stevenson made history 
on another continent, becoming the first female qualifier to 
advance to the Wimbledon semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a momentous day for the young, captivating player from  
California and for Erving, the former Philadelphia 76ers star who 
is now a vice president with the NBA's Orlando Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I acknowledge a relationship with her mother in 1980,'' Erving  
said from his office in Florida. ``My wife, who has known from the 
beginning, and children are aware of this situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``All matters concerning Alexandra since her birth have been  
handled privately through counsel. I am pleased to see Alexandra, 
at 18, doing so well and I applaud her mother's efforts and 
courage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility that Erving was Stevenson's father was raised  
this week when The Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel published a copy of 
her birth certificate. Though it listed her father as Julius 
Winfield Erving II, Erving's legal name, the basketball great 
initially denied being her father. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson has taken Wimbledon by storm with her game and  
presence and also by the controversy that has shadowed her run to 
the semis. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother, Samantha Stevenson, is a free-lance journalist who  
covered the 76ers while Erving starred on the team. She stirred 
Wimbledon with accusations of racism and lesbianism on the WTA Tour 
and with a dispute over prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	Mother and daughter declined comment Friday when asked several  
times about Erving's statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson advanced to the semifinals against Lindsay Davenport  
by beating another qualifier, 16-year-old Jelena Dokic, 6-3, 1-6, 
6-3. She hopped and skipped to the net after the final point, 
clapping with one hand on her racquet strings and curtsying four 
times to the crowd on Court 1. 
</P>
<P>
	An ocean away, Dr. J said: ``I haven't talked to her. I only met  
her once, and she was 3 years old. She was brought to me at a 
basketball clinic at a public school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erving soared higher, hung in the air longer and slam-dunked  
with more style that any player before him. He was Michael Jordan 
before Jordan came along, revolutionizing the game during a 16-year 
career in the ABA and with the Sixers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also the epitome of class off the court -- patient,  
considerate and always gracious to his fans. 
</P>
<P>
	If he was watching his daughter on television, there's no way he  
could have missed her crushing serves at speeds up to 113 mph and 
the way she peppered the court with mighty, one-handed backhands 
that are rare in women's tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	But while millions of other kids who grew up in the '80s  
idolized Dr. J, his own daughter had different ideas. Her idol is 
Pete Sampras, and she learned that devastating backhand from his 
old coach, Pete Fischer. 
</P>
<P>
	Erving said he would make no further comments about Stevenson.  
Asked if he wanted to meet her again, Erving said, ``I think it's 
probably her call. I've discussed this with my wife and children. 
Of course, I'd be open to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erving and wife Turquoise have been married since 1972 and have  
four children. He said he has been supporting Alexandra Stevenson 
financially. 
</P>
<P>
	News of his statement swept Philadelphia, where he is still  
respected and beloved. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a recent tabloid headline screamed, ``Dr. Dad,'' and  
Erving's story led newscasts on radio and television. Many radio 
callers expressed disappointment that Erving's only contact with 
his daughter had been through lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The 49-year-old Erving has been successful in business since  
leaving the NBA in 1987. Long gone is the big Afro from his playing 
days; his executive demeanor is accented by prim eyeglasses, 
pinstriped suits and closely cropped, slicked-back hair that is 
streaked with gray. 
</P>
<P>
	He is co-owner of Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co., and had a  
stake in Garden State Cable, which has a business relationship with 
Comcast, another cable company. He also worked for NBC as an NBA 
analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Erving said he hoped coming forward would ease the distractions  
that have shadowed Stevenson's run at Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand they are being besieged because she won her match  
today,'' Erving said. ``Getting this statement out will help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erving won two championships and two MVP awards in the ABA  
before moving to the NBA. He played 11 seasons for the Sixers, 
winning MVP honors in 1981 and leading Philadelphia to its last 
professional sports championship, in 1983. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
