<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seniors Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) -- The long putts were right on target, but  
several of the short ones traveled as if they had a mind of their 
own. And when he expected a birdie, Hubert Green misfired. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Green still managed to shoot a 5-under-par 67 Friday, good  
for a second-place tie with five players after the opening round of 
the State Farm Senior Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Green had a bogey-free round in which he missed just one  
fairway, but he wasn't nearly as consistent on the greens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made some long putts that I didn't expect to make and missed  
some I should have made,'' said Green, who ranks 40th on the money 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	Green nailed a 35-footer for par on No. 12 but failed to  
capitalize on the four par-5s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't make a birdie on a par-5, which for me is horrible,''  
he said. ``I'm surprised I'm this close to the lead, to tell you 
the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GOLF'S HIS RACKET:* Many years ago, Frank Conner made a bold  
career move. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still paying off, in a big way.  
</P>
<P>
	Conner was a three-time All-American tennis player for Trinity  
(Texas) University in the 1960s when he abruptly abandoned the game 
in favor of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Conner has never won a PGA tournament, and there's no guarantee  
his opening 4-under-par 68 Friday will translate to victory in the 
State Farm Senior Classic. But he's collected more than $2.6 
million as a professional golfer, which is a whole lot more than he 
would have garnered playing tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got married after my junior year, and there really wasn't  
any money in tennis,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Things worked out very nicely for Conner, who is one of only two  
men to have played in the U.S. Open in both tennis and golf 
(Ellsworth Vines is the other). 
</P>
<P>
	He played a fine round of golf Friday, sinking four birdies on  
the back nine after closing the front nine with two straight 
bogeys. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always nice to get off to a good start, especially in a  
54-hole tournament,'' he said. ``I played the back side pretty 
consistently.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OUTTA HERE:* Calvin Peete withdrew from the tournament Friday  
after shooting a 1-over 37 on the front nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Peete, who ranks No. 95 on the money list, cited a sore shoulder  
as the reason for his withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Sigel also withdrew from the tournament, leaving before the  
outset of his round to be with his wife, who is undergoing surgery 
on a herniated disk. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
