<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mars Candy Patriarch Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	McLEAN, Va. (AP) -- Forrest Mars Sr., who created M&AMP;Ms candies  
and built one of the biggest fortunes in America as head of the 
Mars candy empire, has died. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	The reclusive billionaire, one of the richest men in America,  
died of natural causes Thursday night in Miami, said Sharon 
Heffelfinger, a spokeswoman for McLean-based Mars Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	She said no further information would be released.  
</P>
<P>
	The candy giant began in 1911 with Frank C. Mars' small business  
in Tacoma, Wash. In 1940, his son, Forrest, devised a candy modeled 
after a British confection: a circle of chocolate covered with a 
crunchy coating. 
</P>
<P>
	M&AMP;Ms -- promoted, as every Baby Boomer knows, as the candy that  
melts in your mouth, not in your hand -- were created as much out of 
meteorological necessity as anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``In those days, the stores didn't have air conditioning, the  
cars didn't have air conditioning, the homes didn't have air 
conditioning,'' then-Mars spokesman Hans Fiuczynski said as the 
candy turned 50 in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The candy, originally sold in paper tubes, came in brown,  
yellow, orange, red, green and violet, later replaced by tan. 
Beginning in 1950, the candies were stamped with the trademark 
``M'' to assure customers they were getting the real thing. Peanut 
M&AMP;Ms came out in 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	The company now has 30,000 employees. Besides M&AMP;Ms, its candy  
brands include Skittles, Milky Way, Dove, Snickers and Three 
Musketeers. Other brands owned by the Mars companies include Uncle 
Ben's Rice, the Kal Kan and Pedigree pet food labels, and Combos, 
Kudos and Twix snack foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Mars' sons, Forrest Jr. and John, are now co-presidents of the  
privately held company. In its rankings of richest Americans last 
fall, Forbes listed Forrest Jr. as 29th richest, Forrest Sr. as 
30th richest, John as 31st richest and Jacqueline Mars Vogel, John 
and Forrest Jr.'s sister, at 33rd, with fortunes estimated at 
around $4 billion each. The family matriarch, Forrest Sr.'s wife 
Audrey, died in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The family became known for its reticence as well as its riches.  
</P>
<P>
	``Mars's assets are often underestimated because the company is  
as loose with information as its McLean, Va., neighbor, the CIA,'' 
Fortune magazine said in 1988 when it dubbed the family the richest 
in America at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	M&AMP;M's were packed in World War II GI rations, served at the 1984  
Olympics in Los Angeles and launched with 31 shuttle flights as of 
1990. The rock band Van Halen's contract called for a backstage 
stash of three pounds of M&AMP;M's -- with all the brown and tan ones 
removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had discontinued red M&AMP;Ms in 1976 because of the  
cancer scare over Red Dye No. 2, although the candy never contained 
the substance. Red M&AMP;M's reappeared in 1987. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 12:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather May Cooperate at Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- The unreliable English weather looks  
like it may cooperate for Saturday's four semifinals and Sunday's 
two finals at Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast from Britain's national weather office calls for a  
sunny, dry Saturday after early morning showers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday is also expected to be mostly dry with a chance of brief  
showers during the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	With one entire day this week washed out by rain, and two others  
virtually washed out, organizers have been forced to schedule all 
four semifinals on Saturday, a day usually reserved for the women's 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	``Monday looks more showery than Saturday or Sunday, so it would  
be good to get the matches in,'' said forecaster Keith Sutlieff. 
  	   	
</P>
