<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Martin knows the difference  
between a fluke and the real thing. He thinks the car he'll drive 
in the Pepsi 400 on Saturday is much better than the one that took 
him to his last restrictor-plate victory, at Talladega 
Superspeedway in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was not a fast car at Talladega,'' Martin said. ``It was  
something we did to change the setup'' of the chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	Essentially, the crew lowered the chassis by a fraction to  
improve aerodynamics. It resulted in a 188.354 mph average and a 
victory in a rare accident-free race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, we took a 25th-place car to first,'' Martin said.  
``We caught everyone else looking the other way and you don't do 
that too often.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after that race, Martin's aerodynamic advantage wore away  
and he again depended on his team to find an edge for his 
restrictor-plate package. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, Martin feels the mission has been accomplished.  
He says the car he will take to the starting line Saturday has more 
horsepower than any he's driven with a restrictor plate. 
</P>
<P>
	``These races with restrictor plates are more a function of  
mechanics and the team,'' Martin said. ``Drivers do have something 
to do with it, but not as much as at Michigan or Charlotte.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MORE QUALIFYING:* Jeff Burton, fourth in the Winston Cup driver  
standings, elected to use a provisional starting slot after engine 
trouble aborted his qualifying effort. 
</P>
<P>
	After stopping in the middle of his qualifying lap Thursday,  
Burton and his crew started working on a race setup Friday and did 
not choose to run in the second day of qualifying. Burton's car was 
on the track during practice Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Craven and Brett Bodine were the big winners in the second  
day of qualifying. Both elected to try to improve their times and 
both finished among the top 36 drivers who get in based on their 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	Craven circled the 2.5-mile trioval at Daytona International  
Speedway at 190.945 mph. Bodine made it in 190.658. 
</P>
<P>
	Dropped from the starting grid was Hut Stricklin, who elected  
not to run again after qualifying 36th on Thursday. He fell back 
two spots. Derrike Cope ran again, but couldn't improve his 
standing of 37th. 
</P>
<P>
	Others using provisionals include Terry Labonte and Kyle Petty.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JARRETT UPDATE:* What grade would points leader Dale Jarrett  
give himself for the first half of the season? An `A,' of course. 
But with room for improvement, especially in qualifying and at the 
beginning of races. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can we get better? Yeah,'' Jarrett said. ``We can be an  
`A-plus' team because we can run better. We can finish fourth and 
fifth without having to come from 25th to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett has started from the outside pole three times this year,  
but his average starting position is 14th. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he has finished out of the top 10 only twice this year.  
The first came in the Daytona 500 when he was involved in a 
multicar accident. The other came in Las Vegas, when he ran out of 
gas toward the end of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been other days where we've struggled but made  
something of it,'' Jarrett said. ``We've known we had a team 
capable of putting together these kinds of races, these kinds of 
streaks and we hope they continue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking his first points title, Jarrett stands 157 points ahead  
of Bobby Labonte. Martin is another nine points back, followed by 
Jeff Burton and two-time defending champion Jeff Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *VIRTUAL VISION:* Thousands of race fans bring radio scanners to  
the track to listen in on conversations between drivers and their 
crews. Sony and the owners of Daytona International Speedway are 
testing a product that could help them take the experience a step 
further. 
</P>
<P>
	They will debut the Sony Glasstron head-mounted video display in  
selected suites at the track Saturday. Viewers will slip on a pair 
of virtual-reality goggles and be able to select in-car views of 
eight drivers. CBS, which is televising the race, will provide the 
in-car camera feeds. 
</P>
<P>
	The service is already available on some satellite systems, but  
never before has it been brought directly to the track via the 
goggles. 
</P>
<P>
	Retailing for about $900, the goggles have been on the market  
for about a year. But they were mainly geared toward travelers, who 
could attach a portable disc player and watch movies. 
</P>
<P>
	If the new program gets good reviews this weekend, International  
Speedway Corporation and Sony will consider renting the goggles to 
fans much the way vendors rent the scanners. 
</P>
<P>
	``The magic of it here is that you actually get a better  
perspective on the race than the driver does,'' said ISC marketing 
vice president Greg Sullivan. ``Because you can see both the big 
picture, what's going on at the track, and what the driver is 
actually experiencing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS:* On the 50th anniversary of the creation of Petty  
Enterprises, Pontiac is coming out with a Grand Prix to commemorate 
each of Richard Petty's record 200 career victories. The 
metallic-blue car will sell for about $50,000. A total of 1,000 -- 
five for each victory -- will be made. ... Buckshot Jones qualified 
for the Pepsi 400, leaving him with a busy weekend. He will depart 
Daytona after the race Saturday for Milwaukee, where he will drive 
in the Busch series DieHard 250 on Sunday. ... StockCar Stocks 
Index Fund announced the launch of a new NASCAR-related mutual 
fund. Shares will be offered on the company's web site, 
www.stockcars.com, at $15 each. Another class of similar stock went 
on sale last October and sells for $19.15 per share after starting 
at $15. ... The track encountered no weather delays Friday. The 
forecast Saturday calls for a 50-percent chance of rain. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
