<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 10:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Investigating Silicon Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The government will investigate a  
newspaper's report that Silicon Valley high-tech companies pay 
Asian immigrants low wages to assemble electronic parts at home, 
possibly violating a number of labor, tax and safety laws. 
</P>
<P>
	State Labor Commissioner Marcy Saunders told the San Jose  
Mercury News that officials plan to meet next week to begin forming 
a task force of state and federal labor officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about possible overtime violations, child labor  
violations and certainly record-keeping violations and violations 
of other laws as well -- tax laws and OSHA and others,'' said George 
Friday, regional administrator at the federal Department of Labor's 
Wage and Hour Division. 
</P>
<P>
	In stories published Sunday and Monday, the Mercury News  
reported that the use of immigrants to make electronic parts at 
home has been widespread in Silicon Valley since the early 1980s. 
At least a dozen local contract manufacturers, ranging from small 
companies to multibillion-dollar giants, have been involved in 
piecework arrangements within the past year, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract companies are often hired by major computer  
companies to produce parts for larger components. 
</P>
<P>
	Those parts are sometimes made or assembled at home, on kitchen  
tables or in garage workshops. The mostly immigrant labor force is 
sometimes paid as little as a penny per component, sometimes barely 
earning minimum wage, and gets no overtime for work that can be 
hazardous, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears the same thing that's happening in the garment and  
agricultural industries is happening in Silicon Valley,'' said Tom 
Rankin, president of the California Labor Federation.''It's the 
misuse of independent contractors to avoid labor laws, to shield 
the real employer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The practice of paying workers for each item made, so-called  
``piecework,'' rather than by the hour isn't necessarily illegal, 
but the pay rate must mesh with minimum wage and overtime laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The government probe will mark the first in Silicon Valley's  
industrial sector in nearly two decades. A 1980 investigation was 
stalled by a lack of Vietnamese-speaking investigators and ended 
when industry leaders and politicians persuaded labor officials to 
let them police the problem themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	In their upcoming probe, investigators will be checking into  
whether pieceworkers should be classified as independent 
contractors or employees, Friday said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe most companies want to comply with the law,'' Friday  
said. ``Some may be ignorant of what's going on at the lower levels 
of their own companies. Others may just see it as an industry 
practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contract manufacturers have built parts and systems for  
companies such as Hewlett-Packard Co., Sun Microsystems Inc. and 
Cisco Systems Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest contracting company, Solectron Corp. of  
Milpitas, said after the newspaper's reports that while it did use 
home assembly some time ago, the practice now is against company 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Solectron said it conducted an internal audit earlier this year,  
found one subcontractor paying workers by the piece, and suspended 
business with that company. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Microsystems, one of Solectron's biggest customers, said it  
``would fully support any actions taken to eliminate the alleged 
labor violations.'' Company officials said they were not aware of 
any such practices by its contractors or subcontractors. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 08:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Rally Across Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets pushed ahead Friday, with  
blue chips in Tokyo and Hong Kong hitting levels unseen since the 
early months of the region's economic crisis and Singapore shares 
climbing to another record finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets were filled with optimism that any interest rate worries  
are out of the way for now, after the U.S. Federal Reserve nudged 
its rates higher on Wednesday but suggested no more monetary 
tightening is likely to be necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index rose 652.44 points, or 4.8 percent,  
to close at 14,184.58, its highest point gain of the year and the 
best finish since Oct. 9, 1997, when the Asian financial crisis was 
starting to be felt in the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. is now less inclined to raise rates, which is helping  
Hong Kong stocks,'' said Patrick Yiu, an analyst at Kingsway SW 
Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's session was Hong Kong's first chance to respond to the  
U.S. interest rate news, after a public holiday on Thursday, so the 
gains were somewhat exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian markets gained further encouragement from Wall Street,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 95.62 points to 
11,066.42 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, Asia's biggest market, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei  
Stock Average rose 71.72 points, or 0.40 percent, closing at 
17,932.47 points. It was the index's highest closing since Sept. 
29, 1997, when it finished at 17,987.21. On Thursday, the Nikkei 
had closed up 331.01 points, or 1.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by continued brisk buying from overseas institutional  
investors, the Nikkei average briefly passed the 18,000-point, 
rising as high as 18,066.28 before falling back on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence in our country's economy is being reflected in  
stocks, and I am happy about it,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu 
Nonaka told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 121.08 yen by  
late afternoon, up 0.32 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 120.78 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore shares inched up to their second record in as many  
days, pushed higher by small investors buying up small-company 
shares. The benchmark Straits Times Index closed at 2,222.45 
points, up 7.70 points, or 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only very selective buying on the blue chips. The  
small stocks are the ones dominating today,'' said broker William 
Pang at G.K. Goh Stockbrokers said. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai blue chips rose 2.2 percent, after giving up about  
half of their early huge gains. The SET index rose 11.56 points to 
533.33. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares bucked the trend and fell, as renewed  
clashes between police and demonstrators kept nervous investors out 
of the market. The JSX Composite Index dropped 2.504 points, or 
0.37 percent, to 670.538. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed sharply higher on strong buying in  
technology stocks. The Weighted Stock Price Index rose 104.72 
points, or 1.2 percent, to 8,572.09. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices showed a modest rally. The  
NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 14.82 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
2,141.92. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher as interest rate worries  
vanished. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 35.42 
points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,578.72. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed higher, with stronger  
prices for commodities giving a lift to resource-based companies. 
The All Ordinaries Index rose 26.8 points, or 0.9 percent, to 
3,028.9. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Sentiment was boosted by the U.S. interest rate news and  
expectations of a speedup in reforms by leading conglomerates. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 13.44 points, or 1.4 
percent, to 933.42. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Prices were buoyed by regional and Wall Street  
gains as well as enthusiasm about local economic prospects. The 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, closed at 
845.62, up 10.31 points, or 1.23 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 08:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
