<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans: US Authorities Taunted Us </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Two of six Cuban refugees who were allowed to  
remain in the United States after frantically trying to swim past 
Coast Guard boats say U.S. authorities later taunted them and made 
them pose with a photo of Fidel Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	Duviel Rodriguez, 17, and Carlos Hernandez Cordova, 29, told  
reporters that before they were taken to Krome Detention Center for 
processing, they were detained by authorities they perceived to be 
U.S. Border Patrol agents. 
</P>
<P>
	```This is our country,' they told us,'' Hernandez said  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees said they were taunted and cursed, then forced to  
look into a camera while holding a photo of the Cuban president. 
</P>
<P>
	When they protested, they were told to hold the photo higher,  
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's outrageous that these people would be forced to take a  
picture with a photo of Fidel Castro,'' said Ninoska Perez 
Castellon, a spokeswoman for the Cuban American National 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	A Border Patrol spokesman said the agency would investigate.  
</P>
<P>
	``It goes without saying that we would not condone and we will  
not tolerate such behavior,'' spokesman Michael Baron said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Coast Guard also is investigating its treatment of the  
six refugees. Television reports showed the Coast Guard blasting 
the men with a hose as they stood in their 14-foot rowboat about 
150 yards from shore. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency then swarmed them as they jumped overboard and swam  
toward shore. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were later freed from custody and allowed to remain in  
the United States following large protests by the Cuban community. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities also were investigating whether the men really came  
all the way from Cuba in their rowboat. Border control agent Dean 
Sinclair said the refugees had numerous inconsistencies in their 
stories, leading investigators to believe their effort may have 
involved a more sophisticated smuggling operation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
