<HEADLINE> Dunlap Named To New AP Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Veteran Associated Press editor Julie Dunlap has  
been appointed assistant international editor, responsible for 
editorial training of AP's staff on the International Desk in New 
York and in bureaus abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunlap has been assistant managing editor/news, primarily in  
charge of AP's Out Front stories aimed at Page 1 and weekend spot 
features. 
</P>
<P>
	Her appointment, effective in August, was announced Thursday by  
AP International Editor Sally Jacobsen. Other assistant 
international editors are David Minthorn, who directs the World 
Services news report for non-U.S. newspapers, and Bryan Brumley, 
who coordinates European coverage from London. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunlap, 50, began her AP career in Philadelphia in 1974 and  
moved to the New York General Desk in 1976. She was national editor 
for the PM newspaper cycle for three years before joining the 
national desk at The New York Times. She returned to the AP as 
enterprise editor in 1980 and was later appointed assistant 
managing editor/features. 
</P>
<P>
	She was assistant metro editor at The Oregonian in Portland from  
1990-1993. In 1993 she assumed her current position with the AP in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunlap is a graduate of the Pennsylvania State University.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
