<HEADLINE> Jamie Koven Begins Sculls Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HENLEY ON THAMES, England (AP) -- Former world sculling champion  
Jamie Koven of Green Village, N.J., scored another dominant victory 
Friday in defense of his Diamond Sculls title at the Henley 
Regatta. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing in the colors of Riverside Boat Club of Boston, Koven  
easily beat Oxford University sculler Matthew Crocker to advance to 
Saturday's semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The other American in the Diamond Sculls, Koven's training  
partner Aquil Abdullah, racing for Potomac Club of Washington D.C., 
lost after damaging his boat. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah was forced to a sudden halt when his sliding seat  
mechanism jammed just three strokes after the start of his race 
against Richard Briscoe of British club Leander. 
</P>
<P>
	Briscoe stopped and offered a re-row, so both scullers went back  
to the start. Abdullah's problem repeated and Briscoe was given the 
result. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. national sculling squad members, racing as the Augusta  
Sculling Center, had a successful day. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``B'' quadruple scull crew opened their campaign in the  
Queen Mother Cup with a 3 3/4 length win over a composite from London 
club Auriol Kensington and Mainzer from Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The lightweight pair of Conal Groom and Steve Tucker moved into  
the semifinal of the Double sculls event with an easy win over 
British club Dart Totnes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Augusta heavyweight double of Ian McGowan and Nick Petersen  
also won easily against another British club, Minerva-Bath. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Augusta Sculling Center ``A'' crew, racing in the Queen  
Mother Cup for quadruple scullers, completed a clean sweep of 
victories for all four U.S. national squad crews, gliding to a win 
over a quartet from the London club. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Temple Cup for University eights, Princeton moved into  
the quarterfinals with a 1 1/2 length win over Cherwell from Oxford, 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard's freshmen crew defeated St. Joseph's University ``B''  
team from Philadelphia by 2 1/2 lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Princess Elizabeth Cup for schoolboy eights, St. Joseph's  
Preparatory School lost by 2 1/2 lengths to Australia's St. Peter's 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Fawley Cup for junior quadruple sculls crews, well-known  
English prep school Eton was too good for the Bachelor's Barge Club 
of Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, University of California made its debut in the Ladies  
Plate and beat a composite from London Rowing Club, England, and 
Mainzer, Germany, by three lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	The Berkeley crew will face the British lightweight squad,  
racing as Nottinghamshire County and Oxford Brookes University in 
the semifinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
