<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Auto Industry On Pace For Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. reported  
Friday that their U.S. sales edged up 1 percent in June, compared 
with their strong performances a year ago, as the auto industry 
continued its steady growth toward a record sales year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, industry sales were up 7  
percent. If sales were to continue at the same seasonally adjusted 
annual rate in the second half, the industry could sell 16.6 
million cars and light trucks, well ahead of the record 16.1 
million sold in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will 1999 be the best year in the U.S. auto industry? The  
question is fast becoming: By how much will the industry sales 
record be eclipsed?'' said Bob Rewey, Ford's sales and marketing 
chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its car sales were up 3 percent last month, excluding  
its Jaguar and Volvo units. The strongest gains came in a segment 
that has been given up for dead by some automakers: coupes. Sales 
of the redesigned Mustang were up nearly 23 percent, while sales of 
the Mercury Cougar shot up 166 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But like DaimlerChrysler AG, which reported Thursday that its  
Chrysler unit's sales were down 5 percent last month, Ford and GM 
saw demand for their light trucks level off. Analysts and 
executives blamed the comparison to June 1998, when ``loyalty 
coupons'' and other heavy incentive spending spurred record sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had a tough comparison to a year ago,'' said analyst  
David Healy of Burnham Securities Inc. ``I don't think there's any 
real sustained weakness there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's truck sales were flat, with demand for the F-series  
pickup, the nation's most popular vehicle, down fractionally for 
the first time in months. Most of Ford's sport utility vehicles 
also were down. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's truck sales were down about 1 percent. Hard-hit were its  
big SUVs, such as the Chevrolet Suburban, down 24.5 percent, and 
the Chevy Tahoe and GMC Yukon twins, both down 27 percent. GM is 
winding down production of those models as it prepares to introduce 
redesigned models in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Car sales at GM were up about 2 percent, with the biggest  
percentage gains coming at Buick, Pontiac and Saturn. GM has been 
struggling to get its market share back above 30 percent since last 
year's strikes severely damaged the No. 1 automaker's U.S. sales. 
For the first half, it stood at 29.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has some of the highest rebates available this summer,  
ranging as high as $4,000 on the Oldsmobile Aurora. In addition, GM 
has been placing more emphasis on regional discounts in the past 
two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've really jacked up incentives aggressively,'' said  
Healy, who estimated GM's discounts were averaging $2,000 a 
vehicle. GM officials said that figure was high, but declined to 
say what the actual figure was. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're point blank going to be competitive in the  
marketplace,'' said Roy Roberts, vice president of North American 
sales. ``But we want to grow our market share profitably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industry executives remained optimistic about the rest of the  
year. They praised the Federal Reserve's action this week of only 
slightly raising interest rates while signaling that further rate 
increases may not be needed to cool off inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taking out a little insurance against inflation enhances the  
likelihood that the business expansion will continue into the next 
century,'' Rewey said. ``We believe sales will remain strong in the 
second half of 1999, driven by a healthy economy, confident 
consumers and the introduction of several innovative products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Jameson, vice president of sales and marketing at  
DaimlerChrysler, agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the minimalist action by the Fed and the reaction of the  
market and all the other leading indicators, you'd have to be a 
real contrarian to forecast a downturn in the very near future,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other automakers that reported Friday, DaimlerChrysler's  
Mercedes-Benz unit said its U.S. sales were up 8.5 percent in June; 
Hyundai posted a 101 percent gain; Kia improved 47.5 percent; and 
strong demand for its SUVs gave Suzuki a 92 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales at Jaguar surged 116 percent last month, while Volvo  
posted a 1 percent gain. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
