<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  N. Ireland Negotiators Struggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Negotiators in Northern Ireland  
struggled today to surmount the single obstacle blocking the 
creation of a new Protestant-Catholic government, the heart of last 
year's troubled peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, said his party  
was prepared to postpone forming the government indefinitely until 
the Irish Republican Army promised to commit itself to a timetable 
for ``decommissioning,'' or surrendering, its arms. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they're going to force society to wait, well, we will  
wait,'' said Trimble, adding that the alternative to securing IRA 
decommissioning was ``to decommission democracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The British and Irish prime ministers, Tony Blair and Bertie  
Ahern, entered Stormont, site of the talks, without speaking to 
reporters. They were planning a formal statement outlining progress 
and the potentially dangerous route ahead after a week of 
negotiations that Blair had expected to produce a breakthrough two 
days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Their efforts have failed to reconcile the demands of Trimble's  
Ulster Unionists -- Northern Ireland's major British Protestant 
party -- and the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ulster Unionists insist on a start to IRA disarmament as the  
price for sharing power with Sinn Fein. But Sinn Fein insists the 
government's unconditional, immediate formation is the only way to 
encourage an eventual IRA move. 
</P>
<P>
	As he arrived at Stormont, Sinn Fein chief negotiator Martin  
McGuinness criticized the Ulster Unionists for rejecting a paper 
presented Thursday that represented the maximum distance Sinn Fein 
was prepared to go toward promising IRA disarmament. 
</P>
<P>
	That paper said Sinn Fein leaders believed they ``could succeed  
in persuading those with arms to decommission them in accordance 
with the agreement'' if they got their allotted two seats in the 
envisioned 12-member government. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling today's negotiations ``an absolutely critical phase in  
the history of this island,'' McGuinness accused the Ulster 
Unionists of acting like ``spoiled children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein's offer was lauded by Blair as a ``seismic shift'' in  
the party's previous steadfast refusal to link the IRA's arsenal 
with the right to hold office, but the Ulster Unionists want a 
cast-iron assurance that the IRA will disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble, who would lead the government, said Sinn Fein's use of  
``could'' revealed how little had actually been promised. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because `could' also means `could not.' We need to know what  
the IRA actually will do, and when,'' he told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, Gen. John de Chastelain, the Canadian head of the  
international commission that has been seeking disarmament of the 
IRA and outlawed pro-British groups, presented his report on the 
situation to Blair and Ahern and said he hoped it would ``move 
peace forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report confirmed that the IRA, via de Chastelain's  
occasional meetings with McGuinness, had yet to give any 
``unambiguous commitment'' to disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, de Chastelain judged that Sinn Fein's latest  
proposal ``may translate into a commitment to decommission 
paramilitary arms'' by the IRA. For the intended May deadline for 
the IRA's total disarmament, he wrote, ``the process of 
decommissioning should begin as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All sides had been hoping for a breakthrough before July's  
``marching season,'' when hard-line Protestants parades across 
Northern Ireland cause sectarian tensions to run at their highest. 
</P>
<P>
	The major marching group, the Orange Order, says it will defy  
restrictions on a march Sunday in the Protestant heartland of 
Portadown, where confrontations have inspired the worst violence in 
recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Before dawn today, British soldiers began erecting obstacles  
across farm fields to prevent Orangemen this weekend from reaching 
the nearby Garvaghy Road, Portadown's major Catholic section. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
