<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones' SUV Held Up As Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- George Jones' mangled vehicle will serve  
as a vivid -- and elevated -- reminder of the dangers of drinking and 
driving this holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lexus sport utility vehicle that Jones wrecked in March is  
being dangled 100 feet in the air from a crane just off Interstate 
40. It has a sign reading, ``Drive Safely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message is being sponsored by radio station WKDF and the  
owner of the car, Raymond Turek, who paid $22,000 for it a few 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The station will run a promotional spot taped by Jones all  
weekend that says, in part: ``Don't drink and drive. It could kill 
you. And that's the cold, hard truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was driving alone when he lost control and smashed the  
Lexus into a concrete bridge. He nearly died, but has since 
recovered enough to perform. 
</P>
<P>
	The singer pleaded guilty to driving while impaired and  
violating the state's open-container law. He was fined $550 and 
ordered to receive counseling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
