<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 22:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Primary Calendar Concerns GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An advisory panel being set up by the chairman  
of the Republican National Committee will look into ways to stop 
states from holding earlier and earlier presidential primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is so compressed and it goes off like a string of  
firecrackers once it starts,'' RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson said 
Friday. ``A person who might have gotten a bounce because of a 
surprisingly good showing in an early primary ... (won't have) time 
to really maximize that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In releasing a tentative primary schedule for next year,  
Nicholson noted that the Iowa caucuses, one of the first major 
events in 2000, could come as early as Jan. 31. And by the end of 
February, about 40 percent more delegates will have been chosen 
than by the same time in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our major concern is that not enough people get involved in  
this process of choosing who the nominees will be for the most 
important job on Earth,'' Nicholson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I think if you would ask the candidates, they would  
agree,'' he said. ``They would like to have more time to be out in 
more states and learning their issues and learning more about those 
regions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said he will appoint senior Republican officials to  
his advisory panel, which probably will be chaired by a former RNC 
leader since many former chairmen ``have run for and been elected 
president of the United States. ... They've been through the mill 
in this process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel will issue findings by the end of the year so that the  
suggestions can be considered during the RNC winter meeting next 
January in California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will instruct them to examine all possible options,  
including the plan recently put forth by the National Association 
of Secretaries of State, which is a regional rotating primary,'' he 
said. ``I'm going to ask them to look at other possibilities, 
including a stronger incentive-based program, perhaps, a national 
delegate selection day, and others that have been put on the table 
around the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previous incentives, like giving states more delegates if they  
push back their primary, have failed. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said the RNC rules committee also is studying the  
issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
