<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 07:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Mulls Asbestos Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Opponents of a plan to resolve asbestos injury  
claims in an administrative procedure instead of the courts say it 
would possibly deny thousands of people the compensation they 
deserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The Association of Trial Lawyers of America said it doesn't  
believe legislation pending in the House and the Senate will 
provide badly needed relief for a legal system now choked by 
hundreds of thousands of slow-moving asbestos-related lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they say, it will create another layer of bureaucracy  
for people -- many of them suffering from cancer and other disabling 
diseases -- to fight through. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not fair,'' Richard Middleton, the group's  
president-elect, told the House Judiciary Committee on Thursday. 
``It is not fast, it is not efficient and it is not right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But supporters praised the idea as a better and faster way to  
get money to sick and injured people who really deserve it. It also 
would weed out people who are not sick, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The courts of this land simply are not equipped to handle the  
more than 200,000 asbestos-related cases currently in the system 
and the 8,000 new filings thrust upon the courts on the last month 
alone,'' said Conrad Mallet, a former chief justice of the Michigan 
Supreme Court and president of a business group lobbying for the 
idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only losers are a few dozen powerful lawyers,'' said  
Christopher Edley Jr., a Harvard Law School professor. ``This bill 
benefits almost everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Supreme Court decision that threw out a proposed $1.5 billion  
asbestos agreement last week called on Congress to create a better 
way to settle asbestos claims, saying current rules are not 
flexible enough to accommodate cases involving multiple claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill would create a quasi-governmental agency, the  
Asbestos Resolution Corp. Asbestos companies would pay all the 
costs of the non-judicial administrative process, supporters said. 
No taxpayer dollars would be used. 
</P>
<P>
	The first stage of the process would be the determination of  
whether the applicant was ill or injured. If an applicant qualifies 
and receives a ``certificate of medical eligibility,'' the case 
would proceed to mediation if a settlement with the potentially 
liable companies isn't reached during a 60-day grace period. 
</P>
<P>
	If mediation fails, the claimant could choose to file a lawsuit  
or try arbitration. Only claimants with the medical certificate and 
a release from mediation would be allowed to go to court. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporation's seven-member board of directors would be  
nominated by the president and confirmed by the Senate. A Medical 
Advisory Board would provide expert advice to the board on medical 
matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Payments would be made only to claimants who can demonstrate  
that they are sick or have been injured as a result of exposure to 
asbestos using criteria spelled out in the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Punitive damages would be prohibited ``so as to ensure that  
funds would be available to compensate people who may in the future 
become impaired by asbestos-related diseases,'' said a Judiciary 
Committee statement explaining the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Claimants would be able to collect money for nonmalignant  
disease, such as asbestosis -- scarring of the lungs -- without 
losing their right to future compensation if they develop cancer 
later, supporters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney fees and expenses would be capped at 25 percent.  
Supporters of the plan said that as much as two-thirds of some 
asbestos awards today go to lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1283.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
