<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vatican Denies Link to Financier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- The Vatican formally distanced itself from a  
U.S. insurance scandal and two priests who reportedly provided a 
cloak of respectability for a missing financier. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first official statement on the matter, the Vatican said  
Thursday a charitable foundation established by Martin Frankel, the 
missing money manager, had neither legal standing with the Vatican 
nor an account at the Vatican bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators in the United States suspect the charity was  
merely a front for fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel disappeared May 5 after a fire at his home in Greenwich,  
Conn. He is being sought in the disappearance of at least $200 
million from several insurance companies. A lawsuit filed by some 
of the companies put the loss at $915 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Also missing may be as much as $1.98 billion from the St.  
Francis of Assisi Foundation, which Frankel established in the 
British Virgin Islands last August. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Peter Jacobs and Monsignor Emilio Colagiovanni were  
apparently persuaded by Frankel to support the foundation, 
according to The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	In the statement, Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said  
the Holy See had no relations with Jacobs and neither furnished nor 
received funds from the St. Francis foundation or the Monitor 
Ecclesiasticus Foundation, of which Colagiovanni is president. 
</P>
<P>
	That foundation was established by the archdiocese of Naples in  
1967 and was not connected to the Vatican, Navarro-Valls said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vatican bank, formally called the Institute for Religious  
Works, was badly tainted by a banking scandal in the 1980s due to 
the collapse of the Banco Ambrosiano. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
