<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kurt Andersen Sees Future of TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hey, fellow couch potatoes, these are pretty  
good ideas: 
</P>
<P>
	-- E!2, pronounced ``E squared,'' would be a channel spun off  
from cable's E! Entertainment network airing nothing but raw 
footage of celebrity events. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Another cable service, The Chopper Channel, would run 24-hour  
video from helicopters. (``The big picture, from the air, on the 
air, for you!'') 
</P>
<P>
	-- And on the cool new series ``Supreme Court,'' celebrity  
lawyers would argue celebrities' cases in a fake-trial setting 
presided over by Judge Robert Bork. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't look for this programming on your TV just yet. But it's  
part of Kurt Andersen's eerily plausible, wickedly amusing vision 
of life one short year from now, as captured in ``Turn of the 
Century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Along with mapping the media universe, Andersen's instructive  
new novel charts a modern marriage whose partners (Lizzie runs a 
computer-software firm; George produces TV shows) face the 
prevailing struggle of the new millennium: convergence. 
</P>
<P>
	Web sites, it seems, are fated to converge with TV. Business  
must converge with art, show biz with real life. The sacred, of 
course, is converging with the profane. And all the while, staying 
converged with those you hold dear gets trickier by the nanosecond. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's this sense that the old rules are gone,'' Andersen  
said in a recent interview. ``How can I take advantage of that? How 
am I going to be crushed by that? It's an odd new Zeitgeist, 
terrifying and exciting simultaneously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then who can make sense of it? Certainly not George, despite  
pulling down $16,575 per week as a TV magnate, or Lizzie, who just 
might sell her company to Microsoft for $30 million dollars -- all 
at the possible cost of their marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	And who can plot the future? Not even Andersen, who shares the  
uncertainty voiced by George and Lizzie's daughter: ``Is that a 
good thing or a bad thing, Daddy?'' she repeatedly inquires. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer is, both good and bad, according to the novel, whose  
crafting left its author in ``a state of acute ambivalence, more 
than resolution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No matter. It's hard to imagine anyone laying out the  
possibilities and pitfalls of the bitstream revolution in a manner 
more lucid yet rambunctious. More than telling a story, ``Turn of 
the Century'' tells you ideas. Big and small and usually hilarious. 
By the bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Turn to any of its 659 frisky pages and find passing reference  
to a cafe called Ellipsis... (dots included). Or this USA Today 
headline: ``Experts Fear We're Suffering 'Third Millennium' 
Malaise.'' Or a consultant's advice on anchor-appropriate surnames: 
``Nonethnic and bisyllabic with the accent on the first -- like 
RATH-er, BRO-kaw, KOP-pel, JEN-nings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One part Evelyn Waugh and one part Wired magazine, ``Turn of the  
Century'' is a high-res social satire of the dot-com age. 
</P>
<P>
	Andersen, 44, came to it naturally. A gangly intellectual with  
tortoise-shell glasses and a wry wit, he co-created the humor 
magazine Spy, ran New York magazine, dabbled in TV production and 
currently writes for The New Yorker. Earlier this year he was a 
runner-up for president of cable's Comedy Central. Clearly, he 
knows the media inside out, understands all the players and their 
fatuous folkways. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Turn of the Century,'' he set out to create ``a hyper-real  
world that could fit into the real world we inhabit, seamlessly,'' 
as he told TV interviewer Charlie Rose, who, naturally, is among 
the media figures and pop-culture citations with which his book is 
brimming. 
</P>
<P>
	And so it goes: Andersen's convergence of what is and what could  
be. 
</P>
<P>
	Just consider the programming ideas listed above. They seem at  
once preposterous and plausible, which, if you hadn't noticed, are 
conditions no longer mutually exclusive. This marketplace mentality 
is what fuels George's series, ``Real Time'' -- a news magazine 
combined with a hard-hitting drama where the actors and journalists 
are interchangeable. 
</P>
<P>
	Preposterous. But since it just might sell, also plausible.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're at the moment of absolute hegemony of marketplace  
values,'' Andersen said. And among the media, those marketplace 
values swell into this chorus: Let us entertain you! 
</P>
<P>
	``Entertainment, by its nature, is whatever the majority thinks  
is funny or sad or moving,'' Andersen noted. ``So, to regard 
everything, including news, as entertainment is simply another way 
of saying that attracting the most eyeballs is the goal -- period. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can also make it good, so much the better. But there no  
longer is an independent set of values in healthy conflict with the 
profit-making motive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, everything you see or hear must fit into a business plan,  
Andersen said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity for particular, somewhat crazy passions, among  
the creators of culture and the consumers as well, is less than it 
once was. I think there is a sense of joylessness combined with the 
excitement over what's going to happen next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What's going to happen next? Maybe something called TVTVTV.  
Played on monitors installed in its own fleet of school buses, it 
would program nothing but advertising for products aimed at kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Appalling? Brilliant! Why is Andersen giving million-dollar  
ideas away? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best of both worlds,'' he replied, smiling. ``I get  
to invent them and imagine what they'd be like -- and I don't have 
to ask myself, Is this really what my life has come to?'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`20/20': Correspondent Chris Wallace reports how some domestic  
cleaning personnel may be cleaning up the wrong way. In 
hidden-camera footage, he captures one cleaning woman rifling 
through drawers and pocketing cash she finds hidden around the 
house. ``I'd love to have someone clean my house,'' says one victim 
of maid theft. ``But I don't trust anyone in my home anymore.'' It 
airs on ABC News' ``20/20'' tonight at 10 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
