<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Teen Olympic Swimmer Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Anita Nall was a  
record-breaking swimmer and an Olympic gold medalist at 15 -- and 
out of the sport by 19. 
</P>
<P>
	After overcoming health problems that led her to quit, Nall is  
back in the pool and heading the U.S. team at the 20th World 
University Games, where Friday's action was limited to preliminary 
round soccer matches. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening ceremony is Saturday, when events get underway in  
earnest with gymnastics, basketball and volleyball. Over 4,000 
athletes are expected to take part in the 12 sports on tap for the 
biannual games, which run through July 13 on the Spanish island of 
Mallorca. 
</P>
<P>
	Swimming starts Sunday, and Nall can't wait to make her return  
to international competition after a four-year layoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great opportunity for me,'' said Nall, who turns 23  
this month. ``I don't know what to expect out there. But the 
thought of losing doesn't even faze me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was seemingly born to win.  
</P>
<P>
	Though she has long gone by her middle name, Anita, Nall's first  
name is Nadia. She was named for Romanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci, 
who captivated the world with perfect 10s at the 1976 Olympics the 
day Nall's mother went into labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Nall made quite a splash in 1992, smashing the world record for  
the 200 meters breaststroke twice in one day at the national 
Olympic trials, where she also won the 100 breaststroke. The 
Towson, Md., native went on to win gold, silver and bronze medals 
at the Barcelona Games. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a high school freshman and a star with all the  
trappings: endorsement deals, magazine photo spreads. 
</P>
<P>
	``That all seems like forever ago and a whole different person  
ago,'' Nall said. 
</P>
<P>
	That, in large part, is because she struggled throughout 1995  
with what she said was eventually determined to be a blood pressure 
abnormality, and went to the 1996 U.S. trials for the Atlanta 
Olympics without proper preparation. 
</P>
<P>
	Nall finished fourth in both breaststroke events, failing to  
make the team, and promptly retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was probably already beaten before getting in the pool,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nall went through several doctors before one was able to  
successfully diagnose and treat her. In May 1998, she returned to 
her favorite pursuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, she qualified for this University Games  
team, and now has the 2000 Sydney Olympics in her sights. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt really reassured when I qualified and thought why  
wouldn't I try this for one more year,'' said Nall, who is studying 
communications and Spanish at Arizona State. 
</P>
<P>
	She is a co-captain of the U.S. swimming team, and an  
acknowledged leader. ``I try the best I can to lead and share 
experiences I've had that in any way can help,'' Nall said. ``Now 
I'm a strong individual, an adult. Before, I was a piece of clay, 
molded by others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another past breaststroke phenom, Amanda Beard, is also on the  
U.S. team. Beard was 14 when she took one gold and two silvers at 
the 1996 Olympics, and will swim the 100 meters breaststroke in 
Mallorca. 
</P>
<P>
	Nall will swim only the 200 breaststroke, but plans to take a  
crack at both that event and the 100 at next year's U.S. Olympic 
trials. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's that pressure if you've been the darling of swimming  
as she was in 1992 and a record holder in 1992 and then faded 
out,'' U.S. swimming coach Bill Rose said. 
</P>
<P>
	``To her credit, she's back to this level. It's like George  
Foreman staying out of boxing X number of years and being as good 
as before. In swimming terms, she is that old. Eight years is a 
lifetime in swimming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, South Africa pulled out of the soccer competition,  
giving scheduled opponent Brazil a day off. The last-minute 
defection left Pool C with three teams -- and two will qualify for 
the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	In the games' first action -- and the first international soccer  
competition that FIFA, the sport's world body, has allowed to be 
played on artificial turf -- Morocco routed Uruguay 3-0, Mexico 
edged Ireland 1-0, and Nigeria drew 2-2 with the Czech Republic. 
Four other matches were slated for later Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States does not have a team in the soccer  
competition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
