<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Rate Rises to 4.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The unemployment rate edged up slightly to 4.3  
percent in June even though job growth showed a strong rebound 
during the month as amusement parks, restaurants and construction 
firms gobbled up workers, the Labor Department reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing, however, continued to miss out on the economic  
good times, with job losses in that sector now totaling nearly a 
half-million workers since the Asian crisis hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate for more than a year has been at levels not  
seen in nearly three decades. Unemployment in May had dipped to a 
29-year low of 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, which is hoping the good economy  
will convince voters to keep a Democrat in the White House next 
year, pointed to the creation of 268,000 new jobs in June as a sign 
that the current expansion is steaming ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamentals of this economy remain strong,'' Labor  
Secretary Alexis Herman said, noting that unemployment for blacks 
dipped to another record low. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets, which are worried about inflationary  
pressures arising from tight labor markets, took today's report in 
stride. The Dow Jones industrial average was up about 50 points in 
morning trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing lost another 35,000 jobs in June, bringing the  
total job loss at factories since March 1998 to 488,000. 
Manufacturing has been the hardest hit sector from the global 
financial turmoil, suffering a loss of major export markets 
overseas and increased competition from cheap imports. 
</P>
<P>
	In another report today, the Commerce Department said orders to  
American factories for manufactured goods rebounded in May, rising 
1.1 percent, led by a big increase in demand for aircraft, autos 
and other transportation products. 
</P>
<P>
	The low overall jobless rate is a result of the long economic  
expansion. The country is now in its ninth year of uninterrupted 
growth, a peacetime record. This long stretch without a recession 
has allowed prosperity to reach many sectors of the workforce who 
traditionally lag behind. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said today that unemployment for blacks fell to a  
new record low of 7.3 percent in June. Rates for women and 
hispanics remained close to their lowest levels in three decades 
</P>
<P>
	Employment at American businesses accelerated sharply last month  
with a total of 268,000 new jobs created with all industries except 
manufacturing and mining posting solid gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in payroll jobs was slightly stronger than  
economists had been expecting and signaled that labor markets 
remained exceptionally healthy going into the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve on Wednesday boosted a key short-term  
interest rate by a quarter point, citing concerns that tight labor 
markets could begin pushing inflation higher as workers demand 
higher wages. 
</P>
<P>
	While financial markets were initially encouraged that the  
central bank signaled that one rate hike may be all that is needed 
to keep inflation under control, analysts said the strong June jobs 
report means the Fed might still feel the need to raise rates again 
in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,  
increased by 3.7 percent in June, compared to a year ago, to 
$13.23. This was up only slightly from the May year-over-year 
increase of 3.5 percent. Marilyn Schaja, an economist at Donaldson, 
Lufkin and Jenrette, said Fed policymakers are certain to be 
concerned about this upward creep in earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The gain in payroll jobs represented a bounce back from an  
unusually weak performance in May, when business payrolls shrank by 
5,000 workers, the first outright decline in payroll growth since 
January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The declines in manufacturing jobs were widespread last month,  
led by large job losses at aircraft factories and plants making 
electrical equipment and apparel. Mining, another hardhit sector, 
lost another 3,000 jobs in June. 
</P>
<P>
	But construction, which had suffered big job losses in May,  
rebounded last month, posting a gain of 26,000 jobs with plumbing, 
electrical work and roofing all showing increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall gain of 268,000 payroll jobs was led by strong  
hiring at amusement parks with a gain of 20,000 jobs in amusement 
and recreation services. 
</P>
<P>
	Also posting big gains were retail trade, which added 49,000  
jobs in June, bringing total job growth in this sector to 265,000 
through the first half of this year. The largest gain in June came 
from hiring at restaurants and bars. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1.1 percent gain in factory orders was led by a big 9.5  
percent increase in demand for transportation products in May, 
rebounding from a 12.5 percent decrease in the previous month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
