<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Approves Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government approved key economic  
reforms Friday, apparently inspired by the improved prospects of a 
badly needed foreign loan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank announced it was lifting a major  
currency-trading restriction, while the upper house of parliament 
approved several economic bills -- all conditions for getting a $4.5 
billion loan from the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	An IMF team that visited Moscow this week praised Russia's  
economic performance and indicated that lending could soon be 
resumed. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian government officials sounded upbeat.  
</P>
<P>
	``The (economic) crisis has gradually become history, and I hope  
we will soon cease talking about it,'' Prime Minister Sergei 
Stepashin was quoted as saying by Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabinet officials have been making similar pronouncements for  
months, but the millions of Russians struggling to pay for food and 
housing would be hard-pressed to see any difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Moscow is eager to meet the IMF's terms and secure the  
loan, which would allow Russia to pay off this year's payments on 
old debts from the fund and avoid a potentially disastrous default. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank announced that on Monday it will lift a ban on  
foreign banks buying hard currency with rubles kept in required 
Central Bank correspondent accounts. The ban was issued as a way to 
control the ruble's rate by limiting the demand for hard currency 
on money markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban also allowed the Central Bank to fill its own  
hard-currency coffers at a more advantageous rate, but it ran 
against IMF free-market policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank also protects the currency by spend its own  
foreign-currency reserves to buy rubles, thus shrinking the ruble 
supply. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bank on Friday apparently chose to preserve its  
dwindling resources and stopped interfering with money market 
trading, allowing the ruble's value to drop to 24.47 to the dollar, 
down from 24.21 to the dollar on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other key IMF-mandated reforms were approved Friday by  
the upper house of parliament that further freed up money and 
metals markets. One bill allows the Central Bank to buy gold 
directly from mining companies -- making it easier to increase 
reserves of precious metals and foreign currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federation Council also approved a bill that would impose a  
tax on big luxury cars, a bill that would allow the bank to issue 
securities, and one that would allow the liquidation of insolvent 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills have already been approved by the lower house, the  
State Duma, and now must be signed by President Boris Yeltsin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
