<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entrepreneurial Britains Look to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- John Culverhouse's colleagues were stupefied when  
he quit his job editing sports stories at a newspaper to test his 
entrepreneurial skills importing fireworks. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen years later, Culverhouse's firm, Fantastic Fireworks  
Ltd., employs 15 workers and posts annual sales of $2.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision to scrap a comfortable career to start his own  
small business demonstrates an entrepreneurial zeal that British 
officials worry is all too rare today in the land that produced 
Adam Smith and his doctrine of laissez-faire economics. 
</P>
<P>
	To help cultivate a stronger, risk-taking culture in Britain, 75  
American entrepreneurs, policy-makers and venture capitalists 
shared insights Friday with their British counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	No one expected the single day of workshops to transform  
ingrained attitudes and policies in the United Kingdom, but many 
welcomed it as the start of a necessary evolution in mentality. 
</P>
<P>
	``The word 'profit' is still a dirty word in the U.K. British  
society is very modest and doesn't like to boast, and profit is 
about boasting. But without profit, there's no employment,'' said 
Stephen Alambritis of the Federation of Small Businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	British soccer players and pop stars are celebrated as heroes,  
yet ``many successful business people are berated as greedy fat 
cats,'' said Andrew Parkinson, a British Chambers of Commerce 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The need to modify these views is clear. A recent London School  
of Business survey found that a third of all economic activity is 
connected to the work of entrepreneurs, yet only one of every 30 
Britons is actively trying to start a business -- less than half as 
many as in the United States, Canada and Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	The same survey found that 95 percent of Americans believe  
working as an entrepreneur is a respectable occupation, a view 
shared by only 30 percent of Britons interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	British officials, even leaders of the formerly socialist Labor  
Party, are increasingly aware of the need to encourage people to 
take the risk of creating a business. They've sought inspiration 
from the United States, where the dynamic formation of new firms 
has contributed to galloping growth and low unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Innovation is the key to success in the new enterprise  
economy,'' Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown said at the 
conference. ``We here in the United Kingdom have a great deal to 
learn from the successes in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Britain that perfected the idea that businesses should  
operate without government interference, and Scottish economist 
Adam Smith laid the intellectual framework for a global free 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a fear of failure in business has retarded start-up activity  
-- and growth -- in Britain today, executives say. 
</P>
<P>
	``My old boss just couldn't understand why I was giving up a  
safe, well-paid job to take a risk like the one I was taking,'' 
said Culverhouse, the fireworks entrepreneur. 
</P>
<P>
	Harsh, Victorian-era bankruptcy laws have reinforced this fear.  
In Britain, owners of companies that fail cannot borrow money from 
a bank for at least three years. They cannot serve as company 
directors, and in London, they can't even get a license to drive a 
taxi. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. laws give bankrupt companies breathing room to reorganize  
their debts, and owners of failed businesses can quickly start 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	David Rose, 42, of New York City, had to completely restructure  
his software business after cheaper access to the Internet made his 
original plan obsolete. His firm, AirMedia, avoided bankruptcy, but 
its sales dried up and he had to slash its workforce from 120 
people to 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of being traumatized that our first attempt didn't  
work, we picked ourselves up, dusted ourselves off and tried 
again,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A comparatively weak network of support services makes matters  
worse for Britons who want to strike out on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, just this week, the Department of Trade and  
Industry unveiled plans for a Small Business Service, which aims to 
help entrepreneurs and small firms. The service will have an 
initial budget of $160 million. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, small U.S. companies have access to a pool of $48  
billion in loans from the Small Business Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	American start-up companies have better opportunities for  
financing from venture capitalists. British venture capitalists 
have focused more on buying out existing firms than investing in 
new ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Britain's shortcomings, conference participants seemed  
to agree that it still is five to 10 years ahead of its European 
neighbors in terms of supporting its entrepreneurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can assure you that we fully intend to push these issues  
with our European partners,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Americans strained to keep the conference from sounding  
like a triumphant celebration of U.S. business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Elkus Jr. of Atherton, Calif. was one. Elkus helped  
develop the first VCR, heads two high-tech firms and serves on the 
boards of several others. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things change. This is a pretty dynamic world,'' he said.  
``What laurels do you rest on?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
