<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Russians Oppose US Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Nearly half of Russians don't want American  
investments in the area where they live, apparently because their 
resentment of U.S. influence outweighs any suffering from poverty, 
a poll released Friday indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-six percent of respondents in a June 19 poll by the  
independent Public Opinion Fund said they didn't want Americans to 
invest in their home regions or republics. The figure marked a 
sharp increase from the 32 percent who opposed U.S. investment in 
1995, according to a similar poll by the same agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO airstrikes against Russian ally Yugoslavia stoked  
strong anti-American feelings in Russia. Deepening economic 
troubles have also made many Russians increasingly bitter about the 
loss of superpower status and resentful of U.S. influence in the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Many opponents of U.S. investment said it would make Russia  
completely dependent on the United States or even turn Russia into 
an American colony, according to poll results carried by the 
Interfax agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters cited prospects for economic growth, jobs, advanced  
technologies and help in overcoming the country's grinding economic 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	No margin of error was given for the poll of 1,500 people  
throughout Russia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 05:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gotti Says Son Belongs in Asylum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Flabbergasted by the carelessness that  
helped get his son indicted, John J. Gotti said an insane asylum 
might better suit ``Junior'' than prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors filed transcripts Thursday of a prison conversation  
taped in January 1998 that the elder Gotti had with his daughter 
and his brother. 
</P>
<P>
	The material was submitted in advance of a sentencing hearing  
set for next Thursday for John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, who pleaded 
guilty in April to racketeering, bribery, extortion, fraud and 
gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know too much about indictments to believe anything I read  
in the indictment,'' the elder Gotti said in the transcript. ``But 
these people here if ever found guilty they should never be sent to 
jail. They should all be sent to the insane asylum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti was especially appalled that FBI agents had found $358,000  
in cash in a basement his son controlled. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son who is the most legitimate, upstanding citizen you  
could find if you want to be technical. Look what he gives them to 
(hang) their hat on. Funny money in the basement,'' he said in the 
transcript. 
</P>
<P>
	He implied the money could have been from wedding gifts to his  
son, and said, ``A beautiful wedding, you got your money, you take 
your money and you put it in a safe deposit box. That's what a 
normal person would do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanna know what part of this was intelligent,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gotti Sr., the onetime head of the Gambino crime family, got the  
nickname ``Teflon Don'' for escaping conviction in three trials. He 
was finally found guilty in 1992 in a racketeering case that 
featured the Mafia's highest-ranking turncoat, Salvatore ``Sammy 
the Bull'' Gravano. He is serving a life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors accused his son of taking over the crime syndicate,  
saying he performed all the duties of a crime boss and kept a 
``promotion list,'' which was available only to high-ranking Mafia 
members, according to the court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Junior'' Gotti's lawyer, Gerald Shargel, implied that the  
prosecution's argument was actually meant for the press. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing in that letter that the judge has not already  
seen,'' he said. ``I wonder who they're doing it for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter accompanying the transcripts, prosecutors asked  
federal Judge Barrington Parker to sentence young Gotti to seven 
years and three months, the maximum mentioned when he pleaded 
guilty. They detailed some of the evidence prosecutors would have 
presented at trial. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Gotti Jr. received $400 each week for having lunch  
with the owner of a construction company, the papers said. He was 
also the only ``employee'' to get a Christmas bonus -- $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gotti's lawyer said his client ``is not the villain that the  
government portrays him to be.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
