<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apache Opens Door for Collaboration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOREST HILL, Md. (AP) -- Apache, the most widely used software  
for powering Internet servers, will become part of a not-for-profit 
corporation, a move designed to add stability and enable 
collaboration with established companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The free, open-source software, is produced by volunteer  
programmers who share ideas and computer code to create the server 
software now used by 61 percent of Internet-connected servers, 
according a survey by Netcraft, a consulting firm in Bath, England. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Apache Software Foundation will provide organizational,  
legal and financial support for its projects, the group said in a 
statement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Apache's installed base is far ahead of its closest competitor,  
Microsoft's Internet Information Server, which is on 22 percent of 
Internet servers, according to Netcraft. 
</P>
<P>
	By incorporating, Apache can now accept intellectual property  
from companies such as IBM Corp., which has said it will provide 
coding and a team of programmers to the Apache foundation. Sun 
Microsystems Inc. also announced that it will contribute its 
JavaServer Pages software to the Apache project. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
