<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Investigating Calif. Gas Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission is stepping up  
its investigation of California gasoline prices with a new round of 
subpoenas seeking information about oil company pricing methods, a 
source familiar with the investigation said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is one of several regulatory agencies looking  
into California prices, which rose sharply in February and March 
and remain higher than the national average. 
</P>
<P>
	The California and Nevada attorneys general also are  
investigating the price increase. The federal General Accounting 
Office also has been asked to look into gasoline prices in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	One company, San Francisco-based Chevron Corp., acknowledged on  
Friday that it had been notified that it and other oil companies 
would receive subpoenas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have indications that a subpoena will be issued to Chevron  
and all oil companies as part of the investigation,'' spokesman 
Fred Gorell said. ``We intend, as before and in all investigations, 
to cooperate fully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials expect the investigation to conclude that the  
price increase was a result of market forces, not collusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for Tosco Corp. and Arco Products Co., the retailing  
arm of Los Angeles-based Atlantic Richfield Co., said they could 
not determine whether the companies had been subpoenaed or notified 
subpoenas were on the way because corporate attorneys could not be 
reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to Shell Oil Co. and Texaco Inc. after business hours  
Friday were not immediately returned. A call to the FTC also was 
not returned, though the agency typically will not comment on its 
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoenas seek company pricing records and other documents  
that might reveal how companies decide gasoline prices for 
different regions, according to a source who spoke on the condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil refiners have blamed the price hike on a variety of factors,  
including production cuts by OPEC nations and refinery fires that 
forced companies to import gasoline to California from Asia and the 
U.S. Gulf Coast. They also have said that production slowed as 
refineries made their annual switch to summer gasoline formulas 
designed to reduce air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Barbara Boxer, who requested the FTC investigation,  
applauded news that the agency was intensifying its probe. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am gratified to learn the FTC is now escalating that  
investigation,'' she said in a prepared statement. ``I believe that 
California drivers have been overcharged at the gas pumps to the 
tune of tens of millions of dollars.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
