<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Suffers Happy Hour Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Martin thought he was driving  
the best car he had ever brought to Daytona. He won't have the 
chance to find out, due to an accident in Pepsi 400 practice Friday 
evening that left his arm in a splint and his car on a wrecker. 
</P>
<P>
	The right front tire on Martin's Ford split as he was entering  
the third turn of the 2.5-mile trioval at Daytona International 
Speedway during the final ``happy hour'' practice session before 
Saturday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	He received minor injuries to his left wrist and left leg,  
although it's his psyche that surely took the biggest beating. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hit the wall about as hard as I've ever tangled with it,''  
Martin said. ``I'm a little bit sore, but I'm going to be OK. We 
had a fabulous car. This is the best restrictor-plate car I've ever 
driven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from Goodyear said it didn't appear there was anything  
structurally wrong with the tire. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what we can see, it appears there was a cut close to the  
inside shoulder of the tread that caused rapid air loss,'' Goodyear 
public relations manager Carole Swartz said. ``That would explain 
why there was so little warning before the accident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swartz said technicians would examine the tire more thoroughly  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin's car ran the fastest lap of the afternoon practice at  
192.703 mph. That came a day after he qualified third with a speed 
of 194.376. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident crumpled the car's hood. Minutes later, his crew  
was wheeling the backup car into the garage for a few frantic hours 
of work. 
</P>
<P>
	The new car will start from the back of the field for the race.  
Martin said he will take the wheel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'll drive tomorrow,'' he said. ``I'd be ready to drive  
tonight. If they were starting in five minutes, I'd line up and 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Green clipped Martin at the end of the crash, but his car  
received little damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I spun out and did about two or three spins,'' Green said. ``I  
didn't hit anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also during happy hour, Tony Stewart skidded into the wall, but  
his car was expected to be race ready. Stewart, the leading rookie 
on the Winston Cup circuit this season, said he heard there was oil 
on the track near where he wrecked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
