<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hepatitis Culture May Aid in Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A team of German scientists has coaxed a form  
of the Hepatitis C virus to reproduce in a laboratory, a 
preliminary step that could make it easier to develop treatments 
for the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide, Hepatitis C affects an estimated 170 million people  
and can lead to chronic liver problems, including cirrhosis and 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to develop a treatment for Hepatitis C have been  
hampered by the resistance of the virus to being grown in 
laboratory cultures where scientists can study it. 
</P>
<P>
	A paper in this week's edition of the journal Science reports  
that a team at Johannes Gutenburg University in Mainz, Germany, 
managed to engineer the virus' genome in a way that forces it to 
reproduce in cultured human cells. 
</P>
<P>
	In theory, they said, unlimited reproduction of the virus would  
be possible, making it easier to study the virus and test potential 
antiviral drugs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
