<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down; Coffee Falls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures fell sharply a second day Friday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid concerns farmers this fall will 
harvest bumper crops, resulting in continued ample inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, crude rose to new 19-month highs, while coffee  
fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans were expected to escape relatively unscathed  
after a weekend of temperatures soaring into the upper 90s in 
Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have seesawed over the past few sessions as market  
participants attempted to evaluate whether hot, dry weather would 
hurt young crops. But some forecasters are calling for a return of 
normal temperatures later next week and say there is ample soil 
moisture to protect roots. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service after trading had ended reported  
temperatures will remain above-normal to much above-normal in major 
growing regions over the next 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures also were pressured by talk that production could  
soar above 10 billion bushels if they make it through the crucial 
pollination period without significant damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans begin their flowering period next month, and there  
currently appears no threat to reducing what is expected to be 
bumper production. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by expectations for active  
harvesting of the winter wheat crop over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery fell 7 cents to $2.51 3/4 a bushel;  
September corn fell 6 cents to $2.02 1/4 a bushel; September oats fell 
3 cents to $1.08 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 12 1/2 cents to 
$4.34 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange as  
Americans took to the road for the Fourth of July holiday, boosting 
expectations inventories will continue to tighten. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy prices have rallied this week amid industry data that  
shows supplies have been tightening steadily as world oil producers 
have worked to hold a collective 5.3 million barrels daily off the 
market since the beginning of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A year-to-year world surplus in crude now has shrunk to a 3  
percent deficit over this time a year ago, according to the 
industry organization the American Petroleum Institute, helping 
reinforce a belief that world oil producers are sticking to 
commitments to reduce available supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries  
and other top producers have shown unusual cooperation in reducing 
daily output. Much of that came after they saw their revenues 
tumble precipitously because of oversupply and weaker world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	August crude rose 30 cents to $19.69 a barrel; August heating  
oil rose .32 cent to 49.14 cents a gallon; August unleaded gasoline 
rose 1.43 cents to 58.46 cents a gallon; August natural gas fell 
2.2 cents to $2.287 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled on the Board of Trade of the City of New  
York amid expectations Brazilian coffee-growing regions will remain 
frost-free over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee's fortunes have been tied to weather conditions in Brazil  
during its winter. The world's largest producer has gone through 
several growing seasons with no major damage to its crops or trees, 
leading to bumper supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	September arabica coffee fell 2.45 cents to 98 cents a pound.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 20:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
