<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> W. Virginia Losing Its Orchards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) -- West Virginia's fruit orchards are  
going the way of the buggy whip. 
</P>
<P>
	They are ``getting to be obsolete,'' says third-generation  
grower John M. Miller III of Gerrardstown. 
</P>
<P>
	Numbers back Miller's opinion.  
</P>
<P>
	Since 1987, the number of acres used to grow apples in the  
Eastern Panhandle has gone from 15,330 acres to 8,000 acres, says 
Henry Hogmire, extension specialist for the West Virginia 
University Extension Farm in Kearneysville. 
</P>
<P>
	Peach orchards filled 3,340 acres in 1987 but today make up only  
1,300. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining profits and pressure to develop open space are among  
the reasons the orchards are vanishing, agricultural experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Many growers, struggling with lower profit margins, are selling  
their land for commercial and residential development, Hogmire 
says. ``All you have to do is drive around here and see what is 
happening. It's sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia is not alone.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is something we're seeing all along the Eastern  
Seaboard,'' says Jim Cranney, vice president of the U.S. Apple 
Association in McLean, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition from China and Poland is hurting the domestic  
industry, too, Cranney says. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign producers are exporting apple juice concentrate at far  
lower prices than U.S. growers offer, mainly because they receive 
subsidies from their governments to offset costs. U.S. growers do 
not receive subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers in Washington state, the nation's main apple grower,  
have wisely invested in extensive irrigation systems to support 
their orchards and large buyers. That hasn't happened in West 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Hogmire says many Eastern Panhandle growers have diversified,  
planting Christmas trees, pumpkins, strawberries and sweet corn. 
Others, like George S. Orr &AMP; Sons in Arden, have built on their 
foundation, selling a line of apple butter, fruit baskets and 
related goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinsburg grower Jim Seibert is trying to cut costs by selling  
his fruit directly to processors, eliminating the need for packing 
lines and cold storage. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WOODBURN, Ore. (AP) -- Rebounding Japanese demand for  
strawberries along with a crackdown on a pesticide in California 
will help boost Oregon berry prices despite another decline in the 
state harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the strawberry harvest is running about 6 million to 9  
million pounds short of the 1998 harvest of 46 million pounds, said 
Bob Conroy of International Flavors and Fragrances, a processing 
plant in Woodburn. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year we were getting about 500,000 pounds a day on our  
peak days. This year, we'll run maybe 320,000,'' said Conroy, who 
may have watched more strawberry harvests come in than anyone else 
in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther north at Oregon Berry Packing in Hillsboro, Roy Malensky  
says not only is there less fruit from the first picking coming 
into his processing plant, but much of that fruit is 
``monkeyfaced'' or deformed, with hard, seedy green ends. 
</P>
<P>
	Some deformities are to be expected, but Malensky said workers  
on his processing line had to sort out 50 percent more fruit in the 
first week than they did in all of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the berries have a higher sugar content than a year  
ago, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Malensky expects yield per acre will be down, but the price for  
the processed berries was set last week at 51.5 cents a pound, a 
penny and a half higher than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the reason for the slight increase in prices is Japan,  
said Dalton Hobbs, international trade manager with the Oregon 
Department of Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Also boosting the Oregon industry is increased demand from  
Eastern Canada, now up to 17 million pounds. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
