<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tragedy Strikes at Special Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARY, N.C. (AP) -- A 14-year-old athlete died in his sleep. A  
volunteer collapsed and died at the opening ceremonies. Four 
competitors disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	The Special Olympics, an international sports festival for the  
developmentally disabled, have brought together nearly 70,000 
people from around the world for nine days. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers say deaths and disappearances can happen when so many  
people -- many with special medical needs -- are involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to remember that this is a global movement,''  
said Timothy Shriver, president and chief executive officer of 
Special Olympics Inc. ``We have thousands of events a year, and 
periodically we have tragedies occur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1995 Special Olympics in Connecticut, an athlete  
drowned during a beach outing, and two competitors walked away. 
Both were located. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's event features about 7,000 competitors -- most of  
them mentally retarded -- from 150 countries. There are about 2,000 
coaches, 15,000 friends and relatives and 45,000 volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Special Olympics were founded in 1963 by Eunice Kennedy  
Shriver. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after the opening ceremonies ended last Saturday,  
volunteer Neale Orrok, 62, of Hendersonville collapsed and died of 
heart problems while walking to a bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Dominican basketball players and two Moroccan soccer players  
slipped away from their delegations in the days that followed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Mohamed Abdul Baset Barin, a volleyball player from  
Egypt, died in his sleep, apparently from an epileptic seizure. The 
rest of the 32-member Egyptian delegation remained in the 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	And University of North Carolina chancellor Michael Hooker died  
of cancer this week. Hooker, 53, was on the Special Olympics board 
of directors and was instrumental in bringing the games to the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess the ironic thing is they represented three different  
aspects of the games that are very key to our success -- our 
athletes, our community leadership that helped bring the games 
here, and our wonderful volunteer force,'' said Joe Freddoso, chief 
executive officer of the World Games Organizing Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Freddoso said the three would be remembered at Sunday's closing  
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been such a great week of joy for the athletes, and  
we've set new standards for the Special Olympics, but anytime 
something likes this happens we have to take time out to mourn,'' 
Freddoso said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was never a doubt the games would continue following the  
deaths, said LeRoy Walker, president of the Games and former 
president of the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker was an assistant coach on the U.S. track and field team  
when 11 Israelis were killed by terrorists in the 1972 Munich 
Olympics. There were calls at the time to stop the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it was the Israeli delegation that made it very clear that  
there was something more important to this particular incident and 
its meaning,'' he said. ``We had one day of mourning and went on to 
complete the games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So the Special Olympics, with hugs and tears of joy for  
thousands who meet individual goals, will run as scheduled through 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	There was good news Friday when word spread that Jamal Agdani,  
23, one of the missing Moroccans, had turned up at Union Station in 
Washington, apparently safe and healthy. The other three who left 
are in their 20s, described as ``highly functional'' and not 
legally obligated to immediately rejoin their delegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite temperatures in the 80s and humidity to match, no  
problems have developed at outdoor competition sites this week. 
However, officials discussed converting Sunday's marathon into a 
13-mile race because of temperatures forecast in the 90s. They 
decided to run the whole race. 
</P>
<P>
	Tents with water and other drinks will be placed at mile  
intervals along the course, and bicycle-riding physicians and 
volunteers will monitor the athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100 runners also must reach the marathon's midway point in 2  
hours, 15 minutes or be pulled from the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will be one happy guy when everyone crosses that finish  
line,'' marathon coordinator Butch Robertson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
