<HEADLINE> Fire Strands NYC Subway Riders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thousands of subway riders were trapped  
underground inside dark, smoky cars after a fire stalled the system 
during the busy rush-hour commute. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 4,500 passengers were stuck on three trains after the  
fire broke out in an underground storage shed around 5 p.m. 
Thursday, said New York City Transit spokesman Al O'Leary. 
</P>
<P>
	One train was forced to stop in a tunnel just west of the  
Broadway-East New York subway station in Brooklyn. With the lights 
and air conditioning off, the temperature rose and acrid smoke 
billowed into cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``You couldn't see anything,'' said passenger Grace Duku. ``The  
train was filled with black smoke. Everyone was scared because we 
couldn't breathe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 passengers were evacuated along a catwalk to an  
emergency exit, but the rest were kept on the train when it 
appeared power would be restored, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no serious injuries. Fire officials said 51 people  
were required some treatment, mostly for smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was under control at 6:40 p.m. and service was back to  
normal by the morning commute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
