<HEADLINE> Station to Air Olympics in Spanish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Radio Unica will carry Spanish-language broadcasts  
from the 2000 and 2004 Olympic Games, adding to the network's 
rapidly growing list of sports properties for the Hispanic market. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-month-old network acquired the Spanish-language rights in  
a deal with broadcastes Westwood One Inc. Radio Unica also has the 
right of first refusal to broadcast the 2008 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 Olympics will be held next year in Sydney, Australia.  
Athens is the host for the 2004 event. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time in history, U.S. Hispanics will have the  
opportunity to tune in to live and interactive coverage of the 
Olympics that goes beyond the headlines,'' said Joaquin Blaya, 
chairman and CEO of Radio Unica Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio Unica provides 24-hour programming to a network that  
reaches some two-thirds of the nation's Hispanic audience. It owns 
or operates 13 stations in top U.S. Hispanic markets and also can 
be heard in Puerto Rico and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Westwood One, based in Culver City, Calif., provides more than  
160 news, sports, entertainment and talk programs to some 5,000 
affiliates. 

  	   	
</P>
