<DOCNO> APW19990702.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Congress Receives Tax Talk Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans who want to talk taxes at home  
over the Fourth of July recess got some help before leaving town. 
</P>
<P>
	The House GOP leadership has sent its 223 members to their home  
districts with a ``Tax Relief Action Packet'' designed to promote a 
tax cut bill expected to total between $778 billion and $996 
billion over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need your help to communicate this message outside the  
Beltway,'' Rep. J.C. Watts, the No. 4-ranking House Republican, 
wrote in a letter to lawmakers, referring to the superhighway that 
encircles the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ensuring that Americans keep more of what they earn, including  
the tax overpayment due them, is a vital part of our agenda,'' said 
the Oklahoma Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans frequently complain that President Clinton is able  
to outfox them on issues ranging from welfare reform to Social 
Security through his communications skills and use of the 
presidential spotlight. GOP leaders on Capitol Hill have pledged to 
present a more unified message, blaming their 1998 election losses 
in part on their failure to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats say this latest tax-cutting exercise is nothing  
but politics geared to the 2000 elections. Clinton, they say, would 
never sign such a huge tax cut into law, and the GOP has made no 
attempt to craft a more modest compromise with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their goal is purely political -- to energize their political  
base by forcing through an irresponsible tax bill that the 
president will veto,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, top 
Democrat on the House Ways and Means Committee. ``The Republican 
leadership does not care about actually enacting a tax cut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee is scheduled to begin considering  
its tax cut bill, which uses projected budget surpluses, the week 
of July 12. Before that, however, Republican leaders must determine 
how to divide the revised non-Social Security surplus among tax 
relief, higher government spending and Medicare reforms that 
include prescription drug benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the chances of a bipartisan deal on these issues appear  
slim, President Clinton may meet with top Republican and Democratic 
congressional leaders after the recess to discuss the possibility 
of compromise, according to GOP aides and White House officials 
speaking on condition of anonymity Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-page House GOP tax packet includes quotes from Democrats  
that can be used against them in speeches, talking points and fact 
sheets for press conferences or broadcast interviews and sample 
newspaper opinion pieces on several planned elements of the tax 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	A typical talking point: ``You and your family need a break. You  
need more control over your own lives and your own money.'' 
Another: ``You deserve the ability to make your dreams come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watts also asked GOP House members to consider holding a ``tax  
relief event in your state, either a press conference or a town 
hall meeting,'' and show up on local talk radio to get out the 
message. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the same information was included in a larger Republican  
``recess and message packet'' given to both House members and 
senators, which says that the ``main communications focus will 
shift to tax relief'' for the weeklong Independence Day recess. 
</P>
<P>
	That package also includes some basic American history for  
members to recite. It notes, for instance, that Thomas Jefferson 
wrote the first draft of the Declaration of Independence, which was 
voted on by the Continental Congress in Philadelphia on July 4, 
1776. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
