<HEADLINE> INS Officer Reassigned Amid Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An Immigration and Naturalization Service officer  
was reassigned after allegations that Border Patrol agents taunted 
two Cuban refugees and made them pose with a photo of Cuban 
President Fidel Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer was ``temporarily assigned to duties which do not  
involve contact with INS detainees,'' the INS said in a statement. 
The Border Patrol is an arm of the INS. The statement did not 
identify the officer or specify what position he held. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees were among six who frantically tried to swim past  
Coast Guard boats earlier in the week. The two accusing the Border 
Patrol of abuse made it to shore and were detained. Four were 
pulled from the water and taken to an INS detention center. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were freed from custody and allowed to remain in the  
United States following large protests by the Cuban community. 
</P>
<P>
	``INS does not condone or in any way tolerate unprofessional  
behavior on the part of its employees,'' the INS statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duviel Rodriguez, 17, and Carlos Hernandez Cordova, 29, told  
Spanish radio WQBA Thursday they were taunted and cursed. ```This 
is our country,' they told us,'' Hernandez said. 
</P>
<P>
	They said they were forced to look into a camera while holding a  
photo of Castro. When they protested, they were told to hold the 
photo higher, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The allegations are so disgustingly outrageous that if there's  
any truth to them I certainly expect more than a reassignment,'' 
said Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla. ``That's blatant 
psychological torture reminiscent of a totalitarian state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Janet Reno said she was ``deeply troubled'' by the  
allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no room for abusive conduct among the ranks of our  
law enforcement personnel,'' Ms. Reno said in a joint statement 
with Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder. ``We take these, and all 
such allegations, extremely seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Justice said the allegations will be reviewed  
by its Office of Inspector General and its Civil Rights Division. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard also is investigating its treatment of the six  
refugees. Television reports showed the Coast Guard blasting the 
men with a hose as they stood in their 14-foot rowboat about 150 
yards from shore. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency then swarmed them as they jumped overboard and swam  
toward shore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
