<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One-Gun Bill Sent to Calif. Gov. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Handgun buyers in California would be  
allowed to purchase just one per month under a bill before Gov. 
Gray Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved Thursday by the Senate, is the first gun  
control measure to pass the Legislature since lawmakers vowed to 
make gun laws tougher following the massacre at a Littleton, Colo., 
high school in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, a person can walk into a store, buy countless handguns,  
and feed them to the black market where they're snatched by kids, 
felons and gang members,'' said Assemblyman Wally Knox, a Democrat 
and the bill's author. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis has not yet taken a position on the bill. Law enforcement  
authorities, federally licensed collectors and security guards in 
the nation's most populous state would be exempt from the limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents contend limiting handgun sales would infringe the  
constitutional right to bear arms and do little to make California 
safer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This law doesn't ration guns; it rations rights. It's like  
saying you can have your freedom of speech, but only once a 
month,'' said Sen. Bill Morrow, a Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Knox cited a study by Handgun Control Inc., which said about 80  
percent of the guns seized by Southern California law enforcement 
officials were originally purchased from legal gun dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 40,722 handguns were sold in California.  
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the state Senate in New Jersey passed a bill  
requiring the sale of ``smart guns'' with sensors that allow them 
to be fired only by their owners. In a compromise backed by the 
Republican Senate president, the requirement would go into effect 
only when such guns become available commercially from at least two 
manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill passed, 23-17, and now goes to the state Assembly. Gov.  
Christie Whitman, a Republican, has said she supports trigger locks 
and ``smart guns,'' althought she has not publicly said whether she 
would sign this compromise bill if it clears the Assembly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
