<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed slightly higher Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	In London, the fight for control of Allied Domecq's pubs and  
stores took center stage, while blue chips paused for breath after 
Thursday's surge. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the tussle in the brewing sector, the trend  
elsewhere in London was flat, as the FTSE-100 closed up a slight 
0.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, the CAC 40 index of most actively traded French stocks  
added 0.2 percent to finish at a record 4,620.67 points. Casino, 
the food retailer, posted the biggest gain, rising 4.6 percent. 
Renault, the car and truck maker, was the second-leading gainer 
with a 3.9 percent climb. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a fragile start, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX made a major  
comeback, closing at a yearly high of 5,519.05 points, up 0.7 
percent. Its rise was marred only by the underperformance of 
automobile shares in its home market and across much of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	But most investors were preoccupied by gains among European  
technology stocks -- notably the Frankfurt software group SAP, 
Paris-listed semiconductor maker Thomson CSF, Stockholm's Ericsson 
and Helsinki's Nokia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Auto index declined 0.7 percent -- the  
worst-hit sector Friday. Volkswagen closed down 3 percent -- the 
biggest decliner of the Frankfurt market -- and DaimlerChrysler lost 
1.5 percent after it reported a 5 percent dip in June U.S. sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 594 European companies and the Dow  
Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 295 companies in countries 
that joined the euro single currency, both closed up 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan's MIBtel index slipped to close down 0.01 percent, and  
Madrid's IBEX-35 index was up 0.3 percent. Among smaller markets, 
Budapest's BUX ended up 1.8 percent, Dublin's ISEQ rose 1.7 
percent, and Prague fell 1.5 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
