<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fraud Suit Standards Tightened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- In a victory for high-technology companies  
and others facing securities fraud suits, a federal appeals court 
ruled Friday that such suits must be dismissed at the outset unless 
they contain detailed evidence of deliberate fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 2-1 ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said a  
business-sponsored 1995 federal law, passed over President 
Clinton's veto, was intended to set a strict standard to discourage 
meritless suits. 
</P>
<P>
	That means a suit, when filed, must allege ``in the greatest  
detail possible'' what company officials knew, and how they knew 
it, when they made the statements that were the basis of the fraud 
claims, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockholders' lawyers said they would appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	The territory covered by the nine-state circuit court includes  
California's Silicon Valley, home of companies that have been 
frequent targets of securities suits. Those suits typically follow 
a drop in stock prices and claim that company insiders issued 
misleading statements while selling their own stock at a profit. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling conflicted with interpretations by the federal  
Securities and Exchange Commission and most other federal courts, 
which have declared standards that would let more suits survive 
pretrial challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, the other  
major forum for securities fraud suits, ruled earlier this year 
that it was enough to allege facts showing that a company or its 
executives had the motive and opportunity to commit fraud or acted 
recklessly -- a considerably more lenient test than Friday's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	A disagreement among appellate courts makes Supreme Court review  
more likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a reason for every American who's got wealth tied to  
the stock market to care'' about the dispute, said Joseph 
Grundfest, a professor of law and business at Stanford Law School. 
``We don't want frivolous litigation, but on the other hand we 
don't want fraud. Congress adopted a very unclear statute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposing parties in the case disagreed on the effect of the  
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The details required by the court wouldn't be available even to  
a company's chief executive, said Paul F. Bennett, lawyer for a 
stockholder who accused a computer company of stock manipulation 
and insider trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Vanyo, lawyer for Silicon Graphics Inc., countered that  
the ruling merely required investors to show ``that they have a 
real factual basis for their claim of fraud, as opposed to bad news 
and a stock drop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which makes desktop graphic workstations, and six  
officers were accused by stockholders of hiding bad news about a 
new product between September and December 1995. The officers sold 
large numbers of shares before the information was disclosed and 
the stock price plunged, the suits alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	The suits said fraud was shown by internal company reports  
showing problems with the product while officers were making 
optimistic public statements. 
</P>
<P>
	But the court, upholding a lower-court ruling, said the  
allegations weren't specific enough under the Private Securities 
Litigation Reform Act of 1995. That law requires shareholder fraud 
suits to state, in their initial pleadings, ``facts giving rise to 
a strong inference'' of deliberate fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Those facts must demonstrate at least ``deliberate or conscious  
recklessness,'' said the opinion by Judge Joseph Sneed. He said the 
claims against Silicon Graphics failed to allege what was in the 
company reports, who prepared them and who read them; also, the 
stock sales, though substantial, weren't unusual enough to show 
they were probably based on inside information. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is In re Silicon Graphics, 97-16204.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
