<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Aversion to Movie Violence Drops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For all the talk, an Associated Press poll  
suggests that Americans don't seem to be as upset by violent movies 
as they used to be. The poll found that 40 percent of adults said 
they would be less likely to see a movie if they knew it contained 
violence. That's 20 points lower than the percentage who answered 
the same question the same way a decade ago. In the poll, conducted 
by ICR of Media, Pa., only one-third of respondents said violence 
is the biggest problem with current movies, about the same 
percentage who said tickets cost too much. An additional 17 percent 
said movies aren't as good as they used to be, and 13 percent said 
there is too much sex on the big screen. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Discloses $1.7M Income  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush reported today that  
he earned between $1.7 million and $9.7 million last year, mostly 
from selling his interests in oil, gas, real estate and the Texas 
Rangers professional baseball team. The early front-runner for the 
GOP presidential nomination also reported to the Federal Election 
Commission that he received a $106,250 advance for an unspecified 
book that he plans to donate to youth charities. The younger Bush 
reported no debts and listed a diversified trust valued at between 
$1 million and $5 million as his largest asset. He also reported 
owning more than a half million dollars in U.S. Treasury notes. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgrade Seeks Kosovo Troop Return  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Yugoslavia asked the Security Council  
today to allow for the return of Yugoslav forces into Kosovo to 
help maintain security that it claims has seriously lagged since 
international peacekeepers arrived. In a letter to the council, 
Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic urged the council to implement 
an aspect of the June 3 peace agreement that would allow for the 
return of hundreds of Yugoslav forces to the province. The peace 
deal set no timeframe for the return of Serb troops to the province 
and restricts them to guarding Serb monasteries and other religious 
sites in the province. 

</P>
<P>
	Bald Eagle May Leave Endangered List  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Once near extinction, the American bald eagle  
is ``now back from the brink, thriving in virtually every state of 
the union,'' President Clinton declared today at a White House 
celebration. Clinton announced a proposal to remove the majestic 
bird from the endangered species list after a three decade effort 
to protect it. A final decision is expected in July 2000. ``It's 
hard to think of a better way to celebrate the birth of a nation 
than to celebrate the rebirth of our national symbol,'' the 
president said on the eve of the Independence Day weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Arson Suspected at Abortion Clinic  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Arson was suspected in a fire early  
today at a clinic where abortions are performed. The blaze caused 
slight damage to the outside of the complex but no injuries were 
reported. The fire at the Choice Medical Group was contained about 
20 minutes after it was reported at 3:20 a.m., said fire dispatcher 
Tom Shotwell. ``We know only that it was an apparent arson,'' said 
FBI spokesman Nick Rossi. Last month, arson fires were set at three 
synagogues in the Sacramento area, causing an estimated $1 million 
in damage. There have been no arrests. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 59; Nasdaq Up 22  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 59.52 points at 11,125.94. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,489-1,337. The Nasdaq was up 22.07 
at 2,728.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Wings' Driver Arrested Again  
</P>
<P>
	WESTLAND, Mich. (AP) -- The driver of the limousine that crashed  
just over two years ago, severely injuring two members of the 
Detroit Red Wings, was arrested and arraigned this morning on a 
misdemeanor drunken-driving charge. Richard Gnida was stopped after 
allegedly running a stop sign about 2 a.m., Wayne County Sheriff 
Robert Ficano said. Gnida's blood-alcohol content registered just 
above the state's legal threshold, Ficano said. Judge Gail McKnight 
entered an innocent plea on Gnida's behalf and ordered him jailed 
on $25,000 bond, not to consume alcoholic beverages and to attend 
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings twice a week. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras, Agassi, Stevenson Advance  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi are one  
victory from an All-American final on the Fourth of July. Sampras 
reached the semis when Mark Philippoussis quit with a knee injury 
today while holding a one-set lead. Agassi beat Brazil's Gustavo 
Kuerten 6-3, 6-4, 6-4. Alexandra Stevenson, an 18-year-old 
Californian, became the first qualifier in Wimbledon history to 
reach the women's semifinals, beating Jelena Dokic, 6-3, 1-6, 6-3. 
Sampras will face Britain's Tim Henman. Agassi is paired with U.S. 
Open champion Patrick Rafter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
