<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian Teen Nears Wimbledon Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- A year ago, Mirjana Lucic was living  
in fear. Now she's one match away from the Wimbledon final. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the 17-year-old Croatian upset 1998 runner-up  
Nathalie Tauziat 4-6, 6-4, 7-5 to reach the semifinals, marking an 
amazing turnaround in her fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	After long being spoken of as one of the new teen-age stars  
along with Martina Hingis, Venus and Serena Williams and Anna 
Kournikova, Lucic has made her breakthrough on tennis' biggest 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	While holding a place in tennis history by winning her debut  
tournaments in both singles and doubles, Lucic was distracted by a 
volatile relationship with her father Marinko, a former Olympic 
decathlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucik accused him of beating her whenever she lost matches, a  
charge he denies. 
</P>
<P>
	After her second round defeat at Wimbledon a year ago, she  
revealed that her father had tried to stop her from playing again, 
and the entire family -- mother Angelka, together with two brothers 
and sisters -- made the decision to move to Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``At Wimbledon (in 1998) he told me he would make sure I never  
play tennis again,'' Lucic told a Zagreb newspaper, Slobodna 
Dalmacija, after arriving in the United States. ``Beatings ... 
there have been more of them than anyone can imagine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucic, who won the 1998 Australian Open doubles title with  
Hingis, is thrilled that she made the move to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love it,'' she said Friday. ``It's perfect. I have the  
support of so many people. My whole family is very happy, healthy, 
so I enjoy it very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucic, who upset fourth-seeded Monica Seles in the third round,  
walked a tightrope to victory over Tauziat, with the Frenchwoman 
serving for the match at 5-4 in the final set. When it was over, 
Lucic raised her arms in celebration of the biggest moment of her 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beating Monica was definitely big,'' she said. ``But I would  
say this win today was bigger, because it's the first time that I'm 
playing the quarterfinals (of a Grand Slam).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucic's match against the eighth-seeded Tauziat began on  
Thursday and was repeatedly suspended by rain before being 
postponed with Tauziat leading 6-4, 3-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``We went on and off three times yesterday, and to come back  
today and be down 5-3 in the third, it's really tough,'' Lucic 
said. ``I'm very happy that I did it because it was not just about 
tennis. It's very mental, this game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
