<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India Jets Pound Islamic Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Indian fighter jets pounded Islamic  
guerrillas entrenched on Himalayan mountaintops in Kashmir today as 
advancing ground troops closed in on a strategic peak overlooking 
an Indian national highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Press Trust of India news agency said the Indian soldiers  
launched a final assault on 16,500-foot Tiger Hill on Thursday 
night after surrounding it from three sides. Local commanders said 
supply lines from the Pakistani side to the fighters had been 
broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Ground troops used shoulder-fired missiles to destroy several  
guerrilla bunkers dug into the rocky ridges below the peak, field 
commanders said. There the soldiers seized arms and ammunitions 
that would have lasted the guerrillas three months, they said, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Late this evening, warplanes hunted for fighters riding  
snowmobiles sighted northwest of the peak, air force spokesman 
Group Capt. D. N. Ganesh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Round-the-clock airstrikes for the past week accompanied the  
fiercest fighting in seven weeks between Indian soldiers and 
secessionist Islamic fighters in Indian-held Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	India says the opposing fighters include Pakistani soldiers who  
crossed the 1972 cease-fire line that divides Kashmir between the 
two neighbors. Pakistan has said its troops are engaged only in 
retaliatory shelling. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan both claim all of Kashmir, which has been the  
focus of two of the three wars between the two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Early today, suspected Islamic guerrillas attacked a village in  
India's troubled Jammu-Kashmir state, killing at least 10 Hindus, 
police said. It was the third attack on villagers this week in 
Kashmir by suspected guerrillas who have been fighting a separatist 
war since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten gunmen stormed two adjacent houses in Arahi, a village three  
miles from the cease-fire line, and gunned down six men, two women 
and two children, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting in Kashmir will not delay Indian general elections,  
expected to be held before the first week of October, India's chief 
election commissioner, M.S. Gill, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kashmir conflict has generated international concern because  
India and Pakistan tested nuclear weapons last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan repeated calls today for peace talks between the two  
countries. A government statement said New Delhi must understand 
the ``serious consequences of a wider conflict.'' India has 
rejected any dialogue over the hostilities unless the fighters are 
withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighboring China appealed to the two rivals Thursday to respect  
the 27-year-old dividing line and resume negotiations to ``seek a 
fair and reasonable settlement of all their differences.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
