<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Leaves Talks With North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- South Korea pulled its negotiators out of talks  
with North Korea today after the North refused to discuss reuniting 
separated families. 
</P>
<P>
	Seoul decided to suspend the shipments of fertilizer that had  
coaxed North Korea to the negotiating table until Pyongyang decides 
to discuss the reunions in good faith, said South Korea's chief 
negotiator, Vice Unification Minister Yang Young-shik. 
</P>
<P>
	``So long as the North does not change its position or attitude  
concerning these talks, we believe that is meaningless to continue 
on like this and have decided to go back to Korea,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea's decision came as the talks in Beijing reached an  
impasse. After the last of three sessions ended inconclusively 
Thursday, North Korea's official news agency said no more meetings 
would be held until South Korea shipped more fertilizer. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks were the highest level government contacts between the  
communist North and capitalist South in 14 months. In both cases, 
negotiations broke down over reuniting 10 million people separated 
from relatives by the division of the Korean peninsula 54 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korean negotiators -- headed by an official who once  
threatened to turn Seoul into a ``sea of fire'' -- appeared 
combative during the talks, huffily walking out of two of the three 
sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Yang said the North Koreans refused to shake hands, left  
sessions abruptly and showed no interest in rescheduling another 
meeting after Thursday's talks. They repeatedly raised the issue of 
last month's sinking of a North Korean gunboat in the Yellow or 
West Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	``This sort of behavior or actions by the North tells us they  
are not fully prepared to talks about the separated family issue,'' 
Yang said. ``Perhaps because of the West Sea incident they need 
time to reorganize themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In last month's fight in the disputed sea, one North Korean  
gunboat sank and several others were heavily damaged. About 30 
North Korean sailors were believed to have died. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Korean border village of Panmunjom, North Korean Lt. Gen.  
Ri Chan Bok told the U.N. Command today that ``more serious blood'' 
will flow unless South Korea's navy stops intruding into its 
territorial waters in the Yellow Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Ri's remarks were carried by the North's foreign news outlet,  
KCNA. 
</P>
<P>
	The KCNA report said Ri charged that South Korea's navy has  
violated the North's territorial waters in and around the disputed 
zone 63 times since the June skirmish. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Maj. Gen. Michael M. Dunn, representing the U.N. Command,  
denied the North Korean charges and urged the North's navy to stay 
out of the contested area, command officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Beijing, Yang accused North Korea of violating an agreement  
made last month, under which the North promised to discuss 
reuniting families split by the 54-year division of the Korean 
Peninsula in return for fertilizer it badly needs to help revive 
its flagging agriculture sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Yang also said the North Koreans had promised to contact the  
South Koreans this morning but did not. 
</P>
<P>
	Withdrawing the badly needed fertilizer aid puts real pressure  
on North Korea to resume the talks quickly to get the rest of the 
fertilizer in time to use on summer crops, Yang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign aid groups have warned that the upcoming harvest will be  
meager without fertilizer for spent fields and fuel to run farm 
machinery. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Pyongyang and Seoul appeared to have compelling reasons to  
strike a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Successive years of floods and droughts wrecked North Korea's  
already struggling economy, leaving it dependent on international 
aid to stave off famine. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean President Kim Dae-jung has staked much political  
capital on a more open policy toward North Korea and needs proof of 
success to fend off domestic critics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
