<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Medicare Plan Offers Saving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A little-noticed part of President Clinton's  
plan to overhaul Medicare would offer retirees the chance to save 
money if they see doctors who agree to special discount contracts 
with the health insurance program for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beneficiaries would pay lower cost-sharing when using  
preferred providers,'' said a document released by the White House 
late Friday, offering more details of proposed changes to Medicare 
that Clinton announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has not specified how much of a discount  
would be offered to retirees who used designated doctors. 
Currently, beneficiaries pay 20 percent of the costs of doctors' 
office visits regardless of which doctor they see. 
</P>
<P>
	The new system would make Medicare more like private managed  
care health plans, known as preferred provider organizations, in 
which many working-age Americans are enrolled. 
</P>
<P>
	People in such plans, commonly known as PPOs, can choose to see  
any doctor they want and still get reimbursed by insurers for a 
portion of the costs. But those who choose from a designated 
network of doctors, with whom the insurance company has worked out 
special pricing deals, pay less out of pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea would be to encourage Medicare beneficiaries to see  
doctors who have agreed to fee arrangements that would also save 
the government money. Such arrangements would not be limited to 
doctors under Clinton's plan, but also could include other types of 
health care providers. 
</P>
<P>
	``By selecting providers for special designation and providing  
beneficiaries incentives to use these providers, Medicare would be 
able to purchase high-quality services and items at more 
competitive rates, as private plans are able to do now,'' said the 
administration document. 
</P>
<P>
	To set up the new system, Medicare would likely contract with  
groups of doctors who already participate in similar private-sector 
arrangements, the administration document said. Those who agreed to 
participate would be offered perks by Medicare, such as faster 
claims payment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
