<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RNC Asks for 'Soft Money' Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican National Committee is asking  
presidential candidates to help raise money for ads that would 
benefit the eventual GOP nominee next year. Both parties were 
criticized for such advertising strategies in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In a June 18 letter, RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson asked candidates  
to encourage people who have reached the $1,000 maximum for 
campaign donations to send additional money to the party for an 
``aggressive issue-advertising campaign'' designed to counter 
Democratic ads like those that helped re-elect President Clinton in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let your donors know that once they have reached their  
contribution limit, ... all further support should be channeled to 
the RNC,'' Nicholson wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Many advocates of changing the campaign-finance laws view the  
tactic of directing contributions to the party for ``issue ads'' as 
a way to circumvent Watergate-inspired contribution and spending 
limits for presidential campaigns. The law requires that personal 
donations in excess of $1,000 go to the party as ``soft money'' for 
use in ``party-building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	RNC spokesman Mike Collins said ``it should come as no  
surprise'' that they seek donations from supporters of Republican 
presidential candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's election law is so ridiculously complex that most  
Americans are unaware that, while their freedom to support a 
presidential candidate is restricted, they can still assist the 
candidate's political party,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee has never sent this kind of  
letter to its candidates, and it has no plans to do so, said 
spokeswoman Jenny Backus. But She said the party was keeping its 
options open on issue advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	The RNC letter says candidates will be informed which of their  
contributors make donations to the Republican ``Media 2000'' ad 
campaign, which will begin after the presidential primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will assure them that you will be aware of their  
significant support,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	RNC spokesman Mark Pfeifle confirmed wording of the letter,  
which was first published Friday in The Arizona Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, with an early lead in the polls and a  
record $36 million in fund raising, will not tell his contributors 
to donate to the RNC advertising campaign, spokesman Dave Beckwith 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are currently pursuing our own fund-raising efforts and  
will do so through the primary season. After the primaries are over 
I'm sure we'll work closely with the RNC,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said the Forbes  
office was reviewing the letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates of campaign finance reform have long criticized ``soft  
money,'' unlimited, unregulated donations that are supposed to help 
finance general political party activities but not to help elect 
federal candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Both national parties were criticized for using ``issue ads''  
paid for with soft money to help their presidential candidates in 
1996. But the Justice Department, after looking into the matter, 
found no evidence the ads violated election law. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Election Commission rejected its auditors'  
recommendation that the campaigns of Clinton and GOP nominee Bob 
Dole repay millions of dollars in federal funds because of the ads. 
But commissioners have begun trying to clarify the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all completely legal, and it's exactly why we need reform  
of the campaign finance system,'' said Jodie Silverman, spokeswoman 
for Public Campaign, a group advocating campaign finance reform. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
