<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Verrett Stars in Broadway Revival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                  *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was 1903 when ``In Dahomey,'' a musical  
comedy in which most of the performers are black, first opened on 
Broadway, running 53 performances. A sprightly revival, starring 
Shirley Verrett, is now appearing at the off-Broadway Harry de Jur 
Playhouse in the Henry Street Settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only is it fascinating to see a Broadway show from that era,  
but ``In Dahomey'' is entertaining on its own terms, especially its 
songs. Besides Shirley Verrett, who sang in ``Carousel'' on 
Broadway after leaving the Metropolitan Opera, LaTrice Verrett, who 
plays her daughter and is not related to her, stood out in the 
cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Marion Cook, a noted composer and orchestra leader in his  
day, wrote the music, and Paul Laurence Dunbar was one of the 
lyricists. The vaudevillians Bert Williams and George Walker were 
in the original cast. Williams recorded two of the songs, now on CD 
compilations. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Shauneille Perry has worked on the book. She omitted a  
couple of songs from the original and used ``Brown Skin Baby of 
Mine'' and ``I Want To Be an Actor Lady,'' which Cook added to an 
early revival. 
</P>
<P>
	The plot, which exists as an excuse for some very attractive  
songs, requires a cast of 11. They rehearse a show, which will be a 
benefit for the African nation of Dahomey. There, LaTrice Verrett 
sings ``I Want To Be an Actor Lady'' to the displeasure of Shirley 
Verrett's character, who describes herself when she sings ``Colored 
Aristocracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In another plot line, Kim Sullivan, playing a prince from  
Dahomey, hires two American detectives for some work back in his 
country. The two, played by Brian Chandler and Keith Lee Grant, 
both sang and danced well but need more presence. 
</P>
<P>
	Act 2, set in Dahomey, sags a bit as the plot is talked. In the  
livelier Act 1, most of it is sung. 
</P>
<P>
	What used to be known as ``parlor songs'' are heard in this  
musical -- and when does one get a chance to hear anything from that 
charming genre these days? There also is ``Cake Walk,'' a favorite 
of Cook's and Dunbar's. And there is ``I'm a Jonah Man,'' which 
expresses the hard-luck character Williams created for himself for 
vaudeville. 
</P>
<P>
	Act 2 has a pleasing love song, ``My Dahomian Queen,'' sung by  
Cedric D. Cannon to Shirley Verrett. Cannon also has sung opera and 
musical comedy, as Old Deuteronomy in ``Cats'' in Hamburg, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	By play's end, the problem needing detecting in Dahomey is  
solved, without much help from the detectives. They do manage to 
solve their romantic rivalry. They both loved the same girl back in 
Florida, where the benefit show was staged. One gets her in the 
final scene. The other wins an African sweetheart who will come to 
America later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
