<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Brazil Stock Markets Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's stock market is making a strong comeback  
less than a year after the economy crashed, but fears of getting 
burned twice have tempered investors' urge to snap up low-priced 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	And on the Brazilian stock market, the long roller coaster ride  
touched off by the Asian financial crisis two years ago seems to 
have subsided, but analysts warned that Brazil is still not out of 
the woods. 
</P>
<P>
	Fueled by expectations of a new $4.5 billion loan from the  
International Monetary Fund and higher world oil prices, the 
Russian Trading System index rose 1.6 percent Friday to close at 
133.67 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is up 110 percent since last year's crash, a  
remarkable turnaround after the troubles set off by Asia's 
financial crash in the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly bankrupt, Russia was forced to default on its debt last  
August and devalue the ruble, sending the market into a tailspin. 
Spooked by rumors of everything from government nationalization to 
the return of communism, investors fled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russia limped through the crisis and its market has bounced  
back in spite of political turmoil that saw three prime ministers 
and new Cabinets with each one. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, trading volumes on Russia's market these days are  
modest. On Friday, the volume reached $27 million, far below 
pre-crisis levels but still up from recent volumes of about $5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebound is largely attributed to new IMF optimism and talk  
of more credits. Also, the government has made some headway in 
persuading creditors to reschedule its Soviet-era debts, which 
account for about two-thirds of its $150 billion foreign debt 
burden. 
</P>
<P>
	But the fact that prices are so low are certainly not a  
deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
	``People started buying Russian shares again mostly because the  
price is so low,'' Boris Fyodorov, former tax minister, wrote this 
week in Segodnya daily. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brazil, the Bovespa index of the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange --  
Latin America's largest -- has averaged a healthy 11,300 points in 
the last four months. Investors, however, are still cautious, 
because they believe Brazil will remain vulnerable to external 
shocks until it puts its fiscal house in order. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bovespa index had reached a high of about 14,000 points in  
August 1997 but then dropped later that year, hitting 7,800 points 
on Nov. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic struck. Investors pulled their money from Brazil. The  
Central Bank spent $10 billion to shore up the real currency and 
interest rates skyrocketed to 43 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A fiscal austerity package announced by the government in late  
1997 breathed life back into Brazilian stocks, which returned to 
the 12,000-point range by April 1998, but the euphoria was 
short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia defaulted on some of its debt, and the index nose-dived  
to less than 5,000 points in September of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	With the help of a $41.5 billion rescue package, stitched  
together by the IMF in November of 1998, and the Jan. 15 currency 
devaluation that made share prices cheaper in dollar terms, the 
markets slowly inched up to their current levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``While in nominal terms share prices have made a significant  
recovery, in dollar terms they are still some 20 percent below 
their pre-Asian crisis levels,'' said Odair Abate, chief economist 
at Lloyds Bank in Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	Worrying investors, he said, were stubborn budget and trade  
deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, official figures also show Brazil's unemployment  
rate at close to 8 percent. But in Sao Paulo, Latin America's 
largest city, labor unions say the jobless rate is 20 percent of 
the work force -- more than 1.7 million people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
