<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Official Urges Passage of FAA Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The transportation secretary is urging the  
Senate to pass a bill renewing the Federal Aviation Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which has been delayed three times, includes critical  
funding for airport and air traffic control modernization, 
management changes at the FAA and a long-term, stable source of 
income for the agency. The latest extension expires on Aug. 6, the 
day Congress is scheduled to begin its summer recess. 
</P>
<P>
	``I clearly think it needs to be made more of a priority,''  
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said Thursday in an 
interview with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged Senate leaders to pass the bill if only so it can be  
moved into a conference committee, where it can be reconciled with 
similar legislation already passed by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	It is in such committees that most congressional horse-trading  
occurs. The committees are also a prerequisite to developing a 
completed piece of legislation for final votes in the House and 
Senate and signature by the president. 
</P>
<P>
	While Slater refused to comment, legislative sources say the  
bill is hung up in the Senate over two issues favored by Sen. John 
McCain, R-Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator, who is chairman of the Commerce Committee, wants  
increased flights at airports in New York, Washington and Chicago, 
as well as 24 daily exemptions to the current 1,250-mile limit on 
flights from Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who is running for the Republican presidential  
nomination, has said both changes would benefit business and 
consumers alike. Legislators from the surrounding areas have fought 
back, saying the changes would increase noise and create safety 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator's spokeswoman said that, like Slater, McCain wants  
the legislation resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is McCain's intention to have comprehensive legislation  
pass this year,'' said spokeswoman Pia Pialorsi. ``We're simply 
waiting for (Senate Majority Leader Trent) Lott to schedule it for 
floor action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for whether McCain remained insistent on the flight and  
perimeter-rule provisions, Pialorsi said: ``He will try to pass the 
bill that passed the committee.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
