<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-U.K. Aviation Talks Off Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and the United Kingdom were  
supposed to reconvene formal talks about a new aviation agreement 
next week but instead have postponed them indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials expressed disappointment Thursday about the  
decision announced by the British government in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been nine months since we last had formal talks with the  
British government ... and the time frame for accomplishing such an 
agreement is growing increasingly short,'' said Transportation 
Department spokesman Bill Schulz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear from what we've seen from the other side is  
there's an inability to develop a position,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hang-up reportedly stems from a dispute between British  
Airways and officials in the British Office of Fair Trading, as 
well as the country's transport offices. Both entities want the 
airline to surrender takeoff and landing slots at London's popular 
Heathrow Airport, but the airline apparently is balking at the 
number. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have insisted on more slots since British Airways  
proposed an alliance with American Airlines in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current aviation treaty, known as Bermuda II, only two  
U.S. carriers -- American and United Airlines -- are allowed to fly 
into Heathrow. Business travelers in particular like the airport 
because it offers the most connections to international points. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an ``open skies'' deal, an unlimited number of carriers  
could serve any U.S. or British airport. U.S. officials believe 
added access to Heathrow would drive down airfares and give 
customers more flight selections. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations collapsed last fall after only three days of  
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, top transportation officials from both countries said  
preliminary talks would resume, with an eye toward returning to 
formal negotiations. Recently, both governments announced the 
formal talks would take place next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The British government said in a statement: ``We are still  
refining our negotiating position in talks with the airlines. We've 
postponed our talks and no alternative date has been set.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 09:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Face Brazil in Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- Brazil vs. the United States. Fourth of  
July. Stanford, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Again.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the two nations met at Stanford Stadium in the men's  
World Cup. Brazil won 1-0 and went on to win the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years later, the same countries, the same venue and the  
same red-white-and-blue date are the setting for Sunday's semifinal 
in the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Only this time, the United States will be the favorite.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every game is a different story. Sometimes the same story  
repeats,'' Brazilian coach Wilson de Oliveira said. ``We hope this 
story repeats. We have a dream. If we can emulate what happened in 
this stadium five years ago, our dream will come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams advanced with one-goal victories Thursday night. With  
President Clinton and his family among the 54,642 fans at Jack Kent 
Cooke Stadium, defenders Brandi Chastain and Joy Fawcett scored off 
corner kicks to rally the U.S. team from a 2-1 halftime deficit in 
a 3-2 victory over Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we'll have to play better against Brazil,'' said coach  
Tony DiCicco, whose team overcame its first real test after winning 
its three first-round games by a combined scored of 13-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil blew a 3-0 halftime lead against Nigeria before Sissi  
scored the first sudden-death overtime goal in Women's World Cup 
history. The midfielder's 22-yard free kick, her tournament-high 
seventh goal, won the game 4-3 in the 104th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the game I turned into an old man,'' de Oliveira said.  
``But after the game I became a young man again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results mean all four teams have qualified for the 2000  
Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The doubleheader was evidence of the unexpected surge in  
popularity of the biggest all-women's sports event ever. Extra 
seats were made available to meet demand, and the crowd was late 
arriving because of a 20-mile backup to the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, also arriving late, watched the second half of the  
U.S.-Germany match from a luxury box with wife Hillary, daughter 
Chelsea, two of Chelsea's friends and Health and Human Services 
Secretary Donna Shalala. 
</P>
<P>
	After the match, the presidential party met the U.S. team in the  
locker room. The players chanted ``Clinton'' as he posed for a 
group picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told us what an inspiration the team was, coming from  
behind,'' midfielder Julie Foudy said. ``I told him thanks for 
coming, it makes a ton of difference for this team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Down 2-1, the Americans tied the score in the 49th minute when  
Chastain volleyed in Mia Hamm's corner kick. 
</P>
<P>
	Fawcett, who almost never joins the attack -- she had 18 goals in  
140 international games heading into the World Cup -- scored the 
game-winner in the 66th when she was positioned perfectly for a 
side header past the outstretched arm of goalkeeper Silke 
Rottenberg. The corner kick came from Shannon MacMillan, who had 
entered the game seconds earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	As it has the whole tournament, the U.S. team came out sloppy.  
Chastain, who later would sustain a mile ankle sprain, played a 
loose ball back to goalkeeper Briana Scurry. Scurry wasn't 
expecting it, and the result was an own goal for Germany in the 
fifth minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffeny Milbrett's low shot tied the game in the 16th minute,  
but Germany regained the lead in injury time when Bettina Wiegmann 
made a move around Cindy Parlow and sent a 22-yard rocket into the 
top left corner of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	That prompted an urgent halftime talk from U.S. captain Carla  
Overbeck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carla said that everything we done in this lifetime comes down  
to these 45 minutes,'' Foudy said. ``We had 45 minutes to make a 
difference. That's it and we had to leave everything on the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the second game, Sissi played a part in all four Brazilian  
goals. Her free kick started a sequence that led to Cidinha's score 
in the fourth minute, and her chip from the corner of the penalty 
box was headed home by Cidinha at the far post in the 22nd. 
</P>
<P>
	Sissi then played the ball to Nene for a 40-yard chip that  
sailed over goalkeeper Ann Chiejine's head from the right flank in 
the 35th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria rallied with goals from Prisca Emeafu, Nkiru Okosieme  
and Nkechi Egbe before Sissi's ``Golden Goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, Sissi is the queen of soccer,'' de Oliveira said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990702.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Negotiations in N. Ireland Fail  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Negotiations on a new  
government for Northern Ireland failed Friday, prompting the 
British and Irish prime ministers to launch an alternative plan to 
jump-start the government in the next 16 days. However, serious 
doubts remained that the plan -- devised by Britain's Tony Blair and 
Ireland's Bertie Ahern -- could ever get off the ground, since key 
parties in Northern Ireland did not endorse it. The talks this week 
stumbled over the long-running issue of disarming the Irish 
Republican Army. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Calls Arafat To Discuss Peace  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak broke weeks of  
silence on peace issues Friday with a friendly telephone call to 
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. With his government due to take 
office next week, Barak told Arafat he would take up the mantle of 
slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin to restore confidence in the 
stalled negotiations and bring peace to the region, his office 
said. The two leaders agreed to meet soon after Barak takes office, 
expected on July 7. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Sees Serb Threat on Montenegro  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and his  
army are threatening Montenegro with the presence of some 40,000 
troops, four times the normal strength in the republic, the Clinton 
administration said Friday. State Department spokesman James Foley 
said the troops were a threat to the democratically elected 
government of President Milo Djukanovic. The smaller of 
Yugoslavia's two republics behind much stronger and larger Serbia, 
Montenegro has staked out an independent course from Belgrade, 
thereby pleasing the Clinton administration. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Kim Warn NKorea on Missiles  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and South Korean President  
Kim Dae-jung agreed Friday that any further long-range ballistic 
missile tests by North Korea would pose ``a serious obstacle to 
peace.'' At the same time, the two leaders ruled out the 
possibility of responding to a new missile test by disavowing the 
1994 U.S.-North Korean agreement, under which the North pledged not 
to become a nuclear power. Clinton and Kim, who met for two hours, 
did not discuss the actual measures that would be taken in the 
event of a new missile test, senior officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Boorda's Navy Record Won't Change  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- The Navy has decided that the official  
record of Adm. Jeremy ``Mike'' Boorda, who committed suicide amid 
questions about Vietnam combat decorations he had worn, should 
continue to show he did not earn the medals. Boorda, who joined the 
Navy at 16 and became the only enlisted man to rise to chief of 
naval operations, took his life in 1996 after 40 years of service. 
He was about to be asked by Newsweek reporters about why he wore 
Combat Vs -- tiny bronze letters standing for ``valor.'' Wearing an 
unauthorized decoration is a severe breach of military protocol. 

</P>
<P>
	UN OK's Population Growth Proposals  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Delegates from 180 countries Friday  
approved proposals to slow world population growth -- including 
calls for giving women greater access to abortion and adolescents 
to sex education. Approval came despite reservations from a few 
conservative countries and the Vatican. But women's groups hailed 
the agreement as a giant advance beyond what was agreed to at the 
landmark 1994 U.N. population conference in Cairo because it 
compels governments to take action to increase and improve access 
to reproductive health care. 

</P>
<P>
	Economy Booming for All  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A record-length peacetime economic expansion  
is reaching groups that often lag behind. The jobless rate for 
blacks fell to a record low of 7.3 percent in June, the Labor 
Department said Friday. And rates for women and Hispanics remained 
close to their lowest levels in three decades. The economy is still 
roaring ahead, creating more than a quarter-million new jobs 
overall in June. Though the overall unemployment rate crept up to 
4.3 percent, all industries except manufacturing and mining posted 
solid gains. Financial markets were buoyed by today's report. The 
Dow Jones industrial average posted a record high close, up 72.82 
points to 11,139.24. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros Snap Reds' Winning Streak  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Carl Everett had four hits, including an  
inside-the-park homer and a two-run double, as the Houston Astros 
ended Cincinnati's 10-game winning streak with a 7-5 victory 
Friday. Jeff Bagwell hit his 26th homer as Houston, stung by 
Cincinnati's four-game sweep at the Astrodome last weekend, pulled 
back into a first-place tie with the Reds in the NL Central. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By ELIZABETH KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
