<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Retools Inner Circle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to energize his presidential campaign,  
Vice President Al Gore is retooling his inner circle with additions 
of a new media consultant, policy adviser and pollster. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not termed a shakeup, advisers said the changes were part  
of a significant reorganization that would diminish the roles of 
some aides, redefine the jobs of others and create the potential 
for personality conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of consultant Carter Eskew creates the greatest  
shift in authority, cutting into the wide range of chores handled 
by longtime Gore confidant Bob Squier. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is bracing for a challenge for the Democratic nomination  
from former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley. His political situation 
is complicated by the surging Republican candidacy of George W. 
Bush, the Texas governor who is handily beating Gore in 
head-to-head public opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are defining roles and responsibilities and we're adding  
strong members to the team when appropriate,'' campaign chairman 
Tony Coelho said Thursday when told that Democratic officials were 
privately leaking word of the hirings. 
</P>
<P>
	He confirmed the addition of Eskew, pollster Celinda Lake and  
policy coordinator Lauren Choi, saying several more new advisers 
will be hired soon. Denying reports he planned to clean house, 
Coelho said, ``There will be no dismissals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Eskew adds an awkward personal dynamic to Gore's  
inner circle. He and Squier are former business partners who had a 
bitter falling out. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no evidence that their relationship has mended, and it  
was unclear how Squier would accept the changes, officials familiar 
with the hirings said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing that I'm interested in is that they both share  
with me one common desire and that is to get Al Gore elected,'' 
Coelho said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob is a key strategist, adviser and friend of Al Gore's. He's  
been that for years and he will remain that,'' Coelho said. 
</P>
<P>
	Squier will focus now on his specialty, political advertising.  
Eskew will work to refine Gore's message. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign officials compared Coelho's plans with efforts by  
former White House chief of staff Leon Panetta to reshape President 
Clinton's staff after his first administration got off to a shaky 
start. Heads didn't roll, but Panetta retooled many job 
descriptions and drew clear lines of authority in the West Wing. 
</P>
<P>
	Eskew, in his mid-40s, is a longtime confidant of Gore and  
worked on Clinton's 1992 campaign. He is a partner in the issues 
advocacy firm of Bozell Eskew. His clients include pharmaceutical 
manufacturers, a life insurance foundation and Empire Blue 
Cross/Blue Shield, New York state's largest health care company. 
</P>
<P>
	He also produced a multimillion-dollar advertising campaign for  
the tobacco industry that is credited with helping kill the 
Senate's tobacco bill last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Squier was quoted by The Washington Post as saying, ``He  
certainly would not have been allowed to represent a client like 
this inside our company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eskew and Squier did not return telephone calls.  
</P>
<P>
	Lake's hiring beefs up Gore's polling operation, run by Mark  
Penn. Choi is moving from a senior post at the Treasury Department. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
