<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 14:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boldon Wins Men's 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Ato Boldon won the men's 100-meter  
showdown Friday night at the Athletissima track and field meet, 
beating world record-holder and training partner Maurice Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones, the world champion in the women's 100, won in  
10.80 seconds, the fastest time of the year, and Michael Johnson 
showed he had recovered from a quadricep injury, winning in 43.92, 
also the year's best time. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, surged down the lightning quick  
Pontaise track in 9.86, tying the season's second-best time and his 
personal best. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last thing my mother said was, `Don't run 9.86 again,' ''  
Boldon, who has run the 100 in 9.86 four times, said laughing. 
``Maybe they were expecting a record, but it is nothing to be 
ashamed of when you hit your personal best for the second time in 
three weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon also ran 9.86 at Athens last month, but finished second  
to Greene, who shattered the world record in 9.79. This time, 
Boldon finished .07 seconds ahead of Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were anybody else I'd probably be upset,'' Greene said.  
``But I'm not unhappy. I ran the best race that I could today. He 
just ran better than me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Jason Gardener broke the 10-second barrier for the  
first time in his career, placing third in 9.98. Olympic silver 
medalist Frank Fredericks of Namibia was fourth in 10.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian Bruny Surin, who had run under 10 seconds his previous  
three races including a wind-aided 9.88 at the Canadian 
championships last week, withdrew at the last minute because of 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was fresh off a victory in the 200 at Oslo Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Sevatheda Fynes of the Bahamas finished second in the women's  
100 in 10.91, ahead of Inger Miller, the U.S. champion, who was 
third in 11.02. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is unbeaten in a race since losing to Jamaica's Merlene  
Ottey in the 100 at Tokyo in September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who skipped a 200 showdown against Greene at the U.S.  
Championships last week because of the injury, became the first 400 
runner under 44 seconds this season. It was Johnson's 72nd win in 
74 finals in the 400. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't too concerned with my time,'' Johnson said. ``I was  
more intent on finding my form and the right feeling on the track 
after five weeks off. 
</P>
<P>
	``My injury was painful, but now I feel good.''  
</P>
<P>
	Jerome Young, the U.S. champion, was second in 44.34.  
</P>
<P>
	Making up for a disappointing seventh-place at the U.S.  
Championships, Larry Wade registered the season's fastest time in 
the men's 110 hurdles with 13.01. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be the best at what I do,'' Wade said. ``I don't  
have a time or a championship to aspire to. I just want to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wade led an American sweep, as Mark Crear was second in 13.04  
and Olympic gold medalist Allen Johnson third in 13.10. Britain's 
Colin Jackson, the world record-holder indoors and outdoors, 
finished fourth in 13.13. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Daniel Komen of Kenya set a meet record in  
the 3,000 of 7:30.62. Komen led a Kenyan sweep of the top six 
places, with Paul Bitok second in 7:36.25 and five-time world 
cross-country champion Paul Tergat third in 7:42.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Moroccans women had a good day, setting two meet records. Hasna  
Benhassi won the 800 in 1:57.45 and Nezha Bidouane took the 400 
hurdles in 53.08. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Morrison made up for a bad stumble at the U.S.  
Championships, winning the women's 100 hurdles in 12.74, .01 second 
ahead of. Nigeria's Glory Alozie. 
</P>
<P>
	Norberto Tellez of Cuba won the men's 800 in 1:44.05, the  
second-fastest time of the season. Kenya's Kennedy Kimwetich was 
second in 1:44.13 and Olympic silver medalist Hezekiel Sepeng of 
South Africa third in 1:44.31. 
</P>
<P>
	Falilat Ogunkoya of Nigeria posted the fastest time of the  
season in the women's 400 with 50.01, nearly a half-second ahead of 
Jamaica's Lorraine Graham. Suziann Reid, runner-up at the U.S. 
Championships, finished third. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
