<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Sues Rival Over iMac Design </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc. accused a  
competitor Thursday of stealing the design of its iMac personal 
computers to make low-cost PCs unveiled at a computer show last 
week, complete with a curvy translucent look and five gemstone 
colors. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple's complaint, filed in San Jose District Court, alleges  
Future Power Technologies, an 8-month-old Silicon Valley company, 
and Korea's Daewoo Telecom illegally copied iMac's unique features 
to make their E-Power PC. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a universe of original designs that Future Power and  
Daewoo could have created for their computers, but instead they 
chose to copy Apple's designs,'' said Steve Jobs, Apple's interim 
CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've invested a lot of money and effort to create and market  
our award-winning designs, and we intend to vigorously protect them 
under the law,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo denies that it copied the iMac design. ``Our product is  
based on a totally different concept from that of iMac,'' the 
company said in a statement, noting that, unlike iMac, Daewoo's 
E-Power runs on Intel chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo acknowledged that its E-Power PC has a shape resembling  
iMac, but said Apple cannot sue just because of that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot understand the lawsuit,'' the statement said.  
</P>
<P>
	Apple, which declined to comment beyond the wording of its  
complaint, wants an injunction preventing the companies from 
distributing the E-Power computers. It's also seeking actual and 
punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Future Power created a sensation at the PC Expo in New York City  
last week with the E-power, which has a shape resembling the iMac, 
and comes in five translucent colors: amethyst, ruby, topaz, 
emerald and sapphire. 
</P>
<P>
	Also like iMac, which Apple sells in strawberry, blueberry,  
grape, tangerine and lime -- the E-power has an all-in-one design 
and a single power cord. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the iMac, the E-power runs on Microsoft's Windows  
operating system and has a floppy disk drive. Also, it is priced to 
sell at two-thirds the cost of Apple's model. 
</P>
<P>
	Wired magazine reported from the PC Expo that Future Power  
didn't deny that iMac was its source of inspiration for E-Power -- 
the startup even held talks with Apple's lawyers before launching 
the new product, presumably in hopes of heading off a legal 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Future Power said the company would not  
comment until it received a copy of the lawsuit. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
