<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Continues Abortion Funds Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abortion-rights forces have lost an attempt in  
the Senate to end a longtime ban on coverage of most abortions by 
federal workers' health-insurance plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate refused to remove the prohibition Thursday from a  
$27.7 billion bill financing the Treasury Department and smaller 
agencies for the coming fiscal year. The vote to leave the ban 
intact was 51-47. The overall bill was approved by voice vote, and 
shortly afterward the Senate adjourned for a 10-day July Fourth 
recess. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also used a voice vote to approve $411 million in  
federal contributions to the District of Columbia's city budget. 
The measure bans the use of federal or district funds for most 
abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage of both measures means the Senate has approved seven of  
the 13 annual spending bills for fiscal 2000, which starts Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The House has passed three of the measures, but none have been  
sent to President Clinton. There remains a strong possibility of 
yet another autumn spending showdown between the White House and 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury measure also raises the possibility of a $4,600  
cost-of-living pay raise next year for members of Congress. 
Legislators get an automatic annual increase unless they vote to 
deny it, under a 1989 law. The Treasury bill is the traditional 
vehicle for a provision blocking the raise, but so far there is no 
such prohibition. 
</P>
<P>
	A version of the measure approved by a House subcommittee also  
lacks language blocking the pay raise. Lawmakers currently earn 
$136,700, a level reached two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The abortion prohibition for federal employees would allow  
exceptions for cases of rape, incest and when the woman's life is 
in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, sponsored the abortion ban, saying 73  
percent of the cost of federal workers' health plans comes from 
taxpayers' dollars. He said abortions ``violate the conscience of 
many taxpayers'' and federal dollars should not be used to pay for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said the 1.2 million women  
affected by the prohibition would lose coverage for a procedure 
that privately employed women have. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can't repeal her right to choose, take away her ability  
to pay for what is legal,'' Boxer said of her opponents' tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials said in a written statement the  
White House ``would strongly oppose'' the prohibition, but did not 
mention a veto threat. The ban has been included in the bill in all 
but two years since 1983, DeWine said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury bill includes $8.2 billion for the Internal Revenue  
Service, nearly $200 million less than this year. And it would cut 
President Clinton's $195 million request for an anti-drug media 
campaign by $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the House Appropriations Committee approved a $14.1  
billion measure financing federal land and cultural programs, and 
an $8.4 billion bill for military construction projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The land bill provides nearly $1.2 billion less than Clinton  
wants, cutting his requests for land and water conservation, 
purchase of property for federal and state parks, restoration of 
Florida's Everglades and energy conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee approved an amendment by Rep. Lucille  
Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., that would allow women to breast-feed in 
national parks or cultural institutions covered by the bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
