<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic ShutOut: High School Bands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Some took on extra part-time jobs to raise  
money. Others delayed plans to attend college out of state. All had 
been learning new music all year. 
</P>
<P>
	But those preparations for a once-in-a-lifetime chance to play  
in front of millions at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia, may 
have been for nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 1,300 high school band students from the United States and  
Japan, including 800 in Southern California and several hundred 
more from Atlanta, learned this week that the Sydney Organizing 
Committee for the Olympic Games was rescinding its invitation for 
their bands to play a seven-minute show during opening ceremonies 
of the Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of upset. We put a lot of work into this,'' said Erik  
Donzella, a 15-year-old sophomore who plays the baritone at 
Valhalla High School in El Cajon, Calif., 20 miles east of San 
Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG chief Sandy Hollway said Wednesday that a reprieve for the  
students might be possible, but so far the invitations remain 
withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee had dropped the contingent of international  
children from the opening ceremonies after local radio programs and 
newspapers complained that the event should feature local culture. 
</P>
<P>
	Many students had taken on extra jobs and spent time in  
fund-raising activities to help pay for the $3,000 trip. An $800 
deposit that has already been paid will be returned if the students 
don't go to Australia, school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the same radio stations and newspapers which tore into the  
organizing committee for including foreign band members are tearing 
into them for kicking them out. 
</P>
<P>
	Band leaders from six schools in Orange and San Diego counties  
are traveling to Australia this weekend and hope to persuade 
organizers to honor the original invitations. They were originally 
scheduled to make the trip to inspect performing facilities, but it 
has turned into a lobbying effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try to convince them to turn this back  
around,'' said Roy Anthony, the band director at Valhalla High 
School. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad,'' he said. ``We're talking about an international  
competition and they have an opportunity to have an international 
band, but they're shutting us down to do their own thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hollway hinted on Wednesday that band members might be used  
after all, but perhaps in a capacity outside the opening 
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a flicker of light and certainly a sense of sympathy,  
wherever it comes out for these people overseas who have been 
affected,'' Hollway said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to speculate, don't want to raise hopes because  
there might not be feasible alternatives, but yes, it's something 
that's worth looking at. I'm exploring it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted, ``I would be hurt if there's a belief that we have  
caused hurt over there -- we probably have some explaining to do 
with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Hollway said the issue was not dead.  
</P>
<P>
	``Don't have a picture that the issue has been taken off my desk  
or simply relegated to the trash can,'' he said. ``I understand 
there's an issue here and I'm going to be doing everything I can to 
work it through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the students wait. Most aren't concerned with the  
money or time spent practicing, according to trumpet player Andrew 
Bearden, 15, of Valhalla High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``For most of the kids in my group this was going to be a big  
highlight of their lives,'' Bearden said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
