<HEADLINE> Bush Discloses At Least $2.1M Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush reported today he  
has no debts and a hefty financial portfolio that includes at least 
$7 million in U.S. Treasury notes and a diversified trust worth at 
least $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The early front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination also  
reported to the Federal Election Commission that he received an 
advance of $106,250 for an unspecified book. He reported he has 
earmarked those proceeds for youth charities. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial disclosure report, required of all presidential  
candidates, shows the son of former President George Bush is a 
millionaire several times over. 
</P>
<P>
	But because the report lists assets and income in only broad  
ranges, it gives a far less complete picture than the income tax 
return Bush made public in April that showed he and his wife had 
$18 million in income and paid $3.7 million in federal taxes in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The report he filed today described income only in ranges that  
fell between $2.1 million and $10.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush reported his largest asset was his investment in U.S.  
Treasury notes, which he valued at between $7.2 million and $14 
million. He reported those notes alone earned him between $351,000 
and $1.2 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	His other large assets included a diversified trust valued at  
between $1 million and $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also disclosed three checking accounts valued at between  
$3,000 and $45,000 as well as a few thousand dollars in stocks in 
high-tech companies like computer chip maker Intel, software giant 
Microsoft and communications company Lucent Technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	He also reported owning two money market accounts with a total  
value between $600,000 and $1.25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush described his largest source of income as capital gains  
from his sale of his interest in the Texas Rangers professional 
baseball team, which he listed at more than $1 million. The actual 
total is $14.9 million. In addition, Bush reported retaining an 
interest in the partnership that owned the team worth between $1 
million and $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his $97,890 governor's salary, Bush also listed:  
</P>
<P>
	--Capital gains income of between $100,000 and $1 million from  
Crescent Real Estate Equities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Capital gains income of $100,000 to $1 million from Advance  
Paradigm. 
</P>
<P>
	--Capital gains income of between $50,000 and $100,000 from GFW  
Energy LP. 
</P>
<P>
	--A book advance of $106,250 that he said was donated directly to  
the Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts and other youth charities. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
