<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Backer Acquitted in Money Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Tennessee developer who has known Vice  
President Al Gore since childhood was acquitted of giving illegal 
donations to Gore and other politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury cleared Franklin L. Haney of 42 charges on  
Thursday in a case prosecutors had called open and shut. ``If you 
looked at the facts in this case, you would convict in five 
minutes,'' prosecutor Pamela Huff said in her closing argument to 
the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	But the jury took about six hours, and at one point declared  
itself deadlocked. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to putting this trial behind us and getting on  
with our lives,'' Haney said in a statement issued at the 
courthouse. He declined interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Haney is the only person acquitted so far in the Justice  
Department's investigation of unorthodox contributions to the 1996 
Clinton-Gore re-election campaign. A dozen people have pleaded 
guilty or have negotiated a deal to cooperate with prosecutors from 
the Justice Department's campaign finance task force, and five 
other cases are pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Haney was accused of using straw donors to mask about $100,000  
of his own political donations to the 1996 race and other 
campaigns, and lying about it in filings to federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Haney's lawyers admitted he gave the money but argued that Haney  
misinterpreted a confusing set of rules on how to raise and record 
political donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors did not comment after the trial, but Justice  
Department spokesman Myron Marlin said the verdict will not affect 
the task force's work. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed, but we respect the verdict,'' Marlin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	During six days of testimony, prosecutors argued Haney tried to  
dodge campaign rules by reimbursing friends, employees and even 
strangers who made political donations at his behest. Paperwork 
sent to the Federal Election Commission listed the individuals, 
because federal campaign finance rules limit individual donations 
to $1,000, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors tried to show the Chattanooga, Tenn., millionaire  
was a sophisticated political veteran who got in over his head when 
he pledged to raise tens of thousands for Clinton-Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic booster for three decades, Haney, 59, was  
accustomed to giving his own money but unprepared to find enough 
legitimate individual donors to fulfill his promise, prosecutors 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense did not present any witnesses. Defense lawyer Ted  
Wells argued to the jury Wednesday that prosecutors did not prove 
Haney knowingly did anything wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Haney believed that it was permissible, and in no way that  
he was violating the law,'' Wells said after the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells called the reimbursements gifts, and said Haney had made  
no attempt to hide the arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	Haney was also at the center of a Justice Department  
investigation last year into whether he paid a $1 million reward to 
1996 Clinton-Gore campaign manager Peter Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight, a former top aide to Gore, got the money shortly before  
he took the campaign job. Congressional Republicans issued a report 
in December questioning whether the money was an illegal 
contingency fee for helping to get the Federal Communications 
Commission to move to a Haney development in Washington called 
Portals. 
</P>
<P>
	Haney and Knight both have said the payment represented legal  
fees for Knight's work on several Haney projects over three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
