<DOCNO> APW19990702.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 09:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small-Cap Value Delights Contrarians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A recent rally by stock mutual funds with a  
small-cap value strategy has brought a taste of sweet vindication 
for fund investors and managers who pride themselves on thinking 
contrarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past several years until this spring, small-cap value  
funds had been suffering from a double whammy. Investors favored 
big stocks over small, and high-flying ``growth'' stocks over 
out-of-favor ``value'' stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Many value managers felt as though they had two strikes against  
them before they even got a turn at bat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Value investing in general has been through a very difficult  
couple of years,'' said Bret Stanley, lead manager of the AIM Basic 
Value Fund, part of the $109 billion fund family run by AIM 
Advisors Inc. in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Just how difficult? In 1998, Morningstar Inc.'s small-value  
average, measuring funds specializing in small stocks with 
relatively low market valuations, dropped 7.19 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morningstar average of small growth funds, by contrast, rose  
5.16 percent, while large-cap value funds gained 12.59 percent and 
large-cap growth funds soared 35.51 percent. From the front to the 
back of this stretched-out field, small-cap value trailed large-cap 
growth by 42.7 percentage points! 
</P>
<P>
	The picture was much the same in the first quarter of this year.  
Then in April it suddenly shifted. In the three months ended May 
31, according to Morningstar, small value funds returned 11.30 
percent, besting small growth, up 9.76 percent; large value, up 
9.07 percent, and large growth, up only 3.10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It will take much more than a few months to reverse a trend that  
has been in force for years. But many analysts argue that a 
turnaround was long overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Something's stirring in the stock market. It could be the  
return of some sanity,'' says veteran fund-watcher Jay Schabacker 
in the current issue of his Mutual Fund Investing newsletter, based 
in Potomac, Md. ``The overpriced large-cap growth stocks are taking 
a well-deserved breather. On the upturn are the previous laggards, 
the small-cap value stocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schabacker sees ``two reasons why the time is ripe for a  
small-cap value resurgence'' -- a huge disparity in relative values, 
and a possible change in the economic climate that might favor 
small value. 
</P>
<P>
	By his reckoning, price-earnings ratios of small value stocks  
recently averaged about 19 to 1, or about half the 38 multiple 
commanded by large growth stocks. In addition, he points to recent 
signs of stronger-than-expected growth in the economy, accompanied 
by stirrings of concern about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This economic mode favors the economically sensitive small-cap  
value industrial stocks and natural-resource stocks,'' Schabacker 
argues. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Kobren, a Wellesley Hills, Mass., adviser on funds, says,  
``I'm pleased that the market has finally broadened out and has 
begun to focus on value stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, investors should be willing to pay more for a company  
growing 20 percent a year (a typical growth stock) than for a 
company growing 12 percent a year (a value stock). But the 
difference just got too great. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second reason, and the likely catalyst for the value rally  
that started in April, was the stronger-than-anticipated economy,'' 
Kobren added in his FundsNet Insight letter. ``Value stocks are 
inherently more sensitive to the economy than growth stocks, and 
the report of improving growth prompted investors to plow money 
into value stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally, the golden economy has trickled down to smaller  
firms. Thanks to the terrific economy, small- and mid-cap firms are 
showing consistent earnings improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What next? Recent experience reinforces the idea that it's very  
hard to guess when investors' favor will shift next among big and 
small, and growth and value stocks. Advocates of small-cap value 
proclaimed buying opportunities for many months before the category 
showed any signs of life -- and by then they had lost a good part of 
their audience. 
</P>
<P>
	So the recent small-cap value revival doesn't tell us much about  
whether it is likely to last, or for how long. It does, however, 
remind everybody concerned that no category of stocks wins the 
performance derby every time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
