<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies Change Medical Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dr. Michael G. Ciccotti took over as the  
Philadelphia Phillies' team doctor Friday, replacing Dr. Phillip 
Marone, who becomes assistant director. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John McShane will serve as an assistant director of the  
medical team. Ciccotti and McShane are both affiliated with the 
Rothman Institute at Jefferson Hospital. Marone heads the Jefferson 
Sports Medicine Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Marone, the team physician for 26 years, told Phillies general  
manager Ed Wade in December this season would be his last. Marone 
will be 69 on Aug. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``Along with my orthopaedic practice, it just became a little  
too much for me,'' Marone said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciccotti is a graduate of the College of Holy Cross and  
Georgetown medical school. Ciccotti has served as an assistant for 
the Los Angeles Lakers, Rams, Kings, Dodgers and Angels among 
others and has been an orthopaedic consultant for the Flyers and 
Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	``This transition has been in the planning stages for several  
years,'' Ciccotti said. ``Dr. Marone has as much experience with a 
major league baseball team as anyone and over the years has shown 
tremendous devotation and loyality. I will try to continue that 
trend.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
