<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tariffs Recommended For Steel Wire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A U.S. trade panel recommended Friday that  
President Clinton impose tariffs on foreign shipments of a type of 
steel used to make fencing and other wire products. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who has grappled to balance the needs of a struggling  
U.S. steel industry with his desire to keep international markets 
open, will have until mid-September to make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the trade complaints were filed under a special section  
of U.S. trade law, the U.S. International Trade Commission's 
recommendations on steel wire rods are not binding. But Friday's 
action forces Clinton to confront the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases were filed by U.S. steel producers and their  
steelworkers' unions to combat low-priced imports, which they blame 
for thousands of layoffs nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports reached record highs last year because of the Asian  
economic crisis, in which lowered demand abroad forced foreign 
producers to send products to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the three voting commissioners recommended 15 percent  
tariffs on wire rod for the first year, with the tariff level going 
down each year to 9 percent in the fourth and final year. They did 
not recommend quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	The third commissioner did not detail her minority  
recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariffs would cover most wire rod imports, although  
shipments from Canada, Mexico and Israel would be among those 
exempted. Also exempted would be certain specialty grades of wire 
rod, including those used to make tire cords and valve springs. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the commission reached a split decision on whether  
foreign steel wire rod is hurting U.S. producers. Three 
commissioners who found injury were the ones who voted Friday on a 
relief recommendation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
