<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retailer Laura Ashley Sells Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- British-based Laura Ashley Holdings has completed  
the sale of its unprofitable chain of 94 North American stores. 
</P>
<P>
	But the retailer of English country fashions and furnishings  
still has to overcome years of losses and management turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Ashley sold its U.S. and Canadian stores to a group of  
investors supported by Malayan United Industries, the Malaysian 
firm that last year injected $70 million into Laura Ashley in 
exchange for a 40 percent stake. Terms of the sale, completed 
Friday, were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Ashley had been successful in the 1970s selling women's  
clothes, bedding and other home furnishings. 
</P>
<P>
	After the sudden death in 1995 of its founder, designer Laura  
Ashley, the company suffered a string of reversals. During the 
1980s it failed to keep up with changing fashions. In 10 years, 
Laura Ashley had seven chief executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Ashley began to expand aggressively into the United States  
in the 1980s and early 1990s. But its stores have struggled for 
years. The company reported an annual pretax loss of $26.7 million 
for the year ending January 1999 -- nearly all of it attributable to 
its U.S. operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new arrangement, Boston-based Laura Ashley (North  
America) Inc. will buy products from the British firm, paying a 
royalty based on a percentage of sales and licensing fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal gives Laura Ashley's North American division an  
infusion of $6 million from investors and a line of credit with a 
bank in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	It also allows the former parent company to write off $34.4  
million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, announced April 28, leaves Laura Ashley with some 300  
stores in Britain and continental Europe and an additional 200 
franchised and licensed stores in other countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
