<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Oil Firm to Restructure Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Creditors of Russia's fifth-biggest oil producer  
have agreed to drop bankruptcy proceedings against the company and 
come up with a restructuring plan, the company said in a statement 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sidanko owes $400 million, $150 million of it to foreign  
creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	The end of bankruptcy proceedings ``is a step on the road (but)  
it's very much a work in progress,'' said Howard Chase, director of 
external relations for BP Amoco, which is owed about 5 percent of 
Sidanko's debt and is also owner of 10 percent of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco has a lot of money riding on the outcome of Sidanko's  
bankruptcy, but the damage to BP Amoco's investment in Sidanko 
could also bode ill for other foreign investors in Russia, Chase 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfgang Rutke of Dresdner Bank, chairman of the Sidanko  
creditors' committee, said creditors representing 96 percent of 
Sidanko's debts have approved the basic principles of a debt 
restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, a previously unknown, Russian-registered company  
called Beta-Ekho launched bankruptcy proceedings against Sidanko, 
suing it for debts of around $20,000 -- a fraction of Sidanko's 
overall debts. 
</P>
<P>
	From the beginning, the bankruptcy process was murky, with no  
disclosure of whom the creditor company represents. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco took control over Sidanko's board in April, teaming up  
with other minority shareholders to take some control over the 
bankruptcy process. 
</P>
<P>
	The same month, Russia's prosecutor general began a criminal  
investigation into the possibility that Sidanko had illegally 
forced itself into bankruptcy. The suggestion was prompted by the 
mystery surrounding Beta-Ekho. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
